{"title_page": "OCBC Centre", "text_new": "{{Infobox building\n| name               = OCBC Centre \n| native_name        = \n| image              = OCBC Centre.JPG\n| image_size         = 250px\n| location           = [[Downtown Core]], [[Singapore]]\n|address = 65 Chulia Street, Singapore 049513\n| coordinates        = {{coord|1.285|103.8491|region:SG-01|display=inline,title}}\n| start_date          = 1975\n| completion_date    = 1976\n| building_type      = Commercial offices\n| antenna_spire      = \n| roof               = {{convert|197.7|m|abbr=on}}\n| floor_count        = 52\n| elevator_count     = \n| cost               = \n| floor_area         = {{convert|74900|sqft|abbr=on}} \n| architectural_style = [[Brutalist architecture]]\n| architect          = [[I. M. Pei]] \u8d1d\u807f\u94ed<br> [[BEP Akitek]]\n| structural_engineer= [[Arup Group Limited|Ove Arup & Partners]]\n| main_contractor    = [[Morrison-Knudsen]]<br> [[Low Keng Huat]]\n| developer          = [[Oversea-Chinese Banking Corporation|OCBC Bank]]\n| owner              = [[Oversea-Chinese Banking Corporation|OCBC Bank]]\n| management         = [[Oversea-Chinese Banking Corporation|OCBC Bank]]\n| references         = <ref>{{Emporis|106520}}</ref><ref>{{SkyscraperPage|6242}}</ref><ref>{{Structurae|20011893}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''OCBC Centre''' is a {{convert|197.7|m|abbr=on}}, 52-[[storey]] skyscraper in [[Singapore]]. serving as the current headquarters of [[Oversea-Chinese Banking Corporation|OCBC Bank]], the building was completed in 1976 and was the tallest building in the country, and [[South East Asia]], at that time.<ref>{{cite web | title = Singapore's evolving skyline | publisher = [[Urban Redevelopment Authority]] | url = http://www.ura.gov.sg/skyline/skyline02/skyline02-04/text/evolvingskyline1.html | accessdate = 2008-02-02 }}</ref> There are two extensions, OCBC Centre South and OCBC Centre East. There is an Executive Club on one of the higher floors of the building. OCBC Centre East has food and beverage outlets.\n\n== History ==\nOCBC Centre was the result of the second Sale of Sites of the Urban Renewal Department of the [[Housing and Development Board]] in 1968. <ref>https://banksinsg.com/banks/ocbc-bank-singapore/</ref> The building was designed by [[I. M. Pei]] & Partners (now [[Pei Cobb Freed & Partners]]) together with now defunct BEP Akitek (Pte) Singapore and started construction in 1975. Its construction period was only two years due to a three-tier system. The building was completed on 1 October 1976 and was [[Southeast Asia]]'s tallest building at the time.<ref>{{cite news |title=The 85-year journey of a Singapore bank |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/opinion/the-85-year-journey-of-a-singapore-bank |accessdate=12 August 2019 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=12 November 2017}}</ref> A [[bronze]] sculpture designed by Tan Teng Kee sat at the building until 1983 when it was moved to the now defunct [[Bras Basah Park]]. ''[[Large Reclining Figure]]'', a large bronze sculpture by [[Henry Moore]], replaced it in 1984, and a new [[plaza]] and [[reflecting pool]] were built outside the front entrance of the building. The building has undergone several modernisations and OCBC Centre East and South was constructed at a later date.\n\n==Architecture==\nThe building is an example of [[Brutalist architecture]], a popular architectural style in the 1970s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://issuu.com/iremembersg/docs/brutalist_architecture|title=Brutarch|publisher=}}</ref> \n\nIt is designed to be a symbol of strength and permanence, and its structure consists of two semi-circular [[reinforced concrete]] cores as well as three [[lateral girder]]s which helped make construction faster. The building is divided into three sections due to the [[steel truss]]es being  constructed off-site and were put into position. Each section consists of floors that are cantilevered 6 metres from each column, with load transfer girders spanning at each end taking up boxed sections of the pre-stressed concrete. [[Lattice steel]] models strengthened by [[steel]] and  [[concrete]] compression was installed on the 20th and 35th floors of the building. The building has been nicknamed the [[calculator]] due to its flat shape and [[window]]s which look like button pads.\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of tallest buildings in Singapore]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book | last = Wong | first = Yunn | title = Singapore 1:1 city : a gallery of architecture & urban design | publisher = Urban Redevelopment Authority Distributor, APD Singapore | location = Singapore | year = 2005 | isbn = 9810544677 }}\n*{{cite book | last = Edwards | first = Norman | title = Singapore : a guide to buildings, streets, places | publisher = Times Books International | location = Singapore Kuala Lumpur | year = 1996 | isbn = 9812047816 }}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline|OCBC Centre}}\n\n{{Singapore skyscrapers|state=expanded}}\n{{I. M. Pei}}\n\n[[Category:1976 establishments in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Brutalist architecture in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Downtown Core (Singapore)]]\n[[Category:I. M. Pei buildings]]\n[[Category:Modernist architecture]]\n[[Category:Office buildings completed in 1976]]\n[[Category:Raffles Place]]\n[[Category:Skyscraper office buildings in Singapore]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox building\n| name               = OCBC Centre \n| native_name        = \n| image              = OCBC Centre.JPG\n| image_size         = 250px\n| location           = [[Downtown Core]], [[Singapore]]\n|address = 65 Chulia Street, Singapore 049513\n| coordinates        = {{coord|1.285|103.8491|region:SG-01|display=inline,title}}\n| start_date          = 1975\n| completion_date    = 1976\n| building_type      = Commercial offices\n| antenna_spire      = \n| roof               = {{convert|197.7|m|abbr=on}}\n| floor_count        = 52\n| elevator_count     = \n| cost               = \n| floor_area         = {{convert|74900|sqft|abbr=on}} \n| architectural_style = [[Brutalist architecture]]\n| architect          = [[I. M. Pei]] \u8d1d\u807f\u94ed<br> [[BEP Akitek]]\n| structural_engineer= [[Arup Group Limited|Ove Arup & Partners]]\n| main_contractor    = [[Morrison-Knudsen]]<br> [[Low Keng Huat]]\n| developer          = [[Oversea-Chinese Banking Corporation|OCBC Bank]]\n| owner              = [[Oversea-Chinese Banking Corporation|OCBC Bank]]\n| management         = [[Oversea-Chinese Banking Corporation|OCBC Bank]]\n| references         = <ref>{{Emporis|106520}}</ref><ref>{{SkyscraperPage|6242}}</ref><ref>{{Structurae|20011893}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''OCBC Centre''' is a {{convert|197.7|m|abbr=on}}, 52-[[storey]] skyscraper in [[Singapore]]. serving as the current headquarters of [[Oversea-Chinese Banking Corporation|OCBC Bank]], the building was completed in 1976 and was the tallest building in the country, and [[South East Asia]], at that time.<ref>{{cite web | title = Singapore's evolving skyline | publisher = [[Urban Redevelopment Authority]] | url = http://www.ura.gov.sg/skyline/skyline02/skyline02-04/text/evolvingskyline1.html | accessdate = 2008-02-02 }}</ref> There are two extensions, OCBC Centre South and OCBC Centre East. There is an Executive Club on one of the higher floors of the building. OCBC Centre East has food and beverage outlets.\n\n== History ==\nOCBC Centre was the result of the second Sale of Sites of the Urban Renewal Department of the [[Housing and Development Board]] in 1968. <ref>https://banksinsg.com/banks/ocbc-bank-singapore/</ref> The building was designed by [[I. M. Pei]] & Partners (now [[Pei Cobb Freed & Partners]]) together with now defunct BEP Akitek (Pte) Singapore and started construction in 1975. Its construction period was only two years due to a three-tier system. The building was completed on 1 October 1976 and was [[Southeast Asia]]'s tallest building at the time.<ref>{{cite news |title=The 85-year journey of a Singapore bank |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/opinion/the-85-year-journey-of-a-singapore-bank |accessdate=12 August 2019 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=12 November 2017}}</ref> A [[bronze]] sculpture designed by Tan Teng Kee sat at the building until 1983 when it was moved to the now defunct [[Bras Basah Park]]. ''[[Large Reclining Figure]]'', a large bronze sculpture by [[Henry Moore]], replaced it in 1984, and a new [[plaza]] and [[reflecting pool]] were built outside the front entrance of the building. The building has undergone several modernisations and OCBC Centre East and South was constructed at a later date.\n\n==Architecture==\nThe building is an example of [[Brutalist architecture]], a popular architectural style in the 1970s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://issuu.com/iremembersg/docs/brutalist_architecture|title=Brutarch|publisher=}}</ref> \n\nIt is designed to be a symbol of strength and permanence, and its structure consists of two semi-circular [[reinforced concrete]] cores as well as three [[lateral girder]]s which helped make construction faster. The building is divided into three sections due to the [[steel truss]]es being  constructed off-site and were put into position. Each section consists of floors that are cantilevered 6 metres from each column, with load transfer girders spanning at each end taking up boxed sections of the pre-stressed concrete. [[Lattice steel]] models strengthened by [[steel]] and  [[concrete]] compression was installed on the 20th and 35th floors of the building. The building has been nicknamed the [[calculator]] due to its flat shape and [[window]]s which look like button pads.\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of tallest buildings in Singapore]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book | last = Wong | first = Yunn | title = Singapore 1:1 city : a gallery of architecture & urban design | publisher = Urban Redevelopment Authority Distributor, APD Singapore | location = Singapore | year = 2005 | isbn = 9810544677 }}\n*{{cite book | last = Edwards | first = Norman | title = Singapore : a guide to buildings, streets, places | publisher = Times Books International | location = Singapore Kuala Lumpur | year = 1996 | isbn = 9812047816 }}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline|OCBC Centre}}\n\n{{Singapore skyscrapers|state=expanded}}\n{{I. M. Pei}}\n\n[[Category:Brutalist architecture in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Downtown Core (Singapore)]]\n[[Category:I. M. Pei buildings]]\n[[Category:Modernist architecture]]\n[[Category:Office buildings completed in 1976]]\n[[Category:Raffles Place]]\n[[Category:Skyscraper office buildings in Singapore]]\n", "name_user": "TheGreatSG'rean", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OCBC_Centre"}
{"title_page": "Jeff Hornacek", "text_new": "{{short description|American basketball player and coach}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Jeff Hornacek\n| image = Coach Jeff Hornacek (cropped).jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Hornacek in March 2013\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 3\n| weight_lb = 190\n| position = \n| team = \n| league = \n| nationality = American\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1963|5|3}}\n| birth_place =[[Elmhurst, Illinois]]\n| highschool = [[Lyons Township High School|Lyons Township]]<br/>([[La Grange, Illinois]])\n| college = [[Iowa State Cyclones men's basketball|Iowa State]] (1982\u20131986)\n| draft_year = 1986\n| draft_round = 2\n| draft_pick = 46\n| draft_team = [[Phoenix Suns]]\n| career_start = 1986\n| career_end = 2000\n| coach_start = 2011\n| coach_end = \n| career_position = [[Shooting guard]]/ [[Point guard]]\n| career_number = 14\n| years1 = {{nbay|1986|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1991|end}}\n| team1 = [[Phoenix Suns]]\n| years2 = {{nbay|1992|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1993|end}}\n| team2 = [[Philadelphia 76ers]]\n| years3 = {{nbay|1993|end}}\u2013{{nbay|1999|end}}\n| team3 = [[Utah Jazz]]\n| cyears1 = {{nbay|2010|end}}\u2013{{nbay|2012|end}}\n| cteam1 = [[Utah Jazz]] (assistant)\n| cyears2 = {{nbay|2013|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2015|end}}\n| cteam2 = [[Phoenix Suns]]\n| cyears3 = {{nbay|2016|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2017|end}}\n| cteam3 = [[New York Knicks]]\n| highlights = \n* [[List of NBA All-Stars|NBA All-Star]] ({{nasg|1992}})\n* 2\u00d7 [[NBA All-Star Weekend Three-Point Shootout|NBA Three-Point Shootout champion]] ({{nasg|1998}}, {{nasg|2000}})\n* No. 14 [[Utah Jazz#Retired numbers|retired by Utah Jazz]]\n* First-team All-[[Big Eight Conference|Big Eight]] (1986)\n* No. 14 [[Iowa State Cyclones men's basketball#Retired Jerseys|retired by Iowa State Cyclones]]\n| stats_league = NBA\n| stat1label = [[Point (basketball)|Points]]\n| stat1value = 15,659 (14.5 ppg)\n| stat2label = [[Rebound (basketball)|Rebounds]]\n| stat2value = 3,646 (3.4 rpg)\n| stat3label = [[Assist (basketball)|Assists]]\n| stat3value = 5,281 (4.9 apg)\n| bbr = hornaje01\n}}\n'''Jeffrey John Hornacek''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|h|\u0254r|n|\u0259|s|\u025b|k}}; born May 3, 1963) is an American professional basketball coach and former player. He was the head coach for both the [[Phoenix Suns]] (2013\u20132016) and the [[New York Knicks]] (2016\u20132018) of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA). He played [[shooting guard]] in the NBA from [[1986\u201387 NBA season|1986]] through [[1999\u20132000 NBA season|2000]].\n\n==Elementary and high school==\nHe attended Komarek Elementary School in [[North Riverside, Illinois]], and Gurrie Middle School and [[Lyons Township High School]] in [[La Grange, Illinois|La Grange]], [[Cook County, Illinois]].\n\n==College==\nHornacek [[Redshirt (college sports)|redshirted]] at [[Iowa State Cyclones men's basketball|Iowa State University]] (ISU) in 1981; he was a team [[wiktionary:walk-on|walk-on]] who played from 1982 to 1986.<ref name=\"NBA bio\">{{cite web|title=Jeff Hornacek bio|url=http://www.nba.com/playerfile/jeff_hornacek/bio.html|publisher=NBA|accessdate=June 21, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628192524/http://www.nba.com/playerfile/jeff_hornacek/bio.html|archivedate=June 28, 2011}}</ref> The son of a high school basketball coach, he became an all-conference player in the [[Big Eight Conference]], playing for coach [[Johnny Orr (basketball, born 1927)|Johnny Orr]]. As a [[point guard]] he guided the [[Iowa State Cyclones|Cyclones]] to the Sweet Sixteen of the [[1986 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|1986]] [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship|tournament]]. His shining moment came at the [[Hubert H. Humphrey Metrodome|Metrodome]] in [[Minneapolis]] when, after first hitting a shot to tie the game and send it to [[overtime (sports)|overtime]], Hornacek hit the game winning shot in overtime, a 26-foot jumper at the buzzer, to give ISU its first NCAA tournament victory since [[1944 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|1944]], beating [[Miami RedHawks|Miami University]], March 14, 1986, 81\u201379. Two days later, he led the Cyclones to the NCAA Tournament Sweet Sixteen, in a 72\u201369 upset of second seed [[Michigan Wolverines|Michigan]]. Orr, who had previously left Michigan to coach at Iowa State, called it the greatest victory of his career. Hornacek left ISU with a Big-8 record of 665 career assists and 1,313 career points. He was the fourth player in Cyclone basketball history to have his number retired when his No. 14 jersey was hung from the rafters of [[Hilton Coliseum]] in 1991.\n\n==NBA career==\n\n===Phoenix Suns===\n[[File:Jeff Hornacek - Phoenix Suns.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Hornacek in 1987]]\nHe was the 22nd pick in the second round (46th overall) of the [[1986 NBA draft]], by the [[Phoenix Suns]]. The 2nd round draft pick that was used to select him was traded three times before finally ending up with the Suns.  First, the [[Los Angeles Lakers]] packaged it in the deal to acquire [[Byron Scott (basketball)|Byron Scott]] from the [[San Diego Clippers]] before the 1983\u201384 season.  A week later, the Clippers sent the pick to the [[Detroit Pistons]] in a deal to acquire [[Ricky Pierce]], and on that same day, the Pistons dealt the pick to the Suns for [[David Thirdkill]].\n\nThe Suns struggled in Hornacek's first two seasons, but after hiring [[Cotton Fitzsimmons]] as coach and acquiring free agent [[Tom Chambers (basketball)|Tom Chambers]], the Suns went from 28 wins in 1987\u201388 to 55 in 1988\u201389.  Hornacek was a \"third option\" on offense after Chambers and [[Kevin Johnson (basketball)|Kevin Johnson]].  This trio led the Suns to four straight NBA playoff appearances, including two Western Conference Finals.\n\n===Philadelphia 76ers===\nAfter his sixth and most productive season in [[1991\u201392 NBA season|1991\u201392]], in which he led the Suns in scoring average (20.1 ppg) and earned an [[All-Star]] appearance, Hornacek was traded (along with [[Andrew Lang (basketball)|Andrew Lang]] and [[Tim Perry]]) to the [[Philadelphia 76ers]] for [[Charles Barkley]]. With [[Hersey Hawkins]], the Sixers' leading scorer, in the shooting guard position, Hornacek was assigned point guard responsibilities.  Although he had a career high 6.9 assists per game in his only complete season with the Sixers ([[1992\u201393 NBA season|1992\u201393 season]]), his stint as a point guard was not a success (26 wins, 56 losses). Midway through the [[1993\u201394 NBA season|1993\u201394 season]] (February 24) he was traded to the [[Utah Jazz]] (for [[Jeff Malone]]) where he could return to his natural shooting guard position alongside [[John Stockton]].\n\n===Utah Jazz===\nLike in Phoenix, Hornacek was a complementary \"third option\" to [[Karl Malone]] and Stockton. Hornacek was also one of the best on offense in the NBA in moving without the ball, something essential for a shooting guard. He was an instrumental part of the Jazz's drive to the NBA Finals in [[1997 NBA Finals|1997]] and [[1998 NBA Finals|1998]], where the Jazz lost to the [[Chicago Bulls]] both times.  He remained with the Jazz until knee problems forced his retirement in 2000.  It was revealed that he has no left meniscus due to wear and tear on his body, so bad that he could have needed [[knee reconstruction]] because it also is arthritic.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/813381/Jeff-Hornacek-Battle-on-Wounded-Knee.html?pg=all|title=Jeff Hornacek: Battle on Wounded Knee|date=April 21, 2000|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn November 23, 1994, he set a then-NBA record with eight consecutive three-pointers in a single game against the [[Seattle SuperSonics]]. That same season, he also tied an NBA record 11 consecutive three-pointers, from December 30, 1994 through January 11, 1995. One of the best [[free throw]] shooters in the league, once making 67 in a row (November 12, 1999 \u2013 January 6, 2000), one of his most well-known mannerisms was stroking the side of his face three times before every free-throw attempt. That was his way of saying hello to his three children, Tyler, Ryan and Abigaile, during the game.<ref name=CNN-2000-04-25>[http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/turnersports/nba/news/2000/04/25/turnersports_hornacek/ \"Changing teams: Hornacek will trade NBA for family\"]. \u2013 CNN/Sports Illustrated. \u2013 (CNNSI.com). \u2013 Wednesday, April 26, 2000.</ref> He holds a career free throw percentage of 87.7, 16th highest in NBA history.<ref name=BR-CFTP>[https://www.basketball-reference.com/leaders/FTP_career.html \"Career Leaders and Records for Free Throw %\"]. \u2013 Basketball-Reference. \u2013 Retrieved on August 23, 2007</ref>\n\nHornacek won the NBA three-point competition twice, and along with [[Natalie Williams]], star of the [[San Antonio Silver Stars|Utah Starzz]], won the All-Star 2-Ball Challenge.\n\nAfter the 1999\u20132000 season, Hornacek retired from basketball to spend more time with his family.<ref>{{cite news|last=Robinson|first=Doug|title=Gone, but never forgotten: Jeff Hornacek opens new chapter as full-time husband, dad|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/print/760557/Gone-but-never-forgotten-Jeff-Hornacek-opens-new-chapter-as-full-time-husband-dad.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120724061631/http://www.deseretnews.com/article/print/760557/Gone-but-never-forgotten-Jeff-Hornacek-opens-new-chapter-as-full-time-husband-dad.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 24, 2012|accessdate=June 21, 2011|newspaper=Deseret News|date=May 18, 2000}}</ref> Hornacek's No.&nbsp;14 jersey was retired by the [[Utah Jazz]], for whom he played from 1994 to 2000, and helped get them to the [[NBA Finals]] in 1997 and 1998. Coach [[Jerry Sloan]] and Jazz announcer [[Rod Hundley|\"Hot Rod\" Hundley]] referred to Hornacek affectionately as \"Horny\".<ref name=NBA-26744-68>[http://www.nba.com/suns/history/Jeff_Hornacek-26744-68.html Jeff Hornacek] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516162832/http://www.nba.com/suns/history/Jeff_Hornacek-26744-68.html |date=May 16, 2008 }}. \u2013 NBA.</ref> All in all, Hornacek enjoyed a 14-year NBA playing career including 1,077 career games played.\n\n==NBA career statistics==\n{{NBA player statistics legend}}\n\n===Regular season===\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{Nbay|1986}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1986\u201387 Phoenix Suns season|Phoenix]]\n| 80 || 3 || 19.5 || .454 || .279 || .777 || 2.3 || 4.5 || .9 || .1 || 5.3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{Nbay|1987}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1987\u201388 Phoenix Suns season|Phoenix]]\n| '''82''' || 49 || 27.4 || .506 || .293 || .822 || 3.2 || 6.6 || 1.3 || .1 || 9.5\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{Nbay|1988}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1988\u201389 Phoenix Suns season|Phoenix]]\n| 78 || 73 || 31.9 || .495 || .333 || .826 || 3.4 || 6.0 || 1.7 || .1 || 13.5\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{Nbay|1989}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1989\u201390 Phoenix Suns season|Phoenix]]\n| 67 || 60 || 34.0 || '''.536''' || .408 || .856 || 4.7 || 5.0 || 1.7 || .2 || 17.6\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{Nbay|1990}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1990\u201391 Phoenix Suns season|Phoenix]]\n| 80 || 77 || 34.2 || .518 || .418 || .897 || 4.0 || 5.1 || 1.4 || .2 || 16.9\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{Nbay|1991}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1991\u201392 Phoenix Suns season|Phoenix]]\n| 81 || 81 || '''38.0''' || .512 || .439 || .886 || '''5.0''' || 5.1 || '''2.0''' || '''.4''' || '''20.1'''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{Nbay|1992}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1992\u201393 Philadelphia 76ers season|Philadelphia]]\n| 79 || 78 || 36.2 || .470 || .390 || .865 || 4.3 || '''6.9''' || 1.7 || .3 || 19.1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{Nbay|19