{"title_page": "The Dramatic Imagination", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n'''''The Dramatic Imagination''''' is a book written in 1941 by American [[scenic designer]] [[Robert Edmond Jones]].\n\nIt is considered the basic blueprint from which all innovations of modern [[stage design]] have been crafted.<ref>Waecker, Emily. [http://web.ics.purdue.edu/~fliotsos/b/b/Jones,_R.E..html \"Robert Edmond Jones: Founder of Modern American Stage Design\"]. [[Purdue University]]. Retrieved on April 16, 2016.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dramatic Imagination, The}}\n[[Category:Non-fiction books about theatre]]\n[[Category:1941 non-fiction books]]\n{{theat-book-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n'''''The Dramatic Imagination''''' is a book written in 1941 by American [[scenic designer]] [[Robert Edmond Jones]].\n\nIt is considered the basic blueprint from which all innovations of modern [[stage design]] have been crafted.<ref>Waecker, Emily. [http://web.ics.purdue.edu/~fliotsos/b/b/Jones,_R.E..html \"Robert Edmond Jones: Founder of Modern American Stage Design\"]. [[Purdue University]]. Retrieved on April 16, 2016.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dramatic Imagination, The}}\n[[Category:Non-fiction books about theatre]]\n[[Category:1941 books]]\n\n\n{{theat-book-stub}}\n", "name_user": "I grieve in stereo", "label": "safe", "comment": "Moving fromCategory:1941 bookstoCategory:1941 non-fiction booksusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Dramatic_Imagination"}
{"title_page": "Betrayal of the Left", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n'''''Betrayal of the Left''''' (full title: '''''Betrayal of the Left: an Examination & Refutation of Communist Policy from October 1939 to January 1941: with Suggestions for an Alternative and an Epilogue on Political Morality''''') was a book of essays published on 3 March 1941 by the [[Left Book Club]], edited and largely written by [[Victor Gollancz]]. The book\nhad a preface by [[Harold Laski]].<ref>[[Angus Calder]],''The people's war: Britain, 1939-1945''.\nPanther Books, 1969  (p. 733).</ref>\n\nOther contributions included two essays by [[George Orwell]], \"Fascism and Democracy\" and \"Patriots and Revolutionaries\"<ref name=\"IHR\">http://www.history.ac.uk/reviews/paper/perryMat.html Institute of Historical Research. Matt Perry. University of Sunderland</ref>  that condemned the [[Communist Party of Great Britain]] for backing the [[Molotov\u2013Ribbentrop Pact]] of 1939 and for taking a [[revolutionary defeatist]] position in the war against [[Nazi Germany]]. ''Betrayal of the Left'' also\ncontained an essay by [[John Strachey (politician)|John Strachey]] attacking [[totalitarianism]].<ref>Michael Newman,\n''John Strachey'', Manchester University Press, 1989 {{ISBN|071902174X}} (p.83).</ref>\n\nIt was particularly critical of the Communist Party-organised [[People's Convention]] of January 1941, the high point of the party's revolutionary defeatism during the period of Stalin's alliance with Hitler. It marked a decisive break by the democratic left from its 1930s alliance with the Communist Party.\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Bibliography of George Orwell]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Crimethink}}\n\n[[Category:1941 non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Essays by George Orwell]]\n[[Category:1941 essays]]\n[[Category:Essay anthologies]]\n\n\n{{poli-book-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n'''''Betrayal of the Left''''' (full title: '''''Betrayal of the Left: an Examination & Refutation of Communist Policy from October 1939 to January 1941: with Suggestions for an Alternative and an Epilogue on Political Morality''''') was a book of essays published on 3 March 1941 by the [[Left Book Club]], edited and largely written by [[Victor Gollancz]]. The book\nhad a preface by [[Harold Laski]].<ref>[[Angus Calder]],''The people's war: Britain, 1939-1945''.\nPanther Books, 1969  (p. 733).</ref>\n\nOther contributions included two essays by [[George Orwell]], \"Fascism and Democracy\" and \"Patriots and Revolutionaries\"<ref name=\"IHR\">http://www.history.ac.uk/reviews/paper/perryMat.html Institute of Historical Research. Matt Perry. University of Sunderland</ref>  that condemned the [[Communist Party of Great Britain]] for backing the [[Molotov\u2013Ribbentrop Pact]] of 1939 and for taking a [[revolutionary defeatist]] position in the war against [[Nazi Germany]]. ''Betrayal of the Left'' also\ncontained an essay by [[John Strachey (politician)|John Strachey]] attacking [[totalitarianism]].<ref>Michael Newman,\n''John Strachey'', Manchester University Press, 1989 {{ISBN|071902174X}} (p.83).</ref>\n\nIt was particularly critical of the Communist Party-organised [[People's Convention]] of January 1941, the high point of the party's revolutionary defeatism during the period of Stalin's alliance with Hitler. It marked a decisive break by the democratic left from its 1930s alliance with the Communist Party.\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Bibliography of George Orwell]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Crimethink}}\n\n[[Category:1941 books]]\n[[Category:Essays by George Orwell]]\n[[Category:1941 essays]]\n[[Category:Essay anthologies]]\n\n\n{{poli-book-stub}}\n", "name_user": "I grieve in stereo", "label": "safe", "comment": "Moving fromCategory:1941 bookstoCategory:1941 non-fiction booksusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Betrayal_of_the_Left"}
{"title_page": "Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership", "text_new": "{{About|the regulation and trade agreement|the chemical compound abbreviated as TTIP|Titanium isopropoxide}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox treaty\n| name = Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership\n| long_name =\n| image =[[File:European Union United States Locator.svg|frameless|upright=1.15]]\n| caption = The [[United States]] (orange) and the [[European Union]] (green)\n| type = [[Trade agreement]]\n| date_drafted =  \n| date_signed = No\n| location_signed = \n| date_sealed =\n| date_effective = \n| condition_effective = \n| date_expiration =\n| original_signatories=\n| parties = \n| ratifiers =\n| depositor =\n| languages = \n| wikisource =\n}}\n\nThe '''Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership''' ('''TTIP''') is a proposed [[trade agreement]] between the [[European Union]] and the [[United States]], with the aim of promoting trade and multilateral economic growth. According to [[Karel de Gucht]], European Commissioner for Trade between 2010 and 2014, the TTIP is the largest bilateral trade initiative ever negotiated, not only because it involves the two largest economies in the world but also \"because of its potential global reach in setting an example for future partners and agreements\".<ref>Karel de Gucht, ''Foreword'' in Jean-Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Morin, Tereza Novotn\u00e1, Frederik Ponjaert and Mario Tel\u00f2, ''The Politics of Transatlantic Trade Negotiations, TTIP in a Globalized World'', Routledge, 2015, p.xvii</ref>\n\nNegotiations were halted by President Donald Trump,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/26/world/europe/donald-trump-us-eu-trade.html|title=Europe Averts a Trade War With Trump. But Can It Trust Him?|publisher=|accessdate=28 July 2018}}</ref> who then initiated a trade conflict with the EU. Trump and the EU declared a truce of sorts in July 2018, resuming talks that appeared similar to TTIP.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/26/us/politics/trump-trade-european-union.html|title=Trump's Trade Truce With Europe Has a Familiar Feel: It Mirrors Obama's Path|publisher=|accessdate=28 July 2018}}</ref> On 15 April 2019, the negotiations have been declared \"obsolete and no longer relevant\" by the European Commission.<ref>{{cite web |last1=European Commission |title=Negotiations and Agreements: Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership |url=https://ec.europa.eu/trade/policy/in-focus/ttip/index_en.htm}}</ref>\n\nThe reports on the ongoing negotiations and the contents of the negotiated TTIP proposals are [[classified information|classified]] from the public, and can be accessed only by authorised persons.<ref name=\"Independent 14 August 2015\"/> Multiple [[News leak|leaks]] of proposed TTIP contents into the public caused controversy.<ref>Arthur Neslen. [https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/may/01/leaked-ttip-documents-cast-doubt-on-eu-us-trade-deal Leaked TTIP documents cast doubt on EU-US trade deal]. [[theguardian.com]]. 1 May 2016.</ref>\n\nThe [[European Commission]] says that the TTIP would boost the EU's economy by \u20ac120&nbsp;billion, the US economy by \u20ac90&nbsp;billion and the rest of the world by \u20ac100&nbsp;billion.<ref name=\"EU-ttip\"/> According to Anu Bradford, law professor at [[Columbia Law School]], and Thomas J. Bollyky of the [[Council on Foreign Relations]], TTIP aims to \"liberalise one-third of global trade\" and could create millions of new jobs.<ref name=\"Bollyky Foreign Affairs\"/> A ''[[The Guardian|Guardian]]'' article by [[Dean Baker]] of the US thinktank [[Center for Economic and Policy Research]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rosenberg|first1=Tina|title=The Perils of Petrocracy|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/04/magazine/04oil-t.html?pagewanted=7|accessdate=5 October 2014|work=[[New York Times]]|date=4 November 2007|quote= \u2026 Mark Weisbrot, co-director of the Center for Economic and Policy Research, a left-leaning Washington policy group.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Sussman|first1=Anna Louie|title=Are Women the New Face of Organized Labor?|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/economics/2015/09/07/are-women-the-new-face-of-organized-labor/|accessdate=20 September 2015|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=7 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Fox|first1=Maggie|title=Obamacare won't slash workers' hours, report finds|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-care/obamacare-wont-slash-workers-hours-report-finds-f6C10732487|accessdate=31 October 2014|agency=NBC News|date=24 July 2013}}</ref> argued that the economic benefits per household would be relatively small.<ref name=\"guardian July 15, 2013\"/> According to a [[European Parliament]] report, impacts on labour conditions range from job gains to job losses, depending on economic model and assumptions used for predictions.<ref name=\"EP Kraatz\">Susanne Kraatz. [http://www.europarl.europa.eu/RegData/etudes/BRIE/2014/536315/IPOL_BRI(2014)536315_EN.pdf The Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP) and Labour]. [[European Parliament]].</ref>\n\nThe agreement has been criticized and opposed by some [[Trade union|unions]], charities, [[Non-governmental organization|NGOs]] and environmentalists, particularly in Europe.<ref name=\"guardian August 3, 2015\">Stuart Jeffries. [https://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/aug/03/ttip-what-why-angry-transatlantic-trade-investment-partnership-guide What is TTIP and why should we be angry about it?]. [[theguardian.com]]. Published on 3 August 2015.</ref><ref name=\"The Daily Beast\"/> ''[[The Independent]]'' describes common criticisms of TTIP as \"reducing the regulatory barriers to trade for [[big business]], things like [[food safety]] law, [[Environmental law|environmental legislation]], [[Bank regulation|banking regulations]] and the sovereign powers of individual nations\",<ref name=\"The Independent October 6, 2015\"/> or more critically as an \"assault on European and US societies by transnational corporations\".<ref name=\"The Independent October 6, 2015\"/> ''[[The Guardian]]'' noted the criticism of TTIP's \"undemocratic nature of the closed-door talks\", \"influence of powerful lobbyists\", TTIP's potential ability to \"undermine the democratic authority of local government\",<ref name=\"guardian August 5, 2015\">Tim Smedley. [https://www.theguardian.com/public-leaders-network/2015/aug/05/ttip-free-trade-deal-renewable-energy-transatlantic-partnership-eu-us TTIP: what does the transatlantic trade deal mean for renewable energy?]. [[theguardian.com]]. 5 August 2015.</ref> and described it as \"the most controversial trade deal the EU has ever negotiated\".<ref name=\"theguardian.com 27 August 2016\"/> German economist [[Max Otte]] argued that by putting European workers into direct competition with Americans (and in effect, because of the [[North American Free Trade Agreement]], with Mexicans and Canadians), TTIP would negatively impact the [[European social model]]s.<ref name=\"heute April 8, 2016\"/> An EU [[direct democracy]] mechanism, the [[European Citizens' Initiative]], which enables EU citizens to call directly on the [[European Commission]] to propose a legal act,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/citizens-initiative/public/welcome|title=Homepage \u2013 European Citizens' Initiative \u2013 European Commission|publisher=}}</ref> acquired over 3.2&nbsp;million signatures against TTIP and [[Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement|CETA]] within a year.<ref name=\"guard 3 Aug 2015\" /><ref name=\"Stop TTIP\"/>\n\n==Background==\nEconomic barriers between the EU and the United States are relatively low, not only due to long-standing membership in the [[World Trade Organization]] (WTO) but also recent agreements such as the [[EU\u2013US Open Skies Agreement]] and work by the [[Transatlantic Economic Council]]. The [[European Commission]] claims that passage of a trans-Atlantic trade pact could boost overall trade between the respective blocs by as much as 50%.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/europe/21565973-after-barack-obamas-re-election-it-time-push-transatlantic-free-trade-hope-and-no|accessdate=18 March 2013|title=Hope and no change, After Barack Obama's re-election, it is time to push for transatlantic free trade|publisher=Economist.com|date=10 November 2012}}</ref> Economic gains from a Trade Treaty were predicted in the joint report issued by the [[White House]] and the [[European Commission]].<ref>{{cite web|work=European Commission|accessdate=18 March 2013|url=http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/docs/2013/february/tradoc_150519.pdf|title=Final Report High Level Working Group on Jobs and Growth}}</ref>\n\nSome form of [[Transatlantic Free Trade Area]] had been proposed in the 1990s and later in 2006 by [[Chancellor of Germany (1949\u2013)|German Chancellor]] [[Angela Merkel]] in reaction to the collapse of the [[Doha Development Round|Doha]] world trade talks. However, [[protectionism]] on both sides may be a barrier to any future agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/0,1518,440335,00.html |title=Trans-Atlantic Free Trade?: Merkel for EU Agreement with US \u2013 SPIEGEL ONLINE |publisher=Spiegel.de |date=2 October 2006 |accessdate=2014-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ecipe.org/blog/a-transatlantic-free-trade-area|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100116094133/http://www.ecipe.org/blog/a-transatlantic-free-trade-area|title=A Transatlantic Free Trade Area?|archivedate=16 January 2010|work=ecipe.org}}</ref> It was first initiated in 1990, when, shortly after the end of the [[Cold War]], with the world no longer divided into two blocs, the [[European Community]] (12 countries) and the US signed a \"Transatlantic Declaration\". This called for the continued existence of the [[North Atlantic Treaty Organization]], as well as for yearly summits, biannual meetings between ministers of State, and more frequent encounters between political figures and senior officials.\n\nSubsequent initiatives taken by the European deciders and the US government included: in 1995, the creation of a pressure group of business people, the [[Transatlantic Business Dialogue]] (TABD) by public authorities on both sides of the Atlantic; in 1998, the creation of an advisory committee, the Transatlantic Economic Partnership; in 2007, the creation of the [[Transatlantic Economic Council]], in which representatives from firms operating on both sides of the Atlantic meet to advise the European Commission and the US government \u2013 and finally, in 2011, the creation of a group of high-level experts whose conclusions, submitted on 11 February 2013, recommended the launching of negotiations for a wide-ranging free-trade agreement. On 12 February 2013, President [[Barack Obama]] called in his annual [[State of the Union]] address for such an agreement.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/02/14/business/global/obama-pledges-trade-pact-talks-with-eu.html|title=A Running Start for a U.S.-Europe Trade Pact|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=2014-02-21|first1=James|last1=Kanter|first2=Jack|last2=Ewing|date=13 February 2013}}</ref> The following day, [[EU Commission]] [[European Commission President|President]] [[Jose Manuel Barroso]] announced that talks would take place to negotiate the agreement.<ref>{{cite news|author=Andrew Walker |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-21439945 |title=BBC News \u2013 EU and US free-trade talks launched |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=13 February 2013 |accessdate=2014-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Blenkinsop |first=Philip |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/02/13/us-eu-us-trade-idUSBRE91C0OC20130213 |title=EU, U.S. to start free trade talks |publisher=Reuters |date= 13 February 2013|accessdate=2014-02-21}}</ref>\n\nThe United States and European Union together represent 60% of global GDP, 33% of world trade in goods and 42% of world trade in services. There are a number of trade conflicts between the two powers, but both depend on the other's economic market and disputes only affect 2% of total trade. A free trade area between the two would represent potentially the largest regional free-trade agreement in history, covering 46% of [[world GDP]].<ref name=\"imfgdp-world-eu\">{{cite web |url=http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/weo/2013/02/weodata/weorept.aspx?pr.x=33&pr.y=11&sy=2012&ey=2012&scsm=1&ssd=1&sort=country&ds=.&br=1&c=001%2C998&s=NGDPD&grp=1&a=1 |title=Nominal 2012 GDP for the world and the European Union (EU). |accessdate=2013-10-08 |work=World Economic Outlook Database | date=October 2013 |publisher=[[International Monetary Fund]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/trade/creating-opportunities/bilateral-relations/countries/united-states/ |title=European Commission |publisher=Ec.europa.eu |date= |accessdate=25 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Trade between the EU and the US<br>(in billion euros){{Citation needed|date=May 2015}}{{When|date=May 2015}}\n|-\n! Direction\n! Goods\n! Services\n! Investment\n! Total\n|-\n! EU to US\n| 288\n| 159\n| 1655\n| 2102\n|-\n! US to EU\n| 196\n| 146\n| 1536\n| 1878\n|}\n\nThe United States investment in the European Union is three times greater than US investment in the entire continent of Asia and EU investment in the United States is eight times that of European Union investment in India and China combined. Intra-company transfers are estimated to constitute a third of all transatlantic trade. The United States and European Union are the largest trading partners of most other countries in the world and account for a third of world trade flows. Given the already low tariff barriers (under 3%), to make the deal a success the aim is to remove [[Non-tariff barriers to trade|non-tariff barriers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/trade/policy/countries-and-regions/countries/united-states/ |title=United States \u2013 Trade \u2013 European Commission |publisher=Ec.europa.eu |date= |accessdate=2014-02-21}}</ref>\n\n==Proposed contents==\nDocuments released by the European Commission in July 2014 group the topics under discussion into three broad areas: Market access; Specific regulation; and broader rules and principles and modes of co-operation.<ref name=\"eu state of play\">[http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/html/152666.htm State of Play of TTIP negotiations ahead of the 6th round of negotiations], European Commission DG Trade, 11 July 2014</ref><ref name=\"negotiators\">[http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/html/151668.htm List of lead negotiators for the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership], European Commission DG Trade<p>[http://www.ustr.gov/sites/default/files/lead%20negotiators%20list%20TTIP.pdf List of lead negotiators for the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership], Office of the United States Trade Representative</ref>\n\nThe EU negotiating mandate as of June 2013 gave a fuller view of what the [[Council of the European Union]] ([[Foreign Affairs Council|Foreign Affairs]]) has told its negotiators to try to achieve for each section.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eu-secretdeals.info/upload/TTIP-mandate_M-Schaake_website.pdf|title=Secret Global Affairs \u2013 Search Enabled Priority|website=eu-secretdeals.info|accessdate=28 July 2018}}</ref> No corresponding US text is available, but the American side has released a public statement setting out its objectives and the potential benefits it foresees.<ref>[http://www.ustr.gov/about-us/press-office/press-releases/2014/March/US-Objectives-US-Benefits-In-the-TTIP-a-Detailed-View U.S. Objectives, U.S. Benefits In the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership: A Detailed View] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140719050519/http://www.ustr.gov/about-us/press-office/press-releases/2014/March/US-Objectives-US-Benefits-In-the-TTIP-a-Detailed-View |date=19 July 2014 }}, Office of the [[United States Trade Representative]], March 2014</ref>\n\nThe secret contents of the first concrete American proposal on tariff reduction, and an EU counterproposal, which was leaked to [[Correctiv]] in February 2016, suggest 87.5% to 97% of all tariffs would be cut to zero.<ref>{{cite web|title = TTIP: EU offered 97% cut on US tariffs, secret papers show|url = https://euobserver.com/economic/132376|website = EUobserver|access-date = 23 February 2016|date = 22 February 2016|last = von Daniels|first = Justus|last2 = Orosz|first2 = Marta}}</ref>\n\n=== Market access ===\n{{see also|Non-tariff barriers to trade}}\nTTIP includes chapters on market access for goods and services that aim to remove \"custom duties on goods and restrictions on services, gaining better access to public markets, and making it easier to invest\".<ref name=\"TTIP explained\">[http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/html/152462.htm The Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP) explained], European Commission DG Trade, 8 May 2014</ref> The goods part includes rules on [[market access]] for goods, agriculture and processed agricultural products, and [[rules of origin]].<ref name=\"eu state of play\" /><ref name=\"negotiators\" />\n\n====Services and leaked text====\n{{See also|Public services|Bank regulation|Regulatory taking|Investor-state dispute settlement}}\n\nFor \"Trade in Services, Investment and E-commerce\", a draft text dated 7 July 2013 was leaked by the German newspaper, ''[[Die Zeit]]'' in March 2014. The leaked text contains seven chapters. In Chapter 1, Article 1 states the overall objective of \"a better climate for the development of trade and investment\", particularly the \"[[liberalisation]] of investment and cooperation on e-commerce\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://keionline.org/sites/default/files/eu-kommission-position-in-den.pdf|title=TTIP Draft (02/07/2013) article 1|publisher=Keionline.org|accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref>\n\nChapter II, Article 3 to Article 18 contains general principles for investment. Article 14 contains proposed rules that forbid governments to \"directly or indirectly [[nationalise]], [[expropriate]]\" unless it is for a public purpose, under due process of law, on a non-discriminatory basis, with compensation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://keionline.org/sites/default/files/eu-kommission-position-in-den.pdf|title=TTIP Draft (02/07/2013) article 14(1)|publisher=Keionline.org|accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref> Article 14(2) defines the necessary compensation as being \"fair market value of the investment at the time immediately before the expropriation or the impending expropriation became public knowledge plus [[compound interest|interest at a commercial rate]] established on a market basis\".\n\nChapter III, Articles 19 to 23 contains rules on cross border supply of services.\n\nChapter IV, Articles 24 to 28 would allow free movement of business managers, and other employees of a corporation, for temporary work purposes among all countries party to the agreement.<ref name=\"TTIP Draft, articles 24-28\">{{cite web|url=http://keionline.org/sites/default/files/eu-kommission-position-in-den.pdf |title=TTIP Draft, articles 24\u201328|publisher=Keionline.org|accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref> Article 1(2) makes it clear, however, that no more general free movement of workers and citizens is allowed.\n\nChapter V contains eight sections with particular rules for different economic sectors. Section I, articles 29 to 31, set out principles that states must follow in licensing private corporations, and state that requirements that are not proportionate to a reviewable public policy objective are contrary to the treaty. Section II contains general provisions. Section III covers computer services. Section IV, articles 35 to 39, cover liberalisation of [[postal service]]s.<ref name=\"TTIP Draft, articles 35-39\">{{cite web|url=http://keionline.org/sites/default/files/eu-kommission-position-in-den.pdf|title=TTIP Draft, articles 35\u201339|publisher=Keionline.org|accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref> Section V, articles 40 to 50, apply to electronic communications networks and services (including telecommunications) and mandate competitive markets, absence of cross-subsidies, subject to defined exceptions including in article 46 a right (but not a requirement) for countries to provide [[universal service]].\n\nSection VI of chapter V covers Financial Services, in articles 51 to 59. It limits the laws that governments can pass to regulate or publicly run insurance and banking. Any regulations that do not fall within the Treaty's terms and objectives would be unlawful.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://keionline.org/sites/default/files/eu-kommission-position-in-den.pdf|title=TTIP Draft (02/07/2013) articles 51\u201359|publisher=Keionline.org|accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref> Legitimate reasons for regulation include, in article 52, \"the protection of investors, depositors, policy-holders or persons to whom a [[fiduciary duty]] is owed by a financial service supplier; (b) ensuring the integrity and stability of a Party's financial system\". However article 52(2) states \"measures shall not be more burdensome than necessary to achieve their aim\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://keionline.org/sites/default/files/eu-kommission-position-in-den.pdf|title=TTIP Draft (02/07/2013) art 52(2)|publisher=Keionline.org|accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref> and the Treaty does not include any further reasons to allow regulation. Section VII covers international maritime transport and section VIII covers air transport.\n\nThe Annex on \"[[Investor-state dispute settlement|Investors-state dispute settlement]]\" proposed to allow corporations to bring actions against governments for breach of its rights.<ref name=\"keionline.org\">{{cite web|url=http://keionline.org/sites/default/files/eu-kommission-position-in-den.pdf|title=TTIP Draft, \"Negotiations on Investor-State Dispute Settlement\"|publisher=Keionline.org|accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref> The European Commission launched a public consultation after the draft text was leaked, which led to a number of changes. However, an updated proposed text had yet to be made publicly available.{{when|date=July 2015}} In September 2015, the Commission proposed an \"Investment Court System\" to replace the ISDS clauses, with the scope for investor challenge much reduced and with \"highly skilled judges\" rather than arbitrators used to determine cases.<ref>{{cite web|title = Commission proposes new Investment Court System for TTIP and other EU trade and investment negotiations | url = http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-15-5651_en.htm | work = The European Commission| date = 16 September 2015 | accessdate = 25 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Industry-specific regulation===\n\"Improved regulatory coherence and cooperation by dismantling unnecessary regulatory barriers such as bureaucratic duplication of effort\".<ref name=\"TTIP explained\" />\n\nSpecific heads for discussion include:<ref name=\"eu state of play\" /><ref name=\"negotiators\" />\n* Horizontal chapters:\n** Regulatory coherence<ref>{{cite web|url=http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/html/151622.htm |title=TTIP Initial EU position paper \u2013 Cross-cutting |publisher=Trade.ec.europa.eu |date= |accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref><ref>[http://corporateeurope.org/sites/default/files/ttip-regulatory-coherence-2-12-2013.pdf Subsequent more detailed EU position paper], leaked December 2013</ref>\n** [[Technical barriers to trade]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/html/151627.htm |title=TTIP position paper on technical barriers |publisher=Trade.ec.europa.eu |date= |accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref>\n* Specific sectoral agreements:\n** [[Textile industry|Textiles]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/html/152469.htm |title=EU TTIP position on textiles |publisher=Trade.ec.europa.eu |date= |accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref>\n** [[Chemical industry|Chemicals]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/html/152468.htm |title=EU TTIP position \u2013 chemicals, May 14 |publisher=Trade.ec.europa.eu |date= |accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref>\n** [[Pharmaceutical industry|Pharmaceuticals]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/html/152471.htm |title=EU TTIP position on pharma \u2013 TTIP |publisher=Trade.ec.europa.eu |date= |accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref>\n** Cosmetics<ref>{{cite web|url=http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/html/152470.htm |title=EU TTIP initial position on cosmetics |publisher=Trade.ec.europa.eu |date= |accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref>\n** [[Medical device]]s\n** [[Automotive industry|Cars]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/html/152467.htm |title=EU TTIP position on vehicles |publisher=Trade.ec.europa.eu |date= |accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref>\n** Electronics and information technology\n** Machinery and engineering\n** [[Pesticides]]\n** [[Sanitary and phytosanitary measures and agreements|Sanitary and phytosanitary measures]] (SPS)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/html/151625.htm |title=TTIP position initiale \u2013 mesures sanitaires et phytosanitaires |publisher=Trade.ec.europa.eu |date= |accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref>\u2014i.e., barriers to trade in food and agricultural products\n\n===Broader rules and principles and modes of co-operation===\n\"Improved cooperation when it comes to setting international standards\".<ref name=\"TTIP explained\" />\n\nSpecific heads for discussion include:<ref name=\"eu state of play\" /><ref name=\"negotiators\" />\n* Energy and raw materials<ref>[http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/html/151624.htm Initial EU position on raw materials and energy], 16 July 2013</ref><ref>[http://eu-secretdeals.info/upload/2014/02/TTIPNonPaper-Energy-Sept2013-HuffingtonPost-Leak.pdf Leaked EU illustrative text] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140706003227/http://eu-secretdeals.info/upload/2014/02/TTIPNonPaper-Energy-Sept2013-HuffingtonPost-Leak.pdf |date=6 July 2014 }}, 20 September 2013. Leaked 19 May 2014</ref>\n* Trade and Sustainable Development / Labour and Environment<ref>{{cite web|url=http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/html/151626.htm |title=TTIP Position paper on sustainable development |publisher=Trade.ec.europa.eu |date= |accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref>\n* [[Public procurement]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/html/151623.htm |title=TTIP Initial EU position paper: public procurement |publisher=Trade.ec.europa.eu |date= |accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref>\n* Intellectual property<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://keionline.org/node/1984 |title=Leaked EU analysis of TTIP IPR negotiations &#124; Knowledge Ecology International |publisher=Keionline.org |date=20 March 2014 |accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref>\n** [[Geographical indications]]\n* [[Competition policy]]: [[antitrust]] and [[mergers]]\n** Treatment of state-owned or subsidised companies vis-a-vis private companies\n* [[Small and medium-sized enterprises]] (SMEs)\n* Trade remedies: e.g., [[Dumping (pricing policy)|anti-dumping]] practices\n* Customs and [[Trade Facilitation]]\n\n===Implementation===\n* Dispute settlement (between the parties, not [[investor-state dispute settlement]])\n\n==Negotiations==\n\n===Procedure===\nThe TTIP Agreement texts are being developed by 24 joint EU-US working groups, each considering a separate aspect of the agreement.  Development typically progresses through a number of phases.  Broad ''position paper''s are first exchanged, introducing each side's aims and ambitions for each aspect.  These are followed by ''textual proposals'' from each side, accompanied (in areas such as tariffs, and market access) by each side's \"initial offer.\" These negotiations and draft documents can evolve (change) through the various stages of their development. When both sides are ready, a ''consolidated text'' is prepared, with remaining differences for discussion expressed in square brackets. These texts are then provisionally closed topic by topic as a working consensus is reached.  However the agreement is negotiated as a whole, so no topic's text is finalised until full consensus is reached.<ref>[http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/press/index.cfm?id=1126 Commission publishes state of play of TTIP negotiations ahead of 6th round of talks], European Commission DG Trade, 11 July 2014</ref>\n\n===Negotiation rounds===\nNegotiations are held in week-long cycles alternating between Brussels and the USA.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ec.europa.eu/trade/policy/in-focus/ttip/documents-and-events/index_en.htm#negotiation-rounds |title=Documents and events \u2013 Negotiation rounds |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website= |publisher= [[European Commission|EU Commission]] |accessdate= 4 August 2015}}</ref> The negotiators were hoping to conclude their work by the end of 2016.<ref name=\"trade.ec.europa.eu\">{{cite web|url=http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/docs/2016/april/tradoc_154477.pdf |title=The Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP) State of Play |date= |accessdate=2016-11-22}}</ref>\n\n* The 1st round of negotiations: 7\u201312 July 2013 in Washington DC \n* The 2nd round of negotiations: 11\u201315 November 2013 in Brussels \n* The 3rd round of negotiations: 16\u201321 December 2013 in Washington DC \n* The 4th round of negotiations: 10\u201314 March 2014 in Brussels \n* The 5th round of negotiations: 19\u201323 May 2014 in Arlington, Virginia\n* The 6th round of negotiations: 13\u201318 July 2014 in Brussels \n* The 7th round of negotiations: 29 September \u2013 3 October 2014 in Chevy Chase, Maryland\n* The 8th round of negotiations: 2\u20136 February 2015 in Brussels \n* The 9th round of negotiations: 20\u201324 April 2015 in New York \n* The 10th round of negotiations: 13\u201317 July 2015 in Brussels\n* The 11th round of negotiations: 19\u201323 October 2015 in Miami\n* The 12th round of negotiations: 22\u201326 February 2016 in Brussels\n* The 13th round of negotiations: 25\u201329 April 2016 in New York\n* The 14th round of negotiations: 11\u201315 July 2016 in Brussels\n* The 15th round of negotiations: 3\u20137 October 2016 in New York\n\n===Confidentiality measures===\nOnly a few people can access the documents known as \"consolidated texts\", the drafts containing the most recent results of the negotiations. On the European side, authorised readers include the European Commission negotiators (most of them from the [[Directorate-General for Trade (European Commission)|Directorate-General for Trade]]),{{citation needed|date=April 2016}} [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]]s and European Union members' [[Member of Parliament|MP]]s.<ref name=Guardian160218>[https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/feb/18/mps-can-view-ttip-files-but-take-only-pencil-and-paper-with-them MPs can view TTIP files \u2013 but take only pencil and paper with them] {{snd}} [[The Guardian]], 18 February 2016</ref> Upon the insistence of the US, the documents are not transmitted any more as electronic or even printed documents.<ref name=\"Independent 14 August 2015\" />  \nThey are only available in secure rooms at the European Commission HQ in Brussels, in a number of US embassies,<ref name=\"Independent 14 August 2015\" /> and at the offices of member states' trade ministries.<ref name=Guardian160218 /> In all these secured rooms phones or other types of scanning device are forbidden.<ref name=\"Independent 14 August 2015\" /> Blank sheets of paper, marked with the reader's names, are provided on which visitors can jot down their notes.<ref name=Guardian160218 /> \nOn the US side, the procedure is similar: only Senators and [[Office of the United States Trade Representative|USTR]] negotiators may access the documents and must comply with similar conditions.<ref name=\"Independent 14 August 2015\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/ttip-controversy-secret-trade-deal-can-only-be-read-secure-in-reading-room-in-brussels-10456206.html |title=TTIP controversy: Secret trade deal can only be read in secure 'reading room' in Brussels |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website= |publisher= [[The Independent]] |accessdate= 23 September 2015}}</ref> The US side has insisted on the same security arrangements for the drafts of the [[Trans-Pacific Partnership]] proposal.<ref name=\"Independent 14 August 2015\" />\n\n===Hurdles===\nThe negotiations were planned to be finalized by the end of 2014, but according to economist [[Hosuk Lee-Makiyama]], at least another four or five years of negotiations remained at the end of that year.<ref name=\"Reuters Jun 16, 2015\">Philip Blenkinsop. [http://uk.reuters.com/article/us-eu-usa-trade-idUKKBN0OW0UW20150616 EU-U.S. trade deal seems distant dream after early optimism]. [[Reuters]]. 16 June 2015.</ref> In November 2014 the Bulgarian government announced that it will not ratify the agreement unless the United States lifted visa requirements for Bulgarian citizens.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.novinite.com/articles/165030/Bulgaria+Will+Not+Sign+TTIP+Unless+US+Lifts+Visa+Requirements+-+Minister|title=Bulgaria Will Not Sign TTIP Unless US Lifts Visa Requirements \u2013 Minister|work=novinite.com}}</ref>\n\nGerman Vice Chancellor and Economy Minister [[Sigmar Gabriel]] said that free trade talks between the European Union and the United States have failed, citing a lack of progress on any of the major sections of the long-running negotiations. \"In my opinion the negotiations with the United States have de facto failed, even though nobody is really admitting it\" the German broadcaster [[Zweites Deutsches Fernsehen]] quoted the minister, according to a written transcript of an interview aired on 28 August 2016. \"[They] have failed because we Europeans did not want to subject ourselves to American demands.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/611ff828b5ed44d5ad56ab46e0781e52/german-economy-minister-says-eu-us-trade-talks-have-failed\n|title=german-economy-minister-says-eu-us-trade-talks-have-failed}}</ref>\n\n===Negotiation progress===\nNegotiation progress as of 27 April 2016:<ref name=\"trade.ec.europa.eu\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.agra-net.com/agra/agra-europe/policy-and-legislation/trade-policy/commission-publishes-state-of-play-report-on-ttip-513635.htm|title=Commission publishes state-of-play report on TTIP|publisher=}}</ref>\n{|\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0f0;\"|{{nbsp}}\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''<small>No paper yet</small>'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''<small>US/EU Paper</small>'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''<small>EU & US proposals</small>'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''<small>Consolidation underway</small>'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''<small>Advanced state of consolidation</small>'''\n|-\n| <small>[[Agricultural policy|Agricultural Market Access]]</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| ||\n|-\n| <small>[[Political corruption#Opposing corruption|Anti-corruption]]</small>|| style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| ||||||\n|-\n| <small>Competition</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| || style=\"background:#73b539;\"| \n|-\n| <small>Cross-Border Trade in Services</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| ||\n|-\n| <small>Customs and Trade Facilitation</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| || style=\"background:#73b539;\"| \n|-\n| <small>[[E-Commerce]]</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| ||\n|-\n| <small>Energy and [[Raw Materials]]</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| ||||||\n|-\n| <small>[[Financial Services]]</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| ||\n|-\n| <small>Investment Protection</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| ||||\n|-\n| <small>[[Intellectual Property Rights]]</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| ||||\n|-\n| <small>Legal and Institutional</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| ||||||\n|-\n| <small>[[Market access]]/Industrial goods</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| ||\n|-\n| <small>[[Procurement]]</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| ||\n|-\n| <small>Regulatory Coherence</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| ||\n|-\n| <small>Regulatory Cooperation</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| ||\n|-\n| <small>[[Rules of Origin]]</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| ||\n|-\n| <small>[[Small and medium-sized enterprises]]</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| || style=\"background:#73b539;\"| \n|-\n| <small>[[State-Owned Enterprises]]</small>  || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| ||\n|-\n| <small>Sanitary and Phytosanitary Measures</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| ||\n|-\n| <small>State-to-State Dispute [[Settlement (litigation)|Settlement]]</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| || style=\"background:#73b539;\"| \n|-\n| <small>[[Subsidies]]</small>|| style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| ||||||\n|-\n| <small>[[Sustainable development|Sustainable dev.]]: Labour, Environment</small>|| style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| ||||\n|-\n| <small>[[Technical Barriers to Trade]]</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| ||\n|-\n| <small>[[Telecommunications industry|Telecom]]</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| ||\n|-\n| <small>Textiles and [[Apparel]]</small>|| style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| ||||||\n|-\n| <small>Trade Remedies</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| ||\n|-\n| <small>Sectors</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| ||||\n|-\n| \n|}\n\n==Ratification==\nThe twenty-eight European Union-member governments will have to approve of the partnership, via unanimous voting under TFEU Articles 207 and 218, on the negotiated agreement in the [[Council of the European Union]], at which point the [[European Parliament]] will also be asked for its endorsement. The European Parliament is empowered to approve or reject the agreement. In case the [[Council of the European Union]], following a proposal from the [[European Commission]], designates TTIP to be a \"mixed agreement\", approval from all Parliaments of the EU Member States in accordance with individual constitutional procedures is necessary before the agreement can enter into force. In the United States, both houses of the [[United States Congress|Congress]] will have to pass the agreement for it to be ratified.<ref>Ian F. Fergusson, [https://fas.org/sgp/crs/misc/RL33743.pdf Trade Promotion Authority (TPA) and the Role of Congress in Trade Policy, Congress Research Service ](15 June 2015), p. 9, n.15 (\"Under TPA, reciprocal FTAs and multilateral trade agreements that go beyond tariff reductions are treated as congressional-executive agreements, which require the approval of both houses of Congress. Such approval expresses Congress' consent to bind the United States to the commitments of the agreement under international law. This type of agreement is distinguished from both an [[executive agreement]], requiring only presidential action, and a [[treaty]], requiring a two-thirds vote of the Senate. Because reciprocal trade agreements typically result in tariff rate (revenue) changes, the House of Representatives is necessarily involved.\").</ref>\n\n==Proposed benefits==\nTTIP aims for a formal agreement that would \"liberalize one-third of global trade\" and, proponents argue, will create millions of new paid jobs.<ref name=\"Bollyky Foreign Affairs\">{{cite journal|last=Bollyky|first=Thomas J. and Anu Bradford|title=Getting to Yes on Transatlantic Trade|journal=Foreign Affairs|date=10 July 2013|url=http://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/139569/thomas-j-bollyky-and-anu-bradford/getting-to-yes-on-transatlantic-trade|accessdate=22 July 2013}}</ref> \"With tariffs between the United States and the European Union already low, the London-based [[Centre for Economic Policy Research]] estimates that 80 percent of the potential economic gains from the TTIP agreement depend on reducing the conflicts of duplication between EU and US rules on those and other regulatory issues, ranging from food safety to automobile parts.\"<ref name=\"Bollyky Foreign Affairs\" /> A successful strategy (according to Thomas Bollyky at the [[Council on Foreign Relations]] and Anu Bradford of [[Columbia Law School]]) will focus on business sectors for which transatlantic trade laws and local regulations can often overlap, e.g., pharmaceutical, agricultural, and financial trading.<ref name=\"Bollyky Foreign Affairs\" /> This will ensure that the United States and Europe remain \"standard makers, rather than standard takers\", in the global economy, subsequently ensuring that producers worldwide continue to gravitate toward joint US-EU standards.<ref name=\"Bollyky Foreign Affairs\" />\n\nIn March 2013, an economic assessment by the European [[Centre for Economic Policy Research]] estimates that such a comprehensive agreement would result in GDP growth of 68\u2013119&nbsp;billion euros for the European Union by 2027 and GDP growth of 50\u201395&nbsp;billion euros (about 53.5\u2013101&nbsp;billion US dollars) in the United States in the same time frame. The 2013 report also estimates that a limited agreement focused only on tariffs would yield EU GDP growth of 24&nbsp;billion euros by 2027 and growth of 9&nbsp;billion euros in the United States. If shared equally among the affected people, the most optimistic GDP growth estimates would translate into \"additional annual disposable income for a family of four\" of \"545 euros in the EU\" and \"655 euros in the US\", respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/docs/2013/march/tradoc_150737.pdf|title=Reducing Transatlantic Barriers to Trade and Investment: An Economic Assessment|publisher=Trade.ec.europa.eu|accessdate=2 February 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131228053938/http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/docs/2013/march/tradoc_150737.pdf|archive-date=28 December 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn a ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'' article, the CEO of [[Siemens]] AG (with its workforce located 70% in Europe and 30% in the United States) claimed that the TTIP would strengthen United States and EU global competitiveness by reducing trade barriers, by improving intellectual property protections, and by establishing new international \"rules of the road\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Kaeser |first=Joe |title=Why a US-European trade deal is a win-win |url=https://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702303973704579350783279285204?KEYWORDS=siemens |newspaper=The Wall Street Journal |date=2 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe [[European Commission]] says that the TTIP would boost the EU's economy by \u20ac120&nbsp;billion, the US economy by \u20ac90&nbsp;billion and the rest of the world by \u20ac100&nbsp;billion.<ref name=\"EU-ttip\"/> Talks began in July 2013 and reached the third round of negotiations by the end of that year.<ref name=\"EU-ttip\">{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/trade/policy/in-focus/ttip/ |title=Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP) \u2013 Trade \u2013 European Commission |publisher=Ec.europa.eu |date= |accessdate=2014-02-21}}</ref>\n\nAmerican economist [[Dean Baker]] of the [[Center for Economic and Policy Research]] observed that with conventional trade barriers between the US and the EU already low, the deal would focus on non-conventional barriers, such as overriding national regulations on [[fracking]], [[GMOs]], and finance, but also tightening laws on copyright. He goes on to assert that, with less ambitious projections, the economic benefits per household are unimpressive: \"If we apply the projected income gain of 0.21% to the projected median personal income in 2027, it comes to a bit more than $50 a year. That's a little less than 15 cents a day. Don't spend it all in one place\".<ref name=\"guardian July 15, 2013\">The Guardian (15 July 2013). [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/jul/15/us-trade-deal-with-europe-hype The US-EU trade deal: Don't buy the hype] Retrieved 24 August 2013.</ref>\n\nA 2018 paper by [[KU Leuven]] economists estimated that a \"deep\" free-trade agreement, such as TTIP, between the United States and the European Union would increase EU GDP by 1.3% and US GDP by 0.7%.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://voxeu.org/article/free-trade-between-eu-and-us-match-made-heaven|title=Free trade between the EU and US: A match made in heaven|last=Vandenbussche|first=Hylke|last2=Connell|first2=William|date=2018-08-23|website=VoxEU.org|access-date=2018-08-24|last3=Simons|first3=Wouter}}</ref> These gains would primarily be the result of reductions in [[Non-tariff barriers to trade|non-tariff barriers to trade]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Criticism and opposition==\n[[File:Grossdemonstration gegen TTIP in Berlin Oktober 2015.jpg|thumb|The STOP TTIP CETA demo in Berlin in October 2015 had around 250.000 participants.<ref>{{cite web|title=TTIP bringt Rekordzahl von Gegnern auf die Stra\u00dfe|url=http://www.zeit.de/wirtschaft/2015-10/ttip-demonstration-berlin-gabriel-ceta|publisher=ZEIT ONLINE|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Dearden|first1=Nick|title=Think TTIP is a threat to democracy? There's another trade deal that's already signed|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/may/30/ttip-trade-deal-agreements-ceta-eu-canada|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=7 August 2016|date=30 May 2016}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Cabecera de la mani (17009525818).jpg|thumb|\"Stop TTIP\" protests in [[Barcelona]], Spain, April 18, 2015]]\n[[File:2016-04-23 Anti-TTIP-Demonstration in Hannover, (10118).jpg|thumb|Anti-TTIP demonstration in [[Hannover]], Germany, April 23, 2016]]\n[[File:Stop TTIP-CETA Protest in Brussels 20-09-2016 (15).jpg|thumb|The Stop TTIP-CETA protest in [[Brussels]], Belgium, September 20, 2016]]\n\n=== Secrecy of content and negotiations ===\nThe content of the drafts of agreement, as well as the reports on negotiation rounds, are [[classified information|classified]] from the public, an arrangement that ''[[The Independent]]'' criticised as \"secretive and undemocratic\".<ref name=\"The Independent October 6, 2015\"/> As noted [[#Confidentiality measures|above]], elected representatives may only view the texts in a secure \"reading room\" in Brussels, to avoid any further leaks of information about TTIP negotiations into the public domain.\n\nTo answer the criticism, and months after their leaks by Greenpeace, the European Commission has made negotiation documents public, including all EU proposals in the regulatory and rules components of the agreement.<ref name=\"trade.ec.europa.eu\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euractiv.com/section/trade-society/news/ttip-papers-published-as-eu-ombudsman-demands-more-transparency/|title=TTIP papers published as EU Ombudsman demands more transparency|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/press/index.cfm?id=1230|title=EU negotiating texts in TTIP \u2013 Trade \u2013 European Commission|publisher=}}</ref> The Trade Commissioner has described the negotiations as \"the most transparent trade talks ever conducted by the EU\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/commission/2014-2019/malmstrom/blog/ttip-state-play_en|title=TTIP \u2013 the State of Play \u2013 European Commission \u2013 European Commission|first=Joakim|last=LARSSON|date=27 April 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n=== Possible negative impacts ===\n==== Politics, economy and society====\n''The Guardian'' described TTIP as \"the most controversial trade deal the EU has ever negotiated\".<ref name=\"theguardian.com 27 August 2016\"/> TTIP negotiations are criticized and opposed by some [[Trade union|unions]], charities, [[Non-governmental organization|NGOs]] and environmentalists, particularly in Europe.<ref name=\"guardian August 3, 2015\"/><ref name=\"The Daily Beast\">{{cite web|author=Leo Cendrowicz |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2015/04/22/europeans-fight-u-s-trade-deal-with-fear-of-mchospitals-fracking-under-eiffel-tower.html |title=Europeans Fight U.S. Trade Deal With Fear of McHospitals, Fracking Under Eiffel Tower |publisher=The Daily Beast |date= |accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref> ''[[The Independent]]'' summarizes the negative impact of TTIP as \"reducing the regulatory barriers to trade for big business, things like food safety law, environmental legislation, banking regulations and the sovereign powers of individual nations\",<ref name=\"The Independent October 6, 2015\">Lee Williams [https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/comment/what-is-ttip-and-six-reasons-why-the-answer-should-scare-you-9779688.html What is TTIP? And six reasons why the answer should scare you]. ''[[The Independent]]''. 6 October 2015.</ref> or more critically as an \"assault on European and US societies by transnational corporations\".<ref name=\"The Independent October 6, 2015\"/> German economist [[Max Otte]] stated that the proposed (ISDS) [[Investor-state dispute settlement#Tribunals|court of arbitration and protection of foreign investment]] would mean a \"complete dis-empowerment of politics\"<ref name=\"heute April 8, 2016\">[https://www.3sat.de/page/?source=/makro/magazin/doks/186138/index.html TTIP: \"V\u00f6llige Entmachtung der Politik\"]. [[3sat]]. Published on 8 April 2016.</ref> and that, regarding labour economics, free trade agreements typically enforce lower standards and that TTIP would put European workers into direct competition with Americans (and in effect because of the [[North American Free Trade Agreement]] with Mexicans), which would impact European social models.<ref name=\"heute April 8, 2016\"/> Otte also concluded: \"We really don't want the [[social system]] of these countries [United States and Mexico] here [in Europe].\"<ref name=\"heute April 8, 2016\"/>\n\nAn October 2014 study by Jeronim Capaldo of the [[Global Development and Environment Institute]] at [[Tufts University]] indicates that there will be losses in terms of net exports, net losses in terms of GDP, loss of labour income, job losses, reduction of the labour share, loss of government revenue and higher financial instability among European countries.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Capaldo|first1=Jeronim|title=The Trans-Atlantic Trade and Investment Partnership: European Disintegration, Unemployment and Instability|url=http://ase.tufts.edu/gdae/policy_research/TTIP_simulations.html}}</ref>\n\n==== Labour standards, workers' rights and job security ====\nAnti-poverty group [[Global Justice Now]] asserts that TTIP would undermine job security as well as current minimum labour standards agreed in the EU.<ref name=\"guardian October 18, 2015\"/> [[Labour Party (UK)|British Labour Party]] politician [[John McDonnell (politician)|John McDonnell]], [[Shadow Chancellor of the Exchequer]], has described TTIP as resulting in a huge transfer of powers to Brussels and [[corporatocracy|corporate interests]] that will bring about a form of \"modern-day [[serfdom]]\".<ref name=\"guardian October 18, 2015\"/> According to a [[European Parliament]] report, impacts on labour conditions range from job gains to job losses, depending on economic model and assumptions used for predictions.<ref name=\"EP Kraatz\"/>\n\nIn spite of a study by the Munich-based [[Ifo Institute for Economic Research]] (on behalf of the German Federal Ministry of Economics) claiming that up to 400,000 jobs could be created in the EU by TTIP,<ref>{{cite web|title=Topical Terms in Economics: Transatlantic Free Trade Agreement|url=https://www.cesifo-group.de/ifoHome/facts/Aktuelles-Stichwort/Topical-Terms-Archive/Transatlantic-Free-Trade-Agreement.html}}</ref> Stefan K\u00f6rzell, national board member of the [[Confederation of German Trade Unions]] (DGB) has said \"Whether TTIP can create jobs, and 'how many' and 'where' is unclear. Previous studies, ranging from those conducted by the European Commission across to the expertise of the Ifo Institute, fluctuate between optimism and very low expectations... Consideration of the negative consequences trade agreements can have, if environmental or labour standards are ignored, is often omitted. As of August 2015, the US had ratified two (prohibitions of child labour and slavery) of the eight [[International Labour Organization|ILO]] [[Social clause|core labour standards]].\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Viavision: The Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership|url=http://www.viavision.org.uk/ftp/1887.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==== Democracy and national sovereignty, foreign investor protection ====\n[[Investor-state dispute settlement]] (ISDS) is an instrument that allows an investor to bring a case directly against the country hosting its investment, without the intervention of the government of the investor's country of origin.<ref>{{cite web|author=European Commission |date=3 October 2013|url=http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/docs/2013/october/tradoc_151791.pdf |title=Factsheet on Investor-State Dispute Settlement|accessdate=2014-02-21}}</ref> From the late 1980s, certain trade treaties have included provisions for ISDS that allow foreign investors who claim to have been disadvantaged by actions of a signatory state, to sue that state for damages in a [[Arbitral tribunal|tribunal of arbitration]]. More recently such claims have increased in number and value,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://unctad.org/en/PublicationsLibrary/webdiaepcb2013d3_en.pdf|title=Recent Developments in Investor-State Disputes|publisher=Unctad.org|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref> and some states have become increasingly resistant to such clauses.<ref>Economist (11 October 2014) [https://www.economist.com/news/finance-and-economics/21623756-governments-are-souring-treaties-protect-foreign-investors-arbitration The arbitration game: Governments are souring on treaties to protect foreign investors] Retrieved 24 April 2015.</ref>\n\nCritics of TTIP say that \"ISDS provisions undermine the power of national governments to act in the interests of their citizens\",<ref name=\"guardian August 3, 2015\"/> that \"TTIP could even undermine the democratic authority of local government\",<ref name=\"guardian August 5, 2015\"/> and that it threatens democracy.<ref>Michael Robinson. [https://www.bbc.com/news/business-32116587 Is democracy threatened if companies can sue countries?]. [[BBC News]]. 31 March 2015.</ref> France and Germany have said that they want access to investor-state dispute settlement removed from the TTIP treaty.<ref name=\"guardian June 10, 2015\">Claire Provost and Matt Kennard. [https://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/jun/10/obscure-legal-system-lets-corportations-sue-states-ttip-icsid The obscure legal system that lets corporations sue countries]. [[theguardian.com]]. 10 June 2015</ref> In December 2013, a coalition of over 200 environmentalists, labor unions and consumer advocacy organizations on both sides of the Atlantic sent a letter to the [[Office of the United States Trade Representative|USTR]] and European Commission demanding the investor-state dispute settlement be dropped from the trade talks, claiming that ISDS was \"a one-way street by which corporations can challenge government policies, but neither governments nor individuals are granted any comparable rights to hold corporations accountable\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Stangler |first=Cole |url=http://inthesetimes.com/article/16044/ttip_the_next_corporate_friendly_trade_deal/ |title=The Next Corporate-Friendly Trade Pact |publisher=In These Times |date=30 December 2013 |accessdate=2014-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://action.sierraclub.org/site/DocServer/TTIP_Investment_Letter_Final.pdf?docID=14701 |title=Letter |publisher=Action.sierraclub.org |accessdate=2014-02-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140224075427/http://action.sierraclub.org/site/DocServer/TTIP_Investment_Letter_Final.pdf?docID=14701 |archivedate=24 February 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Some point out the \"potential for abuse\" that may be inherent in the trade agreement due to its clauses relating to investor protection.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/sep/14/ttip-deal-british-sovereignty-cameron-ukip-treaty|title=The TTIP deal hands British sovereignty to multinationals|last=Jones|first=Owen|date=14 September 2014|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=Guardian Media|accessdate=5 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/business/criticism-grows-over-investor-protections-in-transatlantic-trade-deal-a-945107.html|title= Corporation Carte Blanche: Will US-EU Trade Become Too Free?|last=Schiessl|first=Michaela|date=23 January 2014|work=[[Spiegel International]]|publisher=Spiegel Online|accessdate=5 November 2014}}</ref> A recent study shows that investor-state dispute settlement (ISDS) indeed generates strikingly large and consistent opposition to the trade agreement and this effect of dispute settlement characteristic cuts across individuals\u2019 key attributes, including skill levels, information, and national sentiment, which have been viewed as key determinants of trade attitudes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hahm|first=Hyeonho|last2=K\u00f6nig|first2=Thomas|last3=Osnabr\u00fcgge|first3=Moritz|last4=Frech|first4=Elena|date=2019|title=Who Settles Disputes? Treaty Design and Trade Attitudes Toward the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP)|journal=International Organization|language=en|volume=73|issue=4|pages=881\u2013900|doi=10.1017/S0020818319000249|issn=0020-8183}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2013, [[Martti Koskenniemi]], Professor of International Law at the [[University of Helsinki]], warned that the planned foreign investor protection scheme within the treaty, similar to [[World Bank Group]]'s [[International Centre for Settlement of Investment Disputes]] (ICSID), would endanger the sovereignty of the signatory states by allowing for a small circle of legal experts sitting in a foreign court of arbitration an unprecedented power to interpret and void the signatory states' legislation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hs.fi/sunnuntai/Professori+Suomen+valta+s%C3%A4%C3%A4t%C3%A4%C3%A4+lakeja+voi+vaarantua+/a1386995885773|title=Professori: Suomen valta s\u00e4\u00e4t\u00e4\u00e4 lakeja voi vaarantua |last=Konttinen|first=Jussi|date=15 December 2013|work=[[Helsingin Sanomat]]|publisher=Sanoma Oyj|language=Finnish|accessdate=16 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nFaced with such broad and vociferous criticism, ISDS was abandoned in September 2015; in its place, the European Commission proposed an Investment Court System (ICS).<ref>{{cite web|title = EU proposes new trade court with US|url = https://euobserver.com/economic/130297|website = EUobserver|access-date = 23 February 2016|last = Nielsen|first = Nikolaj|date = 16 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.greenpeace.org/eu-unit/Global/eu-unit/reports-briefings/2016/2016_02_11_Greenpeace%20Position%20Paper%20ICS_Final.pdf|title = From ISDS to ICS: A Leopard Can't Change Its Spots|date = 11 February 2016|access-date = 23 February 2016 |page = 1 |publisher = Greenpeace Position Paper |author = Greenpeace}}</ref> Not long afterwards, ICS was declared illegal by the German Association of Magistrates,<ref>{{cite web|title = TTIP investor court illegal, say German judges|url = https://euobserver.com/economic/132142|website = EUobserver|access-date = 6 February 2016|date = 4 February 2016|last = Nielsen|first = Nikolaj}}</ref> though the commission dismissed the magistrates' judgement as based on a misunderstanding.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|title = EU defends TTIP investor court after German backlash|url = https://euobserver.com/economic/132295|website = EUobserver|access-date = 23 February 2016|date = 17 February 2016|last = Nielsen|first = Nikolaj}}</ref> For its part, the United States wants ISDS reinstated.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn February 2016, Labour (UK) leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]] said that human rights should be part of TTIP,   \ndescribing TTIP as a threat to national sovereignty, workers, consumers, health and the environment.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/ttip-human-rights-workers-corporate-court-law-jeremy-corbyn-david-cameron-pmqs-a6889531.html TTIP 'must include human rights', Jeremy Corbyn tells David Cameron] H. Sheffield, The Independent, 22 February 2016</ref>\n\n==== Public health and environment ====\nAccording to a report in ''The Guardian'', TTIP draft leaked in 2016 shows \"irreconcilable\" differences between EU and the US in some areas, with the US demanding that EU compromise its \"environmental, consumer protection and public health standards\".<ref name=\"The Guardian May 1, 2016\">Arthur Neslen. [https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/may/01/leaked-ttip-documents-cast-doubt-on-eu-us-trade-deal Leaked TTIP documents cast doubt on EU-US trade deal]. ''[[The Guardian]]''. 1 May 2016.</ref>\n\n===== Health care =====\n{{See also|Healthcare in Europe|Health care in the United States}}\n[[Trade unions in the United Kingdom|British unions]] such as [[Unite the Union|Unite]] and the [[Trades Union Congress|TUC]] have opposed TTIP on the grounds that it would undermine the [[National Health Service]] and allows for the further [[privatisation]] of public services. A Unite spokesperson described TTIP as \"about deregulation and a [[race to the bottom]] on standards. Unison has fought and won on bringing services back into the public sector. ... We cannot allow TTIP to threaten those successes.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chako|first1=Ben|title=TUC says no to TTIP|url=http://www.ukpressonline.co.uk/ukpressonline/getDocument/DWMS_2014_09_11_001?fileType=PDF|accessdate=7 April 2016|work=Morning Star|date=11 September 2014|page=1|format=PDF|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nFormer Foreign Secretary [[David Owen]] said that TTIP would have a significant negative impact on the UK's [[National Health Service]] because the Service would be subject to increased competition under the TTIP regime.<ref name=\"Telegraph 6/4/16\">[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/04/06/nhs-would-be-completely-unrecognisable-within-years-if-uk-remain/ NHS would be 'completely unrecognisable' within years if UK remains inside the EU] K. McCann, The Daily Telegraph, 6 April 2016</ref>\n\nFormer UK prime minister [[David Cameron]] said that critics of [[free-trade]] should not use the [[National Health Service]] (NHS) to take people's attention away, and honestly speak about trade deals. UK's [[Department of Business, Innovation and Skills]] said that TTIP provided adequate protection for UK's NHS.<ref name=rt09052016TTIP>[https://www.rt.com/uk/342384-ttip-deal-nhs-cameron/ \u2018Slippery fish\u2019 Cameron is duping the public, TTIP is threat to NHS, critics say] RT, 9 May 2016</ref>\n\nAssistant General Secretary of [[Unite the Union|Unite]] [[Gail Cartmail]] said that TTIP was a real and serious threat to the NHS, adding that the threat would not be neutralised unless [[David Cameron]] gave a cast-iron guarantee that he would exclude the NHS from TTIP.<ref name=rt09052016TTIP />\n\n===== Consumer protection and food safety =====\n{{See also|European Food Safety Authority|Regulation of genetically modified organisms in the European Union|Pesticide regulation in the United States}}\n\nDocuments released in May 2015 showed that US negotiators had pressured the EU over proposed pesticide criteria. A number of pesticides containing [[endocrine disrupting chemicals]] were forbidden in draft EU criteria. On 2 May 2013, US negotiators insisted the EU drop the criteria. They stated that a risk-based approach should be taken on regulation. Later the same day [[Catherine Day]] ([[Secretary-General of the European Commission]]) wrote to Karl Falkenberg ([[Directorate-General for the Environment|Director General for the Environment]]) asking for these criteria to be removed.{{r|guardian22may15}} {{As of|2015}}, 82 pesticides used in the US were banned in Europe and US [[animal welfare]] standards are generally lower than those in Europe.<ref name=\"BBC 10 June 2015\"/>\n\nA columnist in ''[[The Guardian]]'' stated that [[food safety]] in the EU might be compromised because of low or different standards in US food regulations,<ref name=\"guardian August 3, 2015\"/> if currently EU-banned food were allowed to be imported.<ref name=\"guardian October 18, 2015\">Phillip Inman. [https://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/oct/18/prospect-ttip-deal-undermining-eu-food-standards-gmos Prospect of TTIP already undermining EU food standards, say campaigners]. [[The Guardian]]. 18 October 2015.</ref> In June 2015, the [[BBC]] reported that food safety had become 'a stumbling block' because of differing US and EU attitudes to [[genetically modified crops]], [[pesticides]] ([[Endocrine disruptor|endocrine disrupting chemicals]]), [[growth hormone#Agricultural use|growth promoting hormones]] in beef and [[pathogen]] reduction treatments of [[Chicken (food)|chicken]], that cause public health concerns for consumers and put European farmers at a cost disadvantage.<ref name=\"BBC 10 June 2015\">Laurence Peter. [https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-33055665 TTIP talks: Food fights block EU\u2013US trade deal]. [[BBC News]]. 10 June 2015.</ref> Ban on [[animal testing]] in the EU has been described by ''The Guardian'' as \"irreconcilable\" with the US approach.<ref name=\"The Guardian May 1, 2016\"/>\n\n===== Environment protection and climate change =====\n{{See also|Environmental policy of the European Union|Climate change mitigation|Politics of global warming}}\n\nA draft of the sustainable development section of TTIP was leaked to ''[[The Guardian]]'' in October 2015. Asked to comment on the document, a French environmental attorney described the proposed environmental safeguards as \"virtually non-existent\" by comparison with the protection granted to investors, and that environmental cases accounted for 60% of the 127 [[Investor-state dispute settlement|ISDS]] cases already brought against EU countries under bilateral trade agreements in the last two decades, according to [[Friends of the Earth Europe]].<ref>{{cite web |last= Nielsen |first= Arthur |date= 23 October 2015 |title= TTIP: EU negotiators appear to break environmental pledge in leaked draft |url= https://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/oct/23/ttip-eu-negotiators-appear-to-break-environmental-pledge-in-leaked-draft |website= theguardian.com |accessdate= 23 February 2016 }}</ref>\nAccording to [[Joseph E. Stiglitz]], TTIP could have a \"chilling\" effect on regulation and thus \"undercut urgently needed action on climate that the Paris agreement requires\". He says that industries that do not pay for the \"social costs\" of pollution in effect receive hidden subsidies, and that TTIP would give companies many more opportunities to sue governments over environmental protection mechanisms.<ref name=\"stiglitz-2016\">{{cite news | first = Joseph E | last = Stiglitz | author-link = Joseph E. Stiglitz | date = 23 April 2016 | title = TTIP and Climate Change: A Tale of Two Cities from Paris to Hannover | newspaper = [[S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung]] | url = http://www.sueddeutsche.de/politik/exterior-view-ttip-and-climate-change-a-tale-of-two-cities-from-paris-to-hannover-1.2963133 | access-date = 11 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe draft energy chapter of the TTIP was leaked to ''[[The Guardian]]'' in July 2016.<ref name=\"neslen-2016\">{{cite news | first = Arthur | last = Neslen | title = Leaked TTIP energy proposal could 'sabotage' EU climate policy | date = 11 July 2016 | newspaper = [[The Guardian]] | url = https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2016/jul/11/leaked-ttip-energy-proposal-could-sabotage-eu-climate-policy | access-date = 11 July 2016}}</ref> According to ''The Guardian'', this draft could \"sabotage\" European efforts to implement mandatory energy savings measures and to favor the switch to renewable electricity generation.  The draft text obliges the two trade blocs to: \"foster industry self-regulation of energy efficiency requirements for goods where such self-regulation is likely to deliver the policy objectives faster or in a less costly manner than mandatory requirements\".<ref name=\"neslen-2016\"/>  The draft also mandates that operators of energy networks grant access to gas and electricity \"on commercial terms that are reasonable, transparent and non-discriminatory, including as between types of energy\".<ref name=\"neslen-2016\"/>  This would open [[feed-in tariff]] schemes to commercial challenge, including [[German Renewable Energy Sources Act|that]] used by Germany.  The [[The Greens (Luxembourg)|Green]] [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]] [[Claude Turmes]] stated: \"These proposals are completely unacceptable. They would sabotage EU legislators' ability to privilege renewables and energy efficiency over unsustainable fossil fuels. This is an attempt to undermine democracy in Europe.\"<ref name=\"neslen-2016\"/>\n\nThe EU's draft text for the trade and sustainable development chapter was also leaked to ''[[The Guardian]]'' in July 2016.<ref name=\"neslen-2016-b\">{{cite news | first = Arthur | last = Neslen | title = TTIP proposal casts doubt on G20 climate pledge, leaked EU draft shows | date =  13 July 2016 | newspaper = The Guardian | url = https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2016/jul/13/ttip-proposal-casts-doubt-on-g20-climate-pledge-leaked-eu-draft-shows | access-date = 2016-07-12}}</ref> The draft, dated 23 June 2016 and marked \"restricted\", reveals new loopholes on a [[G20]] pledge to phase out inefficient [[Energy subsidies|fossil fuel subsidies]] by 2025.  The [[International Monetary Fund|IMF]] estimates these subsidies run globally at $10{{nbsp}}million per minute<ref name=\"carrington-2015\">{{cite news | first = Damian | last = Carrington | title = Fossil fuels subsidised by $10m a minute, says IMF | date = 18 May 2015 | newspaper = The Guardian | url = https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2015/may/18/fossil-fuel-companies-getting-10m-a-minute-in-subsidies-says-imf | access-date = 2016-07-12}}</ref> and [[G7]] ministers pledged to remove them in May 2016 in a meeting in Japan.<ref name=\"mathiesen-2016\">{{cite news | first = Karl | last = Mathiesen | title = G7 nations pledge to end fossil fuel subsidies by 2025 | date = 27 May 2016 | newspaper = The Guardian | url = https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2016/may/27/g7-nations-pledge-to-end-fossil-fuel-subsidies-by-2025 | access-date = 2016-07-12}}</ref> The draft however states that \"such a phasing out may take into account security of supply considerations\".<ref name=\"neslen-2016-b\"/>  ''The Guardian'' believes that this passage could be open to abuse and used to slow the phase out of subsidies.\n\n==== Banking regulation ====\n{{See also|Bank regulation in the United States}}\n\nAccording to critics, TTIP could weaken the stricter [[bank regulation]]s that are governing banks in the United States as part of the financial reforms that followed the [[financial crisis of 2007\u201308]].<ref name=\"The Independent October 6, 2015\"/><ref name=\"BBC 18 December 2014\">Leala Padmanabhan. [https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-30493297 TTIP: The EU-US trade deal explained]. BBC News. 18 December 2014</ref>\n\n==== Privacy ====\n{{See also|Mass surveillance in the United States|Internet censorship in the United States}}\n\nCritics of TTIP argue that its proposals on intellectual property could have a similar effect as the EU-rejected [[Anti-Counterfeiting Trade Agreement]] (ACTA).<ref name=\"BBC 18 December 2014\"/> The [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]] and its German counterpart, [[Foundation for a Free Information Infrastructure|FFII]], in particular, compared TTIP to the ACTA.<ref>{{cite web|work=EFF|url=https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2013/03/transatlantic-declaration-leave-copyright-patent-issues-out-tafta|title=Transatlantic Civil Society Declaration: Leave Copyright and Patent Provisions Out of TAFTA|accessdate= 18 March 2013|date= 18 March 2013|author= Maira Sutton}}</ref>\n\n=== Activism against TTIP ===\n[[File:Stop TTIP Martin Schulz 01.jpg|thumb|\"Stop TTIP\" [[Civil society campaign|campaigner]]s hand 3,284,289 signatures to [[Martin Schulz]], [[President of the European Parliament]], November 2015.]]\nIn March 2013, a coalition of [[digital rights]] organisations and other groups issued a declaration<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.citizen.org/ip-out-of-tafta|title=IP out of TAFTA|work=citizen.org|accessdate=18 March 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130320190633/https://www.citizen.org/IP-out-of-TAFTA|archivedate=20 March 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> in which they called on the negotiating partners to have TTIP \"debated in the [[US Congress]], the [[European Parliament]], national parliaments, and other transparent forums\" instead of conducting \"closed negotiations that give privileged access to corporate insiders\", and to leave intellectual property out of the agreement.\n\nIn 2014, an online consultation conducted by the European Commission<ref>{{cite web |url= http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-14-292_en.htm |title= European Commission launches public online consultation on investor protection in TTIP |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= 27 March 2014 |website= |publisher= [[European Commission]] |accessdate= 26 July 2015}}</ref> received 150,000 responses.  According to the commission, 97% of the responses were pre-defined, negative answers provided by activists.<ref>{{cite news \n|title= EU finds 'huge skepticism' over US trade deal \n|url= https://news.yahoo.com/eu-finds-huge-scepticism-over-us-trade-deal-203636918.html \n|date= 13 January 2015 \n|work=Yahoo News \n|accessdate=21 January 2015 }}\n</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sueddeutsche.de/wirtschaft/buergerbefragung-zu-ttip-prozent-dagegen-1.2302201|title=B\u00fcrgerbefragung zu TTIP: 97 Prozent dagegen|first1=Michael|last1=Bauchm\u00fcller|first2=Cerstin |last2=Gammelin|publisher=|via=Sueddeutsche.de}}</ref> Additionally, hundreds of demonstrations and protests have taken place in an organised \"day of action\" on 11 October 2014,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stop-ttip-ceta-tisa.eu/ |title=October 11, 2014 \u2013 #O11DoA European Day of Action  |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website= |publisher= |accessdate= 26 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://stop-ttip.org/|title=Home \u2013 Stop TTIP Stop TTIP|work=Stop TTIP}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/nov/04/british-government-leading-gunpowder-plot-democracy-eu-us-trade|title=The British government is leading a gunpowder plot against democracy|author=George Monbiot|work=the Guardian}}</ref> and again on 18 April 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.euractiv.com/sections/trade-society/thousands-across-europe-protest-against-ttip-313921|title= Thousands across Europe protest against TTIP |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= 20 April 2015|website= euractiv.com|publisher= |accessdate= 27 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=imk56itZc_w|title= TTIP protests 17 18 April 2015 \u2013 Lewisham PeopleBeforeProfit|last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website= |publisher= YouTube|accessdate= 27 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZLrr0V2a8lE |title=TTIP Aktionstag in Mainz 18 April 2015  |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website= |publisher= YouTube|accessdate= 27 July 2015}}</ref> In February 2016, Greenpeace activists blocked secret talks on the Investment Court System.<ref>{{cite web |title = Greenpeace activists block secret TTIP talks |url = http://www.greenpeace.org/eu-unit/en/News/2016/Greenpeace-activists-block-secret-TTIP-talks/ |website = Greenpeace EU Unit |access-date = 23 February 2016 |date = 22 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nA self-organised [[European Citizens' Initiative]] against TTIP and [[Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement|CETA]] has also been established, acquiring over 3.2&nbsp;million signatures within a year.<ref name=\"guard 3 Aug 2015\" /><ref name=\"Stop TTIP\"/>\n\nIn April 2016, then-President [[Barack Obama]] visited UK, and more than 130,000 people signed a petition organised by political activism group [[38 Degrees]], urging Obama to stop negotiating TTIP.<ref name=\"Independent 190416\" /> The group planned to send an open letter to Obama to urge Obama to oppose the pact, saying that TTIP would be a threat to [[National Health Service (England)|NHS]], food standards, animal welfare and democracy because it 'gives corporations more power than people'.<ref name=\"Independent 190416\">[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/ttip-more-than-130000-people-urge-barack-obama-to-kill-controversial-trade-deal-during-uk-visit-a6991286.html TTIP: More than 130,000 people urge Barack Obama to kill controversial trade deal during UK visit] R. Revesz, The Independent, 19 April 2016</ref>\n\n==== Leaks ====\nIn 2016, Greenpeace published 248 pages of classified documents from the TTIP trade negotiations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ttip-leaks.org/|title=Read the secret #TTIP papers here|publisher=}}</ref> Greenpeace Netherlands said it released the documents \"to provide much needed transparency and trigger an informed debate on the treaty\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/may/01/leaked-ttip-documents-cast-doubt-on-eu-us-trade-deal|title=Leaked TTIP documents cast doubt on EU-US trade deal|first=Arthur|last=Neslen|date=1 May 2016|publisher=|via=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n===National objections===\nFrom both the European and American sides of the agreement, there are issues which are seen as essential if an accord is to be reached.  According to Leif Johan Eliasson of Saarland University, \"For the EU these include greater access to the American public procurement market, retained bans on imports of [[genetically modified organisms]] (GMO) crops and [[Beef hormone controversy|hormone treated beef]], and recognition of [[geographical indications|geographic trademarks on food products]]. For the United States they include greater access for American dairy and other agricultural products (including scientific studies as the only accepted criteria for [[Sanitary and phytosanitary measures and agreements|SPS]] policies).\" He observes that measures like the EU ban on hormone treated beef (based as they are on the [[precautionary principle]]) are not considered by the [[World Trade Organization|WTO]] to be based on scientific studies.\n\nEliasson further states that US objectives in a deal include \"tariff-free motor vehicle exports,\" and retained bans on foreign contractors in several areas,\" including domestic shipping (see [[Merchant Marine Act of 1920]]).<ref name=\"eliasson2013\">Leif Johan Eliasson, [http://jean-monnet-saar.eu/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/10_07_14_TTIP-Eliasson.pdf What is at stake in the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP)? Assessing challenges and possible compromises], Saarland University, 10 July 2014</ref> Already, some American producers are concerned by EU proposals to restrict use of \"[[Geographical indications and traditional specialities in the European Union|particular designations]]\" (also known as <!-- people may search for: -->PDO or GI/geographical indications) that the EU considers location-specific, such as [[feta]] and [[Parmesan]] cheeses and possibly [[Budweiser Budvar|Budweiser]] beer.<ref>[https://www.economist.com/news/united-states/21607867-europeans-want-their-food-names-back-americans-are-peeved-stressed-are-cheesemakers Food names: Stressed are the cheesemakers: Europeans want their food names back. Americans are peeved], [[The Economist]], 19 July 2014</ref><ref>Beer from [[\u010cesk\u00e9 Bud\u011bjovice]]/Budweis([[Czech Republic]]) has [[Geographical indications and traditional specialities in the European Union|Protected Geographical Indication]]. [[Budweiser Budvar]] is already [[Budweiser trademark dispute|party to a trademark dispute]] with [[Anheuser-Busch InBev]] over which has the right to use the term.</ref> This has provoked debate between European politicians such as [[Renate K\u00fcnast]] and [[Christian Schmidt (politician)|Christian Schmidt]] over the value of the designations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euractiv.com/sections/trade-society/germans-fret-about-kentucky-fried-bratwurst-under-ttip-311067|title=Germans fret about 'Kentucky Fried Bratwurst' under TTIP|work=EurActiv \u2013 EU News & policy debates, across languages}}</ref>\n\nAt French insistence, [[Cultural exception|trade in audio-visual services was excluded]] from the EU negotiating mandate.<ref>[http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/html/152670.htm TTIP and Culture], European Commission DG Trade, 16 July 2014</ref> The European side has been pressing for the agreement to include a chapter on the regulation of financial services; but this is being resisted by the American side, which has recently passed the [[Dodd\u2013Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act|Dodd\u2013Frank Act]] in this field.<ref>[http://www.euractiv.com/sections/european-business-summit-2014/eu-us-clash-over-financial-services-ttip-302173 EU-US clash over financial services in TTIP], [[EurActiv]], 15 May 2014</ref> [[United States Ambassador to the European Union|US Ambassador to the European Union]] [[Anthony L. Gardner]] has denied any linkage between the two issues.<ref>[http://www.euractiv.com/sections/trade-industry/us-ambassador-eu-anthony-l-gardner-beyond-growth-ttip-must-happen US Ambassador: Beyond growth, TTIP must happen for geostrategic reasons], [[EurActiv]], 16 July 2014</ref>\n\nEuropean negotiators are also pressing the United States to loosen [[Energy policy of the United States|its restrictions]] on the export of crude oil and natural gas, to help the EU reduce its dependence on energy from Russia.<ref>Zach Carter and Kate Sheppard, [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/05/19/trade-fracking_n_5340420.html Read The Secret Trade Memo Calling For More Fracking and Offshore Drilling], ''Huffington Post'', 19 May 2014<br />Lidia Pillis, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/wonkblog/wp/2014/07/08/could-a-trade-deal-lift-the-u-s-longstanding-ban-on-crude-oil-exports-europe-thinks-so/ A leaked document shows just how much the EU wants a piece of America\u2019s fracking boom], ''Washington Post'', 8 July 2014<br />David J. Unger, [http://www.csmonitor.com/Environment/Energy-Voices/2014/0715/Europe-at-TTIP-talks-Open-the-US-energy-spigot Europe at TTIP talks: Open the US energy spigot], ''Christian Science Monitor'', 15 July 2014</ref>\n\n===Response to criticism===\n[[Karel De Gucht]] responded to criticism in a ''Guardian'' article in December 2013,<ref>The Guardian (2 December 2013) [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/dec/02/transatlantic-free-trade-deal-regulation-by-lawyers-eu-us The lies behind this transatlantic trade deal] Retrieved 1 January 2015.</ref> saying \"The commission has regularly consulted a broad range of civil society organisations in writing and in person, and our most recent meeting had 350 participants from trade unions, NGOs and business\" and that \"no agreement will become law before it is thoroughly examined and signed off by the European parliament and 29 democratically elected national governments \u2013 the US government and 28 in the EU's council\"<ref>The Guardian (18 December 2013) [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/dec/18/wrong-george-monbiot-nothing-secret-eu-trade-deal You're wrong, George Monbiot \u2013 there is nothing secret about this EU trade deal] Retrieved 2 February 2014.</ref> However, the [[Corporate Europe Observatory]] (cited in the original ''Guardian'' article) had pointed out, based on a [[Freedom of Information]] request, that \"more than 93% of the Commission's meetings with stakeholders during the preparations of the negotiations were with big business\". They characterized the industry meetings as \"about the EU's preparations of the trade talks\", and the civil society consultation as \"an information session after the talks were launched\".<ref>Corporate Europe Observatory (4 September 2013) [http://corporateeurope.org/trade/2013/09/european-commission-preparing-eu-us-trade-talks-119-meetings-industry-lobbyists European Commission preparing for EU-US trade talks] Retrieved 14 April 2015.</ref>\n\n== Effect on third-party countries ==\n[[File:Transatlantic Free Trade Area.svg|thumb|A possible future Transatlantic Free Trade Area: <br />the United States and European Union in dark blue and the other possible members in light blue ([[NAFTA]] and [[EFTA]])]]\n\nLooking beyond TTIP, a wider \"transatlantic free trade area\" has been postulated.{{by whom|date=April 2016}}{{citation needed|date=April 2016}} This might include, on the American side, the other members of [[North American Free Trade Area]] (Canada and Mexico); and on the European side, the members of the [[European Free Trade Association]] (Iceland, Norway, Switzerland and Liechtenstein). Mexico already has a free trade agreement with EFTA [[Free Trade Agreement between Mexico and the European Union|and the EU]] while [[Canada\u2013European Free Trade Association Free Trade Agreement|Canada has one with EFTA]] and has [[Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement|negotiated one with the EU]]. These agreements may need to be harmonized with the EU-US agreement and could potentially form a wider free trade area.\n\nIn early 2013, Canadian media observers had speculated that the launch of TTIP talks put pressure on Canada to secure ratification of its own three-year-long FTA negotiations with the EU by the close of 2013.<ref>{{cite news|author=Barrie Mckenna And Bertrand Marotte |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/international-business/potential-us-eu-free-trade-union-puts-the-squeeze-on-canada/article8592389/ |title=Potential US-EU free-trade union 'puts the squeeze' on Canada |publisher=The Globe and Mail |date=13 February 2013 |accessdate=2014-02-21 |location=Toronto}}</ref> Countries with customs agreements with the EU, [[European Union\u2013Turkey Customs Union|like Turkey's]], could face the prospect of opening their markets to American goods, without access for their own goods without a separate agreement with the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/transatlantic-alliance-to-cost-turkey-20-billion.aspx?pageID=238&nid=53844&NewsCatID=344 |title=Transatlantic alliance to cost Turkey '$20&nbsp;billion' \u2013 ECONOMICS |publisher=Hurriyetdailynews.com |date=13 September 2011 |accessdate=2014-02-21}}</ref>\n\n==Reports==\nVarious groups have produced reports about the proposed agreement, including:\n* ''The Politics of Transatlantic Trade Negotiations: TTIP in a Globalized World'' (2015) {{ISBN|9781472443649}}\n* ''The Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership: Ambitious but Achievable \u2013 A Stakeholder Survey and Three Scenarios'' (April 2013)  {{ISBN|978-1-61977-032-4}}<ref name=Stakeholder>{{cite web|title=The Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership: Ambitious but Achievable \u2013 A Stakeholder Survey and Three Scenarios|url=http://www.bertelsmann-stiftung.de/cps/rde/xbcr/SID-4C33D168-3FA15517/bst/xcms_bst_dms_37655_37656_2.pdf|publisher=[[Atlantic Council]], [[Bertelsmann Foundation]]|accessdate=18 May 2014}}</ref>\n* ''TTIP and the Fifty States: Jobs and Growth from Coast to Coast'' (September 2013) {{ISBN|978-1-61977-038-6}}<ref name=CoastToCoast>{{cite web|title=TTIP and the Fifty States: Jobs and Growth from Coast to Coast|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/245085/TTIP_and_the_50_States_GovUK.pdf|publisher=Atlantic Council, Bertelmanns Foundation|accessdate=18 May 2014}}</ref>\n* ''The Transatlantic Colossus: Global Contributions to Broaden the Debate on the EU-US Free Trade Agreement'' (December 2013) {{ISBN|978-3-00-044648-1}}<ref name=TransatlColoss>{{cite web|title=The Transatlantic Colossus: Global Contributions to Broaden the Debate on the EU-US Free Trade Agreement|url=http://bfogp.org/publications/the-transatlantic-colossus/|author=Berlin Forum on Global Politics, Internet & Society Collaboratory, FutureChallenges.org|accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref>\n* ''The Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership: A Charter for Deregulation, An Attack on Jobs, An End to Democracy'' (February 2014)<ref name=Charterforderegulation>{{cite web|title=A Charter for Deregulation, An Attack on Jobs, An End to Democracy|url=http://rosalux.gr/sites/default/files/publications/ttip_web.pdf\n|publisher=Rosa Luxemburg Stiftung, Brussels Office|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Anti-Counterfeiting Trade Agreement]] (ACTA)\n* [[Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement]] (CETA)\n* [[Copyright infringement]]\n* [[Digital rights]]\n* [[European Union free trade agreements]]\n* [[Investor-state dispute settlement]]\n* [[Trade in Services Agreement]] (TISA)\n* [[Trans-Pacific Partnership]] (TPP)\n* [[Transatlantic Free Trade Area]]\n* [[United States\u2013European Union relations]]\n* [[United States free trade agreements]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=guardian22may15>{{cite web|title=EU dropped pesticide laws due to US pressure over TTIP, documents reveal|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2015/may/22/eu-dropped-pesticide-laws-due-to-us-pressure-over-ttip-documents-reveal#comments|publisher=Guardian|accessdate=22 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"guard 3 Aug 2015\">{{cite web |last= Jeffries |first= Stuart |date= 3 August 2015 |title= What is TTIP and why should we be angry about it? |url= https://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/aug/03/ttip-what-why-angry-transatlantic-trade-investment-partnership-guide |website= theguardian.com |accessdate= 23 February 2016 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Stop TTIP\">{{cite web|url=https://stop-ttip.org/|title=Do the CETA-CHECK!|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"theguardian.com 27 August 2016\">Jennifer Rankin. [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/aug/27/cecilia-malmstrom-swedish-politician-play-hardball-with-uk-on-brexit Meet the Swedish politician ready to play hardball with the UK on Brexit]. [[theguardian.com]]. 27 August 2016.</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.dw.de/ttip-mega-marriage-facing-hurdles/av-17863865 What exactly is the Trans Atlantic Trade and Investment Partnership?] Video produced by DW ([[Deutsche Welle]])\n\n=== Official sites ===\n* [http://ec.europa.eu/trade/policy/countries-and-regions/countries/united-states/ EU negotiations site]\n* [http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/press/index.cfm?id=1230 EU negotiating texts in TTIP]\n* [http://ec.europa.eu/trade/policy/in-focus/ttip/ European Commission, DG Trade \u2013 In focus Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP)]\n* [http://www.ustr.gov/TTIP/ USTR Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership]\n\n=== Discussion and analysis ===\n* [https://www.routledge.com/The-Politics-of-Transatlantic-Trade-Negotiations-TTIP-in-a-Globalized/Morin-Novotna-Ponjaert-Telo/p/book/9781472443649 The Politics of Transatlantic Trade Negotiations], by Jean-Frederic Morin, Tereza Novotna, Frederik Ponjaert and Mario Tel\u00f2, Routledge, 2015\n* [http://epthinktank.eu/2014/07/11/towards-an-eu-us-trade-and-investment-deal-2/ Towards an EU-US trade and investment deal], [[European Parliament]]ary Research Service, 11 July 2014\n* [https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld201314/ldselect/ldeucom/179/17902.htm The Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership], UK [[House of Lords]] European Union Committee report, 6 May 2014\n* [http://bfogp.org/publications/the-transatlantic-colossus/ The Transatlantic Colossus: Global Contributions to Broaden the Debate on the EU-US Free Trade Agreement] ''A collaborative publication with over 20 articles on the global implications of the TAFTA | TTIP'', Berlin Forum on Global Politics, December 2013\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_iVuEo23LPw The Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership \u2013 Defensive Move or Constructive Engagement] ''A Research Based Documentary placing the TTIP negotiations in a global context produced by the Institut d'Etudes Europ\u00e9ennes of the Universit\u00e9 Libre de Bruxelles'', 19 March 2014\n* [http://rosalux.gr/sites/default/files/publications/ttip_web.pdf/ The Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership: A Charter for Deregulation, an Attack on Jobs, an End to Democracy], Rosa Luxemburg Stiftung, Brussels Office, February 2014\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140819084540/http://www.rosalux-europa.info/userfiles/file/FreeTrade_UHerrmann.pdf /  Free Trade: Project of the Powerful], Rosa Luxemburg Stiftung, Brussels Office, May 2014\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150402222823/http://katapult-magazin.de/en/artikel/article-katapult/fulltext/politics-at-a-standstill/ /  Politics at a standstill], Katapult Magazine, 11. March 2014\n* [http://www.cepr.net/documents/TTIP-brief-08-2015.pdf TTIP: Are 40 Cents a Day Big Gains?], [[Center for Economic and Policy Research]], August 2015\n\n=== Websites ===\n* [http://www.atlanticcouncil.org/blogs/ttipaction/ TTIP Action] ([[Atlantic Council]])\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140715180614/http://ttip2014.eu/ TTIP: What lies beneath] (European Parliament [[The Greens\u2013European Free Alliance|Greens/EFA]] Group)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140321190740/http://www.amchameu.eu/TTIP/tabid/400/Default.aspx TTIP] ([[American Chamber of Commerce to the European Union]])\n* [http://www.citizen.org/Page.aspx?pid=6037 The Trans-Atlantic \"Free Trade\" Agreement (TAFTA)] ([[Public Citizen]]) (USA)\n* [http://www.businesseurope.eu/Content/Default.asp?PageID=867 Did you say TTIP?] ([[Confederation of European Business]])\n* [http://www.nottip.org.uk/ No TTIP] (UK umbrella organisation)\n* [http://tradeinvest.babinc.org/eu-us-trade/ EU/US Trade & Investment] (British American Business) \u2013 backers of the UK [[All Party Parliamentary Group]] for EU-US Trade & Investment\n* [http://www.ttip-leaks.org/ TTIP Leaks] (TTIP negotiation documents)\n\n{{Free trade agreements of the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|European Union|United States|Politics|Economy}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Transatlantic Trade And Investment Partnership}}\n[[Category:United States diplomacy]]\n[[Category:Economy of North America]]\n[[Category:Economy of Europe]]\n[[Category:2013 in the United States]]\n[[Category:2013 in the European Union]]\n[[Category:Transatlantic relations]]\n[[Category:Presidency of Barack Obama]]\n[[Category:United States\u2013European Union relations]]\n[[Category:Free trade agreements of the United States]]\n[[Category:Proposed treaties]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the regulation and trade agreement|the chemical compound abbreviated as TTIP|Titanium isopropoxide}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox treaty\n| name = Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership\n| long_name =\n| image =[[File:European Union United States Locator.svg|frameless|upright=1.15]]\n| caption = The [[United States]] (orange) and the [[European Union]] (green)\n| type = [[Trade agreement]]\n| date_drafted =  \n| date_signed = No\n| location_signed = \n| date_sealed =\n| date_effective = \n| condition_effective = \n| date_expiration =\n| original_signatories=\n| parties = \n| ratifiers =\n| depositor =\n| languages = \n| wikisource =\n}}\n\nThe '''Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership''' ('''TTIP''') is a proposed [[trade agreement]] between the [[European Union]] and the [[United States]], with the aim of promoting trade and multilateral economic growth. According to [[Karel de Gucht]], European Commissioner for Trade between 2010 and 2014, the TTIP is the largest bilateral trade initiative ever negotiated, not only because it involves the two largest economies in the world but also \"because of its potential global reach in setting an example for future partners and agreements\".<ref>Karel de Gucht, ''Foreword'' in Jean-Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Morin, Tereza Novotn\u00e1, Frederik Ponjaert and Mario Tel\u00f2, ''The Politics of Transatlantic Trade Negotiations, TTIP in a Globalized World'', Routledge, 2015, p.xvii</ref>\n\nNegotiations were halted by President Donald Trump,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/26/world/europe/donald-trump-us-eu-trade.html|title=Europe Averts a Trade War With Trump. But Can It Trust Him?|publisher=|accessdate=28 July 2018}}</ref> who then initiated a trade conflict with the EU. Trump and the EU declared a truce of sorts in July 2018, resuming talks that appeared similar to TTIP.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/26/us/politics/trump-trade-european-union.html|title=Trump's Trade Truce With Europe Has a Familiar Feel: It Mirrors Obama's Path|publisher=|accessdate=28 July 2018}}</ref> On 15 April 2019, the negotiations have been declared \"obsolete and no longer relevant\" by the European Commission.<ref>{{cite web |last1=European Commission |title=Negotiations and Agreements: Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership |url=https://ec.europa.eu/trade/policy/in-focus/ttip/index_en.htm}}</ref>\n\nThe reports on the ongoing negotiations and the contents of the negotiated TTIP proposals are [[classified information|classified]] from the public, and can be accessed only by authorised persons.<ref name=\"Independent 14 August 2015\"/> Multiple [[News leak|leaks]] of proposed TTIP contents into the public caused controversy.<ref>Arthur Neslen. [https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/may/01/leaked-ttip-documents-cast-doubt-on-eu-us-trade-deal Leaked TTIP documents cast doubt on EU-US trade deal]. [[theguardian.com]]. 1 May 2016.</ref>\n\nThe [[European Commission]] says that the TTIP would boost the EU's economy by \u20ac120&nbsp;billion, the US economy by \u20ac90&nbsp;billion and the rest of the world by \u20ac100&nbsp;billion.<ref name=\"EU-ttip\"/> According to Anu Bradford, law professor at [[Columbia Law School]], and Thomas J. Bollyky of the [[Council on Foreign Relations]], TTIP aims to \"liberalise one-third of global trade\" and could create millions of new jobs.<ref name=\"Bollyky Foreign Affairs\"/> A ''[[The Guardian|Guardian]]'' article by [[Dean Baker]] of the US thinktank [[Center for Economic and Policy Research]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rosenberg|first1=Tina|title=The Perils of Petrocracy|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/04/magazine/04oil-t.html?pagewanted=7|accessdate=5 October 2014|work=[[New York Times]]|date=4 November 2007|quote= \u2026 Mark Weisbrot, co-director of the Center for Economic and Policy Research, a left-leaning Washington policy group.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Sussman|first1=Anna Louie|title=Are Women the New Face of Organized Labor?|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/economics/2015/09/07/are-women-the-new-face-of-organized-labor/|accessdate=20 September 2015|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=7 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Fox|first1=Maggie|title=Obamacare won't slash workers' hours, report finds|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-care/obamacare-wont-slash-workers-hours-report-finds-f6C10732487|accessdate=31 October 2014|agency=NBC News|date=24 July 2013}}</ref> argued that the economic benefits per household would be relatively small.<ref name=\"guardian July 15, 2013\"/> According to a [[European Parliament]] report, impacts on labour conditions range from job gains to job losses, depending on economic model and assumptions used for predictions.<ref name=\"EP Kraatz\">Susanne Kraatz. [http://www.europarl.europa.eu/RegData/etudes/BRIE/2014/536315/IPOL_BRI(2014)536315_EN.pdf The Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP) and Labour]. [[European Parliament]].</ref>\n\nThe agreement has been criticized and opposed by some [[Trade union|unions]], charities, [[Non-governmental organization|NGOs]] and environmentalists, particularly in Europe.<ref name=\"guardian August 3, 2015\">Stuart Jeffries. [https://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/aug/03/ttip-what-why-angry-transatlantic-trade-investment-partnership-guide What is TTIP and why should we be angry about it?]. [[theguardian.com]]. Published on 3 August 2015.</ref><ref name=\"The Daily Beast\"/> ''[[The Independent]]'' describes common criticisms of TTIP as \"reducing the regulatory barriers to trade for [[big business]], things like [[food safety]] law, [[Environmental law|environmental legislation]], [[Bank regulation|banking regulations]] and the sovereign powers of individual nations\",<ref name=\"The Independent October 6, 2015\"/> or more critically as an \"assault on European and US societies by transnational corporations\".<ref name=\"The Independent October 6, 2015\"/> ''[[The Guardian]]'' noted the criticism of TTIP's \"undemocratic nature of the closed-door talks\", \"influence of powerful lobbyists\", TTIP's potential ability to \"undermine the democratic authority of local government\",<ref name=\"guardian August 5, 2015\">Tim Smedley. [https://www.theguardian.com/public-leaders-network/2015/aug/05/ttip-free-trade-deal-renewable-energy-transatlantic-partnership-eu-us TTIP: what does the transatlantic trade deal mean for renewable energy?]. [[theguardian.com]]. 5 August 2015.</ref> and described it as \"the most controversial trade deal the EU has ever negotiated\".<ref name=\"theguardian.com 27 August 2016\"/> German economist [[Max Otte]] argued that by putting European workers into direct competition with Americans (and in effect, because of the [[North American Free Trade Agreement]], with Mexicans and Canadians), TTIP would negatively impact the [[European social model]]s.<ref name=\"heute April 8, 2016\"/> An EU [[direct democracy]] mechanism, the [[European Citizens' Initiative]], which enables EU citizens to call directly on the [[European Commission]] to propose a legal act,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/citizens-initiative/public/welcome|title=Homepage \u2013 European Citizens' Initiative \u2013 European Commission|publisher=}}</ref> acquired over 3.2&nbsp;million signatures against TTIP and [[Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement|CETA]] within a year.<ref name=\"guard 3 Aug 2015\" /><ref name=\"Stop TTIP\"/>\n\n==Background==\nEconomic barriers between the EU and the United States are relatively low, not only due to long-standing membership in the [[World Trade Organization]] (WTO) but also recent agreements such as the [[EU\u2013US Open Skies Agreement]] and work by the [[Transatlantic Economic Council]]. The [[European Commission]] claims that passage of a trans-Atlantic trade pact could boost overall trade between the respective blocs by as much as 50%.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/europe/21565973-after-barack-obamas-re-election-it-time-push-transatlantic-free-trade-hope-and-no|accessdate=18 March 2013|title=Hope and no change, After Barack Obama's re-election, it is time to push for transatlantic free trade|publisher=Economist.com|date=10 November 2012}}</ref> Economic gains from a Trade Treaty were predicted in the joint report issued by the [[White House]] and the [[European Commission]].<ref>{{cite web|work=European Commission|accessdate=18 March 2013|url=http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/docs/2013/february/tradoc_150519.pdf|title=Final Report High Level Working Group on Jobs and Growth}}</ref>\n\nSome form of [[Transatlantic Free Trade Area]] had been proposed in the 1990s and later in 2006 by [[Chancellor of Germany (1949\u2013)|German Chancellor]] [[Angela Merkel]] in reaction to the collapse of the [[Doha Development Round|Doha]] world trade talks. However, [[protectionism]] on both sides may be a barrier to any future agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/0,1518,440335,00.html |title=Trans-Atlantic Free Trade?: Merkel for EU Agreement with US \u2013 SPIEGEL ONLINE |publisher=Spiegel.de |date=2 October 2006 |accessdate=2014-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ecipe.org/blog/a-transatlantic-free-trade-area|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100116094133/http://www.ecipe.org/blog/a-transatlantic-free-trade-area|title=A Transatlantic Free Trade Area?|archivedate=16 January 2010|work=ecipe.org}}</ref> It was first initiated in 1990, when, shortly after the end of the [[Cold War]], with the world no longer divided into two blocs, the [[European Community]] (12 countries) and the US signed a \"Transatlantic Declaration\". This called for the continued existence of the [[North Atlantic Treaty Organization]], as well as for yearly summits, biannual meetings between ministers of State, and more frequent encounters between political figures and senior officials.\n\nSubsequent initiatives taken by the European deciders and the US government included: in 1995, the creation of a pressure group of business people, the [[Transatlantic Business Dialogue]] (TABD) by public authorities on both sides of the Atlantic; in 1998, the creation of an advisory committee, the Transatlantic Economic Partnership; in 2007, the creation of the [[Transatlantic Economic Council]], in which representatives from firms operating on both sides of the Atlantic meet to advise the European Commission and the US government \u2013 and finally, in 2011, the creation of a group of high-level experts whose conclusions, submitted on 11 February 2013, recommended the launching of negotiations for a wide-ranging free-trade agreement. On 12 February 2013, President [[Barack Obama]] called in his annual [[State of the Union]] address for such an agreement.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/02/14/business/global/obama-pledges-trade-pact-talks-with-eu.html|title=A Running Start for a U.S.-Europe Trade Pact|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=2014-02-21|first1=James|last1=Kanter|first2=Jack|last2=Ewing|date=13 February 2013}}</ref> The following day, [[EU Commission]] [[European Commission President|President]] [[Jose Manuel Barroso]] announced that talks would take place to negotiate the agreement.<ref>{{cite news|author=Andrew Walker |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-21439945 |title=BBC News \u2013 EU and US free-trade talks launched |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=13 February 2013 |accessdate=2014-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Blenkinsop |first=Philip |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/02/13/us-eu-us-trade-idUSBRE91C0OC20130213 |title=EU, U.S. to start free trade talks |publisher=Reuters |date= 13 February 2013|accessdate=2014-02-21}}</ref>\n\nThe United States and European Union together represent 60% of global GDP, 33% of world trade in goods and 42% of world trade in services. There are a number of trade conflicts between the two powers, but both depend on the other's economic market and disputes only affect 2% of total trade. A free trade area between the two would represent potentially the largest regional free-trade agreement in history, covering 46% of [[world GDP]].<ref name=\"imfgdp-world-eu\">{{cite web |url=http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/weo/2013/02/weodata/weorept.aspx?pr.x=33&pr.y=11&sy=2012&ey=2012&scsm=1&ssd=1&sort=country&ds=.&br=1&c=001%2C998&s=NGDPD&grp=1&a=1 |title=Nominal 2012 GDP for the world and the European Union (EU). |accessdate=2013-10-08 |work=World Economic Outlook Database | date=October 2013 |publisher=[[International Monetary Fund]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/trade/creating-opportunities/bilateral-relations/countries/united-states/ |title=European Commission |publisher=Ec.europa.eu |date= |accessdate=25 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Trade between the EU and the US<br>(in billion euros){{Citation needed|date=May 2015}}{{When|date=May 2015}}\n|-\n! Direction\n! Goods\n! Services\n! Investment\n! Total\n|-\n! EU to US\n| 288\n| 159\n| 1655\n| 2102\n|-\n! US to EU\n| 196\n| 146\n| 1536\n| 1878\n|}\n\nThe United States investment in the European Union is three times greater than US investment in the entire continent of Asia and EU investment in the United States is eight times that of European Union investment in India and China combined. Intra-company transfers are estimated to constitute a third of all transatlantic trade. The United States and European Union are the largest trading partners of most other countries in the world and account for a third of world trade flows. Given the already low tariff barriers (under 3%), to make the deal a success the aim is to remove [[Non-tariff barriers to trade|non-tariff barriers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/trade/policy/countries-and-regions/countries/united-states/ |title=United States \u2013 Trade \u2013 European Commission |publisher=Ec.europa.eu |date= |accessdate=2014-02-21}}</ref>\n\n==Proposed contents==\nDocuments released by the European Commission in July 2014 group the topics under discussion into three broad areas: Market access; Specific regulation; and broader rules and principles and modes of co-operation.<ref name=\"eu state of play\">[http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/html/152666.htm State of Play of TTIP negotiations ahead of the 6th round of negotiations], European Commission DG Trade, 11 July 2014</ref><ref name=\"negotiators\">[http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/html/151668.htm List of lead negotiators for the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership], European Commission DG Trade<p>[http://www.ustr.gov/sites/default/files/lead%20negotiators%20list%20TTIP.pdf List of lead negotiators for the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership], Office of the United States Trade Representative</ref>\n\nThe EU negotiating mandate as of June 2013 gave a fuller view of what the [[Council of the European Union]] ([[Foreign Affairs Council|Foreign Affairs]]) has told its negotiators to try to achieve for each section.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eu-secretdeals.info/upload/TTIP-mandate_M-Schaake_website.pdf|title=Secret Global Affairs \u2013 Search Enabled Priority|website=eu-secretdeals.info|accessdate=28 July 2018}}</ref> No corresponding US text is available, but the American side has released a public statement setting out its objectives and the potential benefits it foresees.<ref>[http://www.ustr.gov/about-us/press-office/press-releases/2014/March/US-Objectives-US-Benefits-In-the-TTIP-a-Detailed-View U.S. Objectives, U.S. Benefits In the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership: A Detailed View] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140719050519/http://www.ustr.gov/about-us/press-office/press-releases/2014/March/US-Objectives-US-Benefits-In-the-TTIP-a-Detailed-View |date=19 July 2014 }}, Office of the [[United States Trade Representative]], March 2014</ref>\n\nThe secret contents of the first concrete American proposal on tariff reduction, and an EU counterproposal, which was leaked to [[Correctiv]] in February 2016, suggest 87.5% to 97% of all tariffs would be cut to zero.<ref>{{cite web|title = TTIP: EU offered 97% cut on US tariffs, secret papers show|url = https://euobserver.com/economic/132376|website = EUobserver|access-date = 23 February 2016|date = 22 February 2016|last = von Daniels|first = Justus|last2 = Orosz|first2 = Marta}}</ref>\n\n=== Market access ===\n{{see also|Non-tariff barriers to trade}}\nTTIP includes chapters on market access for goods and services that aim to remove \"custom duties on goods and restrictions on services, gaining better access to public markets, and making it easier to invest\".<ref name=\"TTIP explained\">[http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/html/152462.htm The Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP) explained], European Commission DG Trade, 8 May 2014</ref> The goods part includes rules on [[market access]] for goods, agriculture and processed agricultural products, and [[rules of origin]].<ref name=\"eu state of play\" /><ref name=\"negotiators\" />\n\n====Services and leaked text====\n{{See also|Public services|Bank regulation|Regulatory taking|Investor-state dispute settlement}}\n\nFor \"Trade in Services, Investment and E-commerce\", a draft text dated 7 July 2013 was leaked by the German newspaper, ''[[Die Zeit]]'' in March 2014. The leaked text contains seven chapters. In Chapter 1, Article 1 states the overall objective of \"a better climate for the development of trade and investment\", particularly the \"[[liberalisation]] of investment and cooperation on e-commerce\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://keionline.org/sites/default/files/eu-kommission-position-in-den.pdf|title=TTIP Draft (02/07/2013) article 1|publisher=Keionline.org|accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref>\n\nChapter II, Article 3 to Article 18 contains general principles for investment. Article 14 contains proposed rules that forbid governments to \"directly or indirectly [[nationalise]], [[expropriate]]\" unless it is for a public purpose, under due process of law, on a non-discriminatory basis, with compensation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://keionline.org/sites/default/files/eu-kommission-position-in-den.pdf|title=TTIP Draft (02/07/2013) article 14(1)|publisher=Keionline.org|accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref> Article 14(2) defines the necessary compensation as being \"fair market value of the investment at the time immediately before the expropriation or the impending expropriation became public knowledge plus [[compound interest|interest at a commercial rate]] established on a market basis\".\n\nChapter III, Articles 19 to 23 contains rules on cross border supply of services.\n\nChapter IV, Articles 24 to 28 would allow free movement of business managers, and other employees of a corporation, for temporary work purposes among all countries party to the agreement.<ref name=\"TTIP Draft, articles 24-28\">{{cite web|url=http://keionline.org/sites/default/files/eu-kommission-position-in-den.pdf |title=TTIP Draft, articles 24\u201328|publisher=Keionline.org|accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref> Article 1(2) makes it clear, however, that no more general free movement of workers and citizens is allowed.\n\nChapter V contains eight sections with particular rules for different economic sectors. Section I, articles 29 to 31, set out principles that states must follow in licensing private corporations, and state that requirements that are not proportionate to a reviewable public policy objective are contrary to the treaty. Section II contains general provisions. Section III covers computer services. Section IV, articles 35 to 39, cover liberalisation of [[postal service]]s.<ref name=\"TTIP Draft, articles 35-39\">{{cite web|url=http://keionline.org/sites/default/files/eu-kommission-position-in-den.pdf|title=TTIP Draft, articles 35\u201339|publisher=Keionline.org|accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref> Section V, articles 40 to 50, apply to electronic communications networks and services (including telecommunications) and mandate competitive markets, absence of cross-subsidies, subject to defined exceptions including in article 46 a right (but not a requirement) for countries to provide [[universal service]].\n\nSection VI of chapter V covers Financial Services, in articles 51 to 59. It limits the laws that governments can pass to regulate or publicly run insurance and banking. Any regulations that do not fall within the Treaty's terms and objectives would be unlawful.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://keionline.org/sites/default/files/eu-kommission-position-in-den.pdf|title=TTIP Draft (02/07/2013) articles 51\u201359|publisher=Keionline.org|accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref> Legitimate reasons for regulation include, in article 52, \"the protection of investors, depositors, policy-holders or persons to whom a [[fiduciary duty]] is owed by a financial service supplier; (b) ensuring the integrity and stability of a Party's financial system\". However article 52(2) states \"measures shall not be more burdensome than necessary to achieve their aim\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://keionline.org/sites/default/files/eu-kommission-position-in-den.pdf|title=TTIP Draft (02/07/2013) art 52(2)|publisher=Keionline.org|accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref> and the Treaty does not include any further reasons to allow regulation. Section VII covers international maritime transport and section VIII covers air transport.\n\nThe Annex on \"[[Investor-state dispute settlement|Investors-state dispute settlement]]\" proposed to allow corporations to bring actions against governments for breach of its rights.<ref name=\"keionline.org\">{{cite web|url=http://keionline.org/sites/default/files/eu-kommission-position-in-den.pdf|title=TTIP Draft, \"Negotiations on Investor-State Dispute Settlement\"|publisher=Keionline.org|accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref> The European Commission launched a public consultation after the draft text was leaked, which led to a number of changes. However, an updated proposed text had yet to be made publicly available.{{when|date=July 2015}} In September 2015, the Commission proposed an \"Investment Court System\" to replace the ISDS clauses, with the scope for investor challenge much reduced and with \"highly skilled judges\" rather than arbitrators used to determine cases.<ref>{{cite web|title = Commission proposes new Investment Court System for TTIP and other EU trade and investment negotiations | url = http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-15-5651_en.htm | work = The European Commission| date = 16 September 2015 | accessdate = 25 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Industry-specific regulation===\n\"Improved regulatory coherence and cooperation by dismantling unnecessary regulatory barriers such as bureaucratic duplication of effort\".<ref name=\"TTIP explained\" />\n\nSpecific heads for discussion include:<ref name=\"eu state of play\" /><ref name=\"negotiators\" />\n* Horizontal chapters:\n** Regulatory coherence<ref>{{cite web|url=http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/html/151622.htm |title=TTIP Initial EU position paper \u2013 Cross-cutting |publisher=Trade.ec.europa.eu |date= |accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref><ref>[http://corporateeurope.org/sites/default/files/ttip-regulatory-coherence-2-12-2013.pdf Subsequent more detailed EU position paper], leaked December 2013</ref>\n** [[Technical barriers to trade]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/html/151627.htm |title=TTIP position paper on technical barriers |publisher=Trade.ec.europa.eu |date= |accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref>\n* Specific sectoral agreements:\n** [[Textile industry|Textiles]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/html/152469.htm |title=EU TTIP position on textiles |publisher=Trade.ec.europa.eu |date= |accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref>\n** [[Chemical industry|Chemicals]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/html/152468.htm |title=EU TTIP position \u2013 chemicals, May 14 |publisher=Trade.ec.europa.eu |date= |accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref>\n** [[Pharmaceutical industry|Pharmaceuticals]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/html/152471.htm |title=EU TTIP position on pharma \u2013 TTIP |publisher=Trade.ec.europa.eu |date= |accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref>\n** Cosmetics<ref>{{cite web|url=http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/html/152470.htm |title=EU TTIP initial position on cosmetics |publisher=Trade.ec.europa.eu |date= |accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref>\n** [[Medical device]]s\n** [[Automotive industry|Cars]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/html/152467.htm |title=EU TTIP position on vehicles |publisher=Trade.ec.europa.eu |date= |accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref>\n** Electronics and information technology\n** Machinery and engineering\n** [[Pesticides]]\n** [[Sanitary and phytosanitary measures and agreements|Sanitary and phytosanitary measures]] (SPS)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/html/151625.htm |title=TTIP position initiale \u2013 mesures sanitaires et phytosanitaires |publisher=Trade.ec.europa.eu |date= |accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref>\u2014i.e., barriers to trade in food and agricultural products\n\n===Broader rules and principles and modes of co-operation===\n\"Improved cooperation when it comes to setting international standards\".<ref name=\"TTIP explained\" />\n\nSpecific heads for discussion include:<ref name=\"eu state of play\" /><ref name=\"negotiators\" />\n* Energy and raw materials<ref>[http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/html/151624.htm Initial EU position on raw materials and energy], 16 July 2013</ref><ref>[http://eu-secretdeals.info/upload/2014/02/TTIPNonPaper-Energy-Sept2013-HuffingtonPost-Leak.pdf Leaked EU illustrative text] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140706003227/http://eu-secretdeals.info/upload/2014/02/TTIPNonPaper-Energy-Sept2013-HuffingtonPost-Leak.pdf |date=6 July 2014 }}, 20 September 2013. Leaked 19 May 2014</ref>\n* Trade and Sustainable Development / Labour and Environment<ref>{{cite web|url=http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/html/151626.htm |title=TTIP Position paper on sustainable development |publisher=Trade.ec.europa.eu |date= |accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref>\n* [[Public procurement]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/html/151623.htm |title=TTIP Initial EU position paper: public procurement |publisher=Trade.ec.europa.eu |date= |accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref>\n* Intellectual property<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://keionline.org/node/1984 |title=Leaked EU analysis of TTIP IPR negotiations &#124; Knowledge Ecology International |publisher=Keionline.org |date=20 March 2014 |accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref>\n** [[Geographical indications]]\n* [[Competition policy]]: [[antitrust]] and [[mergers]]\n** Treatment of state-owned or subsidised companies vis-a-vis private companies\n* [[Small and medium-sized enterprises]] (SMEs)\n* Trade remedies: e.g., [[Dumping (pricing policy)|anti-dumping]] practices\n* Customs and [[Trade Facilitation]]\n\n===Implementation===\n* Dispute settlement (between the parties, not [[investor-state dispute settlement]])\n\n==Negotiations==\n\n===Procedure===\nThe TTIP Agreement texts are being developed by 24 joint EU-US working groups, each considering a separate aspect of the agreement.  Development typically progresses through a number of phases.  Broad ''position paper''s are first exchanged, introducing each side's aims and ambitions for each aspect.  These are followed by ''textual proposals'' from each side, accompanied (in areas such as tariffs, and market access) by each side's \"initial offer.\" These negotiations and draft documents can evolve (change) through the various stages of their development. When both sides are ready, a ''consolidated text'' is prepared, with remaining differences for discussion expressed in square brackets. These texts are then provisionally closed topic by topic as a working consensus is reached.  However the agreement is negotiated as a whole, so no topic's text is finalised until full consensus is reached.<ref>[http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/press/index.cfm?id=1126 Commission publishes state of play of TTIP negotiations ahead of 6th round of talks], European Commission DG Trade, 11 July 2014</ref>\n\n===Negotiation rounds===\nNegotiations are held in week-long cycles alternating between Brussels and the USA.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ec.europa.eu/trade/policy/in-focus/ttip/documents-and-events/index_en.htm#negotiation-rounds |title=Documents and events \u2013 Negotiation rounds |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website= |publisher= [[European Commission|EU Commission]] |accessdate= 4 August 2015}}</ref> The negotiators were hoping to conclude their work by the end of 2016.<ref name=\"trade.ec.europa.eu\">{{cite web|url=http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/docs/2016/april/tradoc_154477.pdf |title=The Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP) State of Play |date= |accessdate=2016-11-22}}</ref>\n\n* The 1st round of negotiations: 7\u201312 July 2013 in Washington DC \n* The 2nd round of negotiations: 11\u201315 November 2013 in Brussels \n* The 3rd round of negotiations: 16\u201321 December 2013 in Washington DC \n* The 4th round of negotiations: 10\u201314 March 2014 in Brussels \n* The 5th round of negotiations: 19\u201323 May 2014 in Arlington, Virginia\n* The 6th round of negotiations: 13\u201318 July 2014 in Brussels \n* The 7th round of negotiations: 29 September \u2013 3 October 2014 in Chevy Chase, Maryland\n* The 8th round of negotiations: 2\u20136 February 2015 in Brussels \n* The 9th round of negotiations: 20\u201324 April 2015 in New York \n* The 10th round of negotiations: 13\u201317 July 2015 in Brussels\n* The 11th round of negotiations: 19\u201323 October 2015 in Miami\n* The 12th round of negotiations: 22\u201326 February 2016 in Brussels\n* The 13th round of negotiations: 25\u201329 April 2016 in New York\n* The 14th round of negotiations: 11\u201315 July 2016 in Brussels\n* The 15th round of negotiations: 3\u20137 October 2016 in New York\n\n===Confidentiality measures===\nOnly a few people can access the documents known as \"consolidated texts\", the drafts containing the most recent results of the negotiations. On the European side, authorised readers include the European Commission negotiators (most of them from the [[Directorate-General for Trade (European Commission)|Directorate-General for Trade]]),{{citation needed|date=April 2016}} [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]]s and European Union members' [[Member of Parliament|MP]]s.<ref name=Guardian160218>[https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/feb/18/mps-can-view-ttip-files-but-take-only-pencil-and-paper-with-them MPs can view TTIP files \u2013 but take only pencil and paper with them] {{snd}} [[The Guardian]], 18 February 2016</ref> Upon the insistence of the US, the documents are not transmitted any more as electronic or even printed documents.<ref name=\"Independent 14 August 2015\" />  \nThey are only available in secure rooms at the European Commission HQ in Brussels, in a number of US embassies,<ref name=\"Independent 14 August 2015\" /> and at the offices of member states' trade ministries.<ref name=Guardian160218 /> In all these secured rooms phones or other types of scanning device are forbidden.<ref name=\"Independent 14 August 2015\" /> Blank sheets of paper, marked with the reader's names, are provided on which visitors can jot down their notes.<ref name=Guardian160218 /> \nOn the US side, the procedure is similar: only Senators and [[Office of the United States Trade Representative|USTR]] negotiators may access the documents and must comply with similar conditions.<ref name=\"Independent 14 August 2015\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/ttip-controversy-secret-trade-deal-can-only-be-read-secure-in-reading-room-in-brussels-10456206.html |title=TTIP controversy: Secret trade deal can only be read in secure 'reading room' in Brussels |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website= |publisher= [[The Independent]] |accessdate= 23 September 2015}}</ref> The US side has insisted on the same security arrangements for the drafts of the [[Trans-Pacific Partnership]] proposal.<ref name=\"Independent 14 August 2015\" />\n\n===Hurdles===\nThe negotiations were planned to be finalized by the end of 2014, but according to economist [[Hosuk Lee-Makiyama]], at least another four or five years of negotiations remained at the end of that year.<ref name=\"Reuters Jun 16, 2015\">Philip Blenkinsop. [http://uk.reuters.com/article/us-eu-usa-trade-idUKKBN0OW0UW20150616 EU-U.S. trade deal seems distant dream after early optimism]. [[Reuters]]. 16 June 2015.</ref> In November 2014 the Bulgarian government announced that it will not ratify the agreement unless the United States lifted visa requirements for Bulgarian citizens.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.novinite.com/articles/165030/Bulgaria+Will+Not+Sign+TTIP+Unless+US+Lifts+Visa+Requirements+-+Minister|title=Bulgaria Will Not Sign TTIP Unless US Lifts Visa Requirements \u2013 Minister|work=novinite.com}}</ref>\n\nGerman Vice Chancellor and Economy Minister [[Sigmar Gabriel]] said that free trade talks between the European Union and the United States have failed, citing a lack of progress on any of the major sections of the long-running negotiations. \"In my opinion the negotiations with the United States have de facto failed, even though nobody is really admitting it\" the German broadcaster [[Zweites Deutsches Fernsehen]] quoted the minister, according to a written transcript of an interview aired on 28 August 2016. \"[They] have failed because we Europeans did not want to subject ourselves to American demands.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/611ff828b5ed44d5ad56ab46e0781e52/german-economy-minister-says-eu-us-trade-talks-have-failed\n|title=german-economy-minister-says-eu-us-trade-talks-have-failed}}</ref>\n\n===Negotiation progress===\nNegotiation progress as of 27 April 2016:<ref name=\"trade.ec.europa.eu\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.agra-net.com/agra/agra-europe/policy-and-legislation/trade-policy/commission-publishes-state-of-play-report-on-ttip-513635.htm|title=Commission publishes state-of-play report on TTIP|publisher=}}</ref>\n{|\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0f0;\"|{{nbsp}}\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''<small>No paper yet</small>'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''<small>US/EU Paper</small>'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''<small>EU & US proposals</small>'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''<small>Consolidation underway</small>'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''<small>Advanced state of consolidation</small>'''\n|-\n| <small>[[Agricultural policy|Agricultural Market Access]]</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| ||\n|-\n| <small>[[Political corruption#Opposing corruption|Anti-corruption]]</small>|| style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| ||||||\n|-\n| <small>Competition</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| || style=\"background:#73b539;\"| \n|-\n| <small>Cross-Border Trade in Services</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| ||\n|-\n| <small>Customs and Trade Facilitation</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| || style=\"background:#73b539;\"| \n|-\n| <small>[[E-Commerce]]</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| ||\n|-\n| <small>Energy and [[Raw Materials]]</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| ||||||\n|-\n| <small>[[Financial Services]]</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| ||\n|-\n| <small>Investment Protection</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| ||||\n|-\n| <small>[[Intellectual Property Rights]]</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| ||||\n|-\n| <small>Legal and Institutional</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| ||||||\n|-\n| <small>[[Market access]]/Industrial goods</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| ||\n|-\n| <small>[[Procurement]]</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| ||\n|-\n| <small>Regulatory Coherence</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| ||\n|-\n| <small>Regulatory Cooperation</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| ||\n|-\n| <small>[[Rules of Origin]]</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| ||\n|-\n| <small>[[Small and medium-sized enterprises]]</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| || style=\"background:#73b539;\"| \n|-\n| <small>[[State-Owned Enterprises]]</small>  || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| ||\n|-\n| <small>Sanitary and Phytosanitary Measures</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| ||\n|-\n| <small>State-to-State Dispute [[Settlement (litigation)|Settlement]]</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| || style=\"background:#73b539;\"| \n|-\n| <small>[[Subsidies]]</small>|| style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| ||||||\n|-\n| <small>[[Sustainable development|Sustainable dev.]]: Labour, Environment</small>|| style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| ||||\n|-\n| <small>[[Technical Barriers to Trade]]</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| ||\n|-\n| <small>[[Telecommunications industry|Telecom]]</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| ||\n|-\n| <small>Textiles and [[Apparel]]</small>|| style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| ||||||\n|-\n| <small>Trade Remedies</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| || style=\"background:#b9eb8d;\"| ||\n|-\n| <small>Sectors</small> || style=\"background:#d46058;\"| || style=\"background:#eeaa4e;\"| || style=\"background:#f0df78;\"| ||||\n|-\n| \n|}\n\n==Ratification==\nThe twenty-eight European Union-member governments will have to approve of the partnership, via unanimous voting under TFEU Articles 207 and 218, on the negotiated agreement in the [[Council of the European Union]], at which point the [[European Parliament]] will also be asked for its endorsement. The European Parliament is empowered to approve or reject the agreement. In case the [[Council of the European Union]], following a proposal from the [[European Commission]], designates TTIP to be a \"mixed agreement\", approval from all Parliaments of the EU Member States in accordance with individual constitutional procedures is necessary before the agreement can enter into force. In the United States, both houses of the [[United States Congress|Congress]] will have to pass the agreement for it to be ratified.<ref>Ian F. Fergusson, [https://fas.org/sgp/crs/misc/RL33743.pdf Trade Promotion Authority (TPA) and the Role of Congress in Trade Policy, Congress Research Service ](15 June 2015), p. 9, n.15 (\"Under TPA, reciprocal FTAs and multilateral trade agreements that go beyond tariff reductions are treated as congressional-executive agreements, which require the approval of both houses of Congress. Such approval expresses Congress' consent to bind the United States to the commitments of the agreement under international law. This type of agreement is distinguished from both an [[executive agreement]], requiring only presidential action, and a [[treaty]], requiring a two-thirds vote of the Senate. Because reciprocal trade agreements typically result in tariff rate (revenue) changes, the House of Representatives is necessarily involved.\").</ref>\n\n==Proposed benefits==\nTTIP aims for a formal agreement that would \"liberalize one-third of global trade\" and, proponents argue, will create millions of new paid jobs.<ref name=\"Bollyky Foreign Affairs\">{{cite journal|last=Bollyky|first=Thomas J. and Anu Bradford|title=Getting to Yes on Transatlantic Trade|journal=Foreign Affairs|date=10 July 2013|url=http://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/139569/thomas-j-bollyky-and-anu-bradford/getting-to-yes-on-transatlantic-trade|accessdate=22 July 2013}}</ref> \"With tariffs between the United States and the European Union already low, the London-based [[Centre for Economic Policy Research]] estimates that 80 percent of the potential economic gains from the TTIP agreement depend on reducing the conflicts of duplication between EU and US rules on those and other regulatory issues, ranging from food safety to automobile parts.\"<ref name=\"Bollyky Foreign Affairs\" /> A successful strategy (according to Thomas Bollyky at the [[Council on Foreign Relations]] and Anu Bradford of [[Columbia Law School]]) will focus on business sectors for which transatlantic trade laws and local regulations can often overlap, e.g., pharmaceutical, agricultural, and financial trading.<ref name=\"Bollyky Foreign Affairs\" /> This will ensure that the United States and Europe remain \"standard makers, rather than standard takers\", in the global economy, subsequently ensuring that producers worldwide continue to gravitate toward joint US-EU standards.<ref name=\"Bollyky Foreign Affairs\" />\n\nIn March 2013, an economic assessment by the European [[Centre for Economic Policy Research]] estimates that such a comprehensive agreement would result in GDP growth of 68\u2013119&nbsp;billion euros for the European Union by 2027 and GDP growth of 50\u201395&nbsp;billion euros (about 53.5\u2013101&nbsp;billion US dollars) in the United States in the same time frame. The 2013 report also estimates that a limited agreement focused only on tariffs would yield EU GDP growth of 24&nbsp;billion euros by 2027 and growth of 9&nbsp;billion euros in the United States. If shared equally among the affected people, the most optimistic GDP growth estimates would translate into \"additional annual disposable income for a family of four\" of \"545 euros in the EU\" and \"655 euros in the US\", respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/docs/2013/march/tradoc_150737.pdf|title=Reducing Transatlantic Barriers to Trade and Investment: An Economic Assessment|publisher=Trade.ec.europa.eu|accessdate=2 February 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131228053938/http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/docs/2013/march/tradoc_150737.pdf|archive-date=28 December 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn a ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'' article, the CEO of [[Siemens]] AG (with its workforce located 70% in Europe and 30% in the United States) claimed that the TTIP would strengthen United States and EU global competitiveness by reducing trade barriers, by improving intellectual property protections, and by establishing new international \"rules of the road\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Kaeser |first=Joe |title=Why a US-European trade deal is a win-win |url=https://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702303973704579350783279285204?KEYWORDS=siemens |newspaper=The Wall Street Journal |date=2 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe [[European Commission]] says that the TTIP would boost the EU's economy by \u20ac120&nbsp;billion, the US economy by \u20ac90&nbsp;billion and the rest of the world by \u20ac100&nbsp;billion.<ref name=\"EU-ttip\"/> Talks began in July 2013 and reached the third round of negotiations by the end of that year.<ref name=\"EU-ttip\">{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/trade/policy/in-focus/ttip/ |title=Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP) \u2013 Trade \u2013 European Commission |publisher=Ec.europa.eu |date= |accessdate=2014-02-21}}</ref>\n\nAmerican economist [[Dean Baker]] of the [[Center for Economic and Policy Research]] observed that with conventional trade barriers between the US and the EU already low, the deal would focus on non-conventional barriers, such as overriding national regulations on [[fracking]], [[GMOs]], and finance, but also tightening laws on copyright. He goes on to assert that, with less ambitious projections, the economic benefits per household are unimpressive: \"If we apply the projected income gain of 0.21% to the projected median personal income in 2027, it comes to a bit more than $50 a year. That's a little less than 15 cents a day. Don't spend it all in one place\".<ref name=\"guardian July 15, 2013\">The Guardian (15 July 2013). [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/jul/15/us-trade-deal-with-europe-hype The US-EU trade deal: Don't buy the hype] Retrieved 24 August 2013.</ref>\n\nA 2018 paper by [[KU Leuven]] economists estimated that a \"deep\" free-trade agreement, such as TTIP, between the United States and the European Union would increase EU GDP by 1.3% and US GDP by 0.7%.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://voxeu.org/article/free-trade-between-eu-and-us-match-made-heaven|title=Free trade between the EU and US: A match made in heaven|last=Vandenbussche|first=Hylke|last2=Connell|first2=William|date=2018-08-23|website=VoxEU.org|access-date=2018-08-24|last3=Simons|first3=Wouter}}</ref> These gains would primarily be the result of reductions in [[Non-tariff barriers to trade|non-tariff barriers to trade]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Criticism and opposition==\n[[File:Grossdemonstration gegen TTIP in Berlin Oktober 2015.jpg|thumb|The STOP TTIP CETA demo in Berlin in October 2015 had around 250.000 participants.<ref>{{cite web|title=TTIP bringt Rekordzahl von Gegnern auf die Stra\u00dfe|url=http://www.zeit.de/wirtschaft/2015-10/ttip-demonstration-berlin-gabriel-ceta|publisher=ZEIT ONLINE|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Dearden|first1=Nick|title=Think TTIP is a threat to democracy? There's another trade deal that's already signed|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/may/30/ttip-trade-deal-agreements-ceta-eu-canada|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=7 August 2016|date=30 May 2016}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Cabecera de la mani (17009525818).jpg|thumb|\"Stop TTIP\" protests in [[Barcelona]], Spain, April 18, 2015]]\n[[File:2016-04-23 Anti-TTIP-Demonstration in Hannover, (10118).jpg|thumb|Anti-TTIP demonstration in [[Hannover]], Germany, April 23, 2016]]\n[[File:Stop TTIP-CETA Protest in Brussels 20-09-2016 (15).jpg|thumb|The Stop TTIP-CETA protest in [[Brussels]], Belgium, September 20, 2016]]\n\n=== Secrecy of content and negotiations ===\nThe content of the drafts of agreement, as well as the reports on negotiation rounds, are [[classified information|classified]] from the public, an arrangement that ''[[The Independent]]'' criticised as \"secretive and undemocratic\".<ref name=\"The Independent October 6, 2015\"/> As noted [[#Confidentiality measures|above]], elected representatives may only view the texts in a secure \"reading room\" in Brussels, to avoid any further leaks of information about TTIP negotiations into the public domain.\n\nTo answer the criticism, and months after their leaks by Greenpeace, the European Commission has made negotiation documents public, including all EU proposals in the regulatory and rules components of the agreement.<ref name=\"trade.ec.europa.eu\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euractiv.com/section/trade-society/news/ttip-papers-published-as-eu-ombudsman-demands-more-transparency/|title=TTIP papers published as EU Ombudsman demands more transparency|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/press/index.cfm?id=1230|title=EU negotiating texts in TTIP \u2013 Trade \u2013 European Commission|publisher=}}</ref> The Trade Commissioner has described the negotiations as \"the most transparent trade talks ever conducted by the EU\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/commission/2014-2019/malmstrom/blog/ttip-state-play_en|title=TTIP \u2013 the State of Play \u2013 European Commission \u2013 European Commission|first=Joakim|last=LARSSON|date=27 April 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n=== Possible negative impacts ===\n==== Politics, economy and society====\n''The Guardian'' described TTIP as \"the most controversial trade deal the EU has ever negotiated\".<ref name=\"theguardian.com 27 August 2016\"/> TTIP negotiations are criticized and opposed by some [[Trade union|unions]], charities, [[Non-governmental organization|NGOs]] and environmentalists, particularly in Europe.<ref name=\"guardian August 3, 2015\"/><ref name=\"The Daily Beast\">{{cite web|author=Leo Cendrowicz |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2015/04/22/europeans-fight-u-s-trade-deal-with-fear-of-mchospitals-fracking-under-eiffel-tower.html |title=Europeans Fight U.S. Trade Deal With Fear of McHospitals, Fracking Under Eiffel Tower |publisher=The Daily Beast |date= |accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref> ''[[The Independent]]'' summarizes the negative impact of TTIP as \"reducing the regulatory barriers to trade for big business, things like food safety law, environmental legislation, banking regulations and the sovereign powers of individual nations\",<ref name=\"The Independent October 6, 2015\">Lee Williams [https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/comment/what-is-ttip-and-six-reasons-why-the-answer-should-scare-you-9779688.html What is TTIP? And six reasons why the answer should scare you]. ''[[The Independent]]''. 6 October 2015.</ref> or more critically as an \"assault on European and US societies by transnational corporations\".<ref name=\"The Independent October 6, 2015\"/> German economist [[Max Otte]] stated that the proposed (ISDS) [[Investor-state dispute settlement#Tribunals|court of arbitration and protection of foreign investment]] would mean a \"complete dis-empowerment of politics\"<ref name=\"heute April 8, 2016\">[https://www.3sat.de/page/?source=/makro/magazin/doks/186138/index.html TTIP: \"V\u00f6llige Entmachtung der Politik\"]. [[3sat]]. Published on 8 April 2016.</ref> and that, regarding labour economics, free trade agreements typically enforce lower standards and that TTIP would put European workers into direct competition with Americans (and in effect because of the [[North American Free Trade Agreement]] with Mexicans), which would impact European social models.<ref name=\"heute April 8, 2016\"/> Otte also concluded: \"We really don't want the [[social system]] of these countries [United States and Mexico] here [in Europe].\"<ref name=\"heute April 8, 2016\"/>\n\nAn October 2014 study by Jeronim Capaldo of the [[Global Development and Environment Institute]] at [[Tufts University]] indicates that there will be losses in terms of net exports, net losses in terms of GDP, loss of labour income, job losses, reduction of the labour share, loss of government revenue and higher financial instability among European countries.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Capaldo|first1=Jeronim|title=The Trans-Atlantic Trade and Investment Partnership: European Disintegration, Unemployment and Instability|url=http://ase.tufts.edu/gdae/policy_research/TTIP_simulations.html}}</ref>\n\n==== Labour standards, workers' rights and job security ====\nAnti-poverty group [[Global Justice Now]] asserts that TTIP would undermine job security as well as current minimum labour standards agreed in the EU.<ref name=\"guardian October 18, 2015\"/> [[Labour Party (UK)|British Labour Party]] politician [[John McDonnell (politician)|John McDonnell]], [[Shadow Chancellor of the Exchequer]], has described TTIP as resulting in a huge transfer of powers to Brussels and [[corporatocracy|corporate interests]] that will bring about a form of \"modern-day [[serfdom]]\".<ref name=\"guardian October 18, 2015\"/> According to a [[European Parliament]] report, impacts on labour conditions range from job gains to job losses, depending on economic model and assumptions used for predictions.<ref name=\"EP Kraatz\"/>\n\nIn spite of a study by the Munich-based [[Ifo Institute for Economic Research]] (on behalf of the German Federal Ministry of Economics) claiming that up to 400,000 jobs could be created in the EU by TTIP,<ref>{{cite web|title=Topical Terms in Economics: Transatlantic Free Trade Agreement|url=https://www.cesifo-group.de/ifoHome/facts/Aktuelles-Stichwort/Topical-Terms-Archive/Transatlantic-Free-Trade-Agreement.html}}</ref> Stefan K\u00f6rzell, national board member of the [[Confederation of German Trade Unions]] (DGB) has said \"Whether TTIP can create jobs, and 'how many' and 'where' is unclear. Previous studies, ranging from those conducted by the European Commission across to the expertise of the Ifo Institute, fluctuate between optimism and very low expectations... Consideration of the negative consequences trade agreements can have, if environmental or labour standards are ignored, is often omitted. As of August 2015, the US had ratified two (prohibitions of child labour and slavery) of the eight [[International Labour Organization|ILO]] [[Social clause|core labour standards]].\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Viavision: The Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership|url=http://www.viavision.org.uk/ftp/1887.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==== Democracy and national sovereignty, foreign investor protection ====\n[[Investor-state dispute settlement]] (ISDS) is an instrument that allows an investor to bring a case directly against the country hosting its investment, without the intervention of the government of the investor's country of origin.<ref>{{cite web|author=European Commission |date=3 October 2013|url=http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/docs/2013/october/tradoc_151791.pdf |title=Factsheet on Investor-State Dispute Settlement|accessdate=2014-02-21}}</ref> From the late 1980s, certain trade treaties have included provisions for ISDS that allow foreign investors who claim to have been disadvantaged by actions of a signatory state, to sue that state for damages in a [[Arbitral tribunal|tribunal of arbitration]]. More recently such claims have increased in number and value,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://unctad.org/en/PublicationsLibrary/webdiaepcb2013d3_en.pdf|title=Recent Developments in Investor-State Disputes|publisher=Unctad.org|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref> and some states have become increasingly resistant to such clauses.<ref>Economist (11 October 2014) [https://www.economist.com/news/finance-and-economics/21623756-governments-are-souring-treaties-protect-foreign-investors-arbitration The arbitration game: Governments are souring on treaties to protect foreign investors] Retrieved 24 April 2015.</ref>\n\nCritics of TTIP say that \"ISDS provisions undermine the power of national governments to act in the interests of their citizens\",<ref name=\"guardian August 3, 2015\"/> that \"TTIP could even undermine the democratic authority of local government\",<ref name=\"guardian August 5, 2015\"/> and that it threatens democracy.<ref>Michael Robinson. [https://www.bbc.com/news/business-32116587 Is democracy threatened if companies can sue countries?]. [[BBC News]]. 31 March 2015.</ref> France and Germany have said that they want access to investor-state dispute settlement removed from the TTIP treaty.<ref name=\"guardian June 10, 2015\">Claire Provost and Matt Kennard. [https://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/jun/10/obscure-legal-system-lets-corportations-sue-states-ttip-icsid The obscure legal system that lets corporations sue countries]. [[theguardian.com]]. 10 June 2015</ref> In December 2013, a coalition of over 200 environmentalists, labor unions and consumer advocacy organizations on both sides of the Atlantic sent a letter to the [[Office of the United States Trade Representative|USTR]] and European Commission demanding the investor-state dispute settlement be dropped from the trade talks, claiming that ISDS was \"a one-way street by which corporations can challenge government policies, but neither governments nor individuals are granted any comparable rights to hold corporations accountable\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Stangler |first=Cole |url=http://inthesetimes.com/article/16044/ttip_the_next_corporate_friendly_trade_deal/ |title=The Next Corporate-Friendly Trade Pact |publisher=In These Times |date=30 December 2013 |accessdate=2014-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://action.sierraclub.org/site/DocServer/TTIP_Investment_Letter_Final.pdf?docID=14701 |title=Letter |publisher=Action.sierraclub.org |accessdate=2014-02-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140224075427/http://action.sierraclub.org/site/DocServer/TTIP_Investment_Letter_Final.pdf?docID=14701 |archivedate=24 February 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Some point out the \"potential for abuse\" that may be inherent in the trade agreement due to its clauses relating to investor protection.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/sep/14/ttip-deal-british-sovereignty-cameron-ukip-treaty|title=The TTIP deal hands British sovereignty to multinationals|last=Jones|first=Owen|date=14 September 2014|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=Guardian Media|accessdate=5 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/business/criticism-grows-over-investor-protections-in-transatlantic-trade-deal-a-945107.html|title= Corporation Carte Blanche: Will US-EU Trade Become Too Free?|last=Schiessl|first=Michaela|date=23 January 2014|work=[[Spiegel International]]|publisher=Spiegel Online|accessdate=5 November 2014}}</ref> A recent study shows that investor-state dispute settlement (ISDS) indeed generates strikingly large and consistent opposition to the trade agreement and this effect of dispute settlement characteristic cuts across individuals\u2019 key attributes, including skill levels, information, and national sentiment, which have been viewed as key determinants of trade attitudes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hahm|first=Hyeonho|last2=K\u00f6nig|first2=Thomas|last3=Osnabr\u00fcgge|first3=Moritz|last4=Frech|first4=Elena|date=2019|title=Who Settles Disputes? Treaty Design and Trade Attitudes Toward the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP)|journal=International Organization|language=en|volume=73|issue=4|pages=881\u2013900|doi=10.1017/S0020818319000249|issn=0020-8183}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2013, [[Martti Koskenniemi]], Professor of International Law at the [[University of Helsinki]], warned that the planned foreign investor protection scheme within the treaty, similar to [[World Bank Group]]'s [[International Centre for Settlement of Investment Disputes]] (ICSID), would endanger the sovereignty of the signatory states by allowing for a small circle of legal experts sitting in a foreign court of arbitration an unprecedented power to interpret and void the signatory states' legislation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hs.fi/sunnuntai/Professori+Suomen+valta+s%C3%A4%C3%A4t%C3%A4%C3%A4+lakeja+voi+vaarantua+/a1386995885773|title=Professori: Suomen valta s\u00e4\u00e4t\u00e4\u00e4 lakeja voi vaarantua |last=Konttinen|first=Jussi|date=15 December 2013|work=[[Helsingin Sanomat]]|publisher=Sanoma Oyj|language=Finnish|accessdate=16 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nFaced with such broad and vociferous criticism, ISDS was abandoned in September 2015; in its place, the European Commission proposed an Investment Court System (ICS).<ref>{{cite web|title = EU proposes new trade court with US|url = https://euobserver.com/economic/130297|website = EUobserver|access-date = 23 February 2016|last = Nielsen|first = Nikolaj|date = 16 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.greenpeace.org/eu-unit/Global/eu-unit/reports-briefings/2016/2016_02_11_Greenpeace%20Position%20Paper%20ICS_Final.pdf|title = From ISDS to ICS: A Leopard Can't Change Its Spots|date = 11 February 2016|access-date = 23 February 2016 |page = 1 |publisher = Greenpeace Position Paper |author = Greenpeace}}</ref> Not long afterwards, ICS was declared illegal by the German Association of Magistrates,<ref>{{cite web|title = TTIP investor court illegal, say German judges|url = https://euobserver.com/economic/132142|website = EUobserver|access-date = 6 February 2016|date = 4 February 2016|last = Nielsen|first = Nikolaj}}</ref> though the commission dismissed the magistrates' judgement as based on a misunderstanding.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|title = EU defends TTIP investor court after German backlash|url = https://euobserver.com/economic/132295|website = EUobserver|access-date = 23 February 2016|date = 17 February 2016|last = Nielsen|first = Nikolaj}}</ref> For its part, the United States wants ISDS reinstated.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn February 2016, Labour (UK) leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]] said that human rights should be part of TTIP,   \ndescribing TTIP as a threat to national sovereignty, workers, consumers, health and the environment.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/ttip-human-rights-workers-corporate-court-law-jeremy-corbyn-david-cameron-pmqs-a6889531.html TTIP 'must include human rights', Jeremy Corbyn tells David Cameron] H. Sheffield, The Independent, 22 February 2016</ref>\n\n==== Public health and environment ====\nAccording to a report in ''The Guardian'', TTIP draft leaked in 2016 shows \"irreconcilable\" differences between EU and the US in some areas, with the US demanding that EU compromise its \"environmental, consumer protection and public health standards\".<ref name=\"The Guardian May 1, 2016\">Arthur Neslen. [https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/may/01/leaked-ttip-documents-cast-doubt-on-eu-us-trade-deal Leaked TTIP documents cast doubt on EU-US trade deal]. ''[[The Guardian]]''. 1 May 2016.</ref>\n\n===== Health care =====\n{{See also|Healthcare in Europe|Health care in the United States}}\n[[Trade unions in the United Kingdom|British unions]] such as [[Unite the Union|Unite]] and the [[Trades Union Congress|TUC]] have opposed TTIP on the grounds that it would undermine the [[National Health Service]] and allows for the further [[privatisation]] of public services. A Unite spokesperson described TTIP as \"about deregulation and a [[race to the bottom]] on standards. Unison has fought and won on bringing services back into the public sector. ... We cannot allow TTIP to threaten those successes.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chako|first1=Ben|title=TUC says no to TTIP|url=http://www.ukpressonline.co.uk/ukpressonline/getDocument/DWMS_2014_09_11_001?fileType=PDF|accessdate=7 April 2016|work=Morning Star|date=11 September 2014|page=1|format=PDF|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nFormer Foreign Secretary [[David Owen]] said that TTIP would have a significant negative impact on the UK's [[National Health Service]] because the Service would be subject to increased competition under the TTIP regime.<ref name=\"Telegraph 6/4/16\">[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/04/06/nhs-would-be-completely-unrecognisable-within-years-if-uk-remain/ NHS would be 'completely unrecognisable' within years if UK remains inside the EU] K. McCann, The Daily Telegraph, 6 April 2016</ref>\n\nFormer UK prime minister [[David Cameron]] said that critics of [[free-trade]] should not use the [[National Health Service]] (NHS) to take people's attention away, and honestly speak about trade deals. UK's [[Department of Business, Innovation and Skills]] said that TTIP provided adequate protection for UK's NHS.<ref name=rt09052016TTIP>[https://www.rt.com/uk/342384-ttip-deal-nhs-cameron/ \u2018Slippery fish\u2019 Cameron is duping the public, TTIP is threat to NHS, critics say] RT, 9 May 2016</ref>\n\nAssistant General Secretary of [[Unite the Union|Unite]] [[Gail Cartmail]] said that TTIP was a real and serious threat to the NHS, adding that the threat would not be neutralised unless [[David Cameron]] gave a cast-iron guarantee that he would exclude the NHS from TTIP.<ref name=rt09052016TTIP />\n\n===== Consumer protection and food safety =====\n{{See also|European Food Safety Authority|Regulation of genetically modified organisms in the European Union|Pesticide regulation in the United States}}\n\nDocuments released in May 2015 showed that US negotiators had pressured the EU over proposed pesticide criteria. A number of pesticides containing [[endocrine disrupting chemicals]] were forbidden in draft EU criteria. On 2 May 2013, US negotiators insisted the EU drop the criteria. They stated that a risk-based approach should be taken on regulation. Later the same day [[Catherine Day]] ([[Secretary-General of the European Commission]]) wrote to Karl Falkenberg ([[Directorate-General for the Environment|Director General for the Environment]]) asking for these criteria to be removed.{{r|guardian22may15}} {{As of|2015}}, 82 pesticides used in the US were banned in Europe and US [[animal welfare]] standards are generally lower than those in Europe.<ref name=\"BBC 10 June 2015\"/>\n\nA columnist in ''[[The Guardian]]'' stated that [[food safety]] in the EU might be compromised because of low or different standards in US food regulations,<ref name=\"guardian August 3, 2015\"/> if currently EU-banned food were allowed to be imported.<ref name=\"guardian October 18, 2015\">Phillip Inman. [https://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/oct/18/prospect-ttip-deal-undermining-eu-food-standards-gmos Prospect of TTIP already undermining EU food standards, say campaigners]. [[The Guardian]]. 18 October 2015.</ref> In June 2015, the [[BBC]] reported that food safety had become 'a stumbling block' because of differing US and EU attitudes to [[genetically modified crops]], [[pesticides]] ([[Endocrine disruptor|endocrine disrupting chemicals]]), [[growth hormone#Agricultural use|growth promoting hormones]] in beef and [[pathogen]] reduction treatments of [[Chicken (food)|chicken]], that cause public health concerns for consumers and put European farmers at a cost disadvantage.<ref name=\"BBC 10 June 2015\">Laurence Peter. [https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-33055665 TTIP talks: Food fights block EU\u2013US trade deal]. [[BBC News]]. 10 June 2015.</ref> Ban on [[animal testing]] in the EU has been described by ''The Guardian'' as \"irreconcilable\" with the US approach.<ref name=\"The Guardian May 1, 2016\"/>\n\n===== Environment protection and climate change =====\n{{See also|Environmental policy of the European Union|Climate change mitigation|Politics of global warming}}\n\nA draft of the sustainable development section of TTIP was leaked to ''[[The Guardian]]'' in October 2015. Asked to comment on the document, a French environmental attorney described the proposed environmental safeguards as \"virtually non-existent\" by comparison with the protection granted to investors, and that environmental cases accounted for 60% of the 127 [[Investor-state dispute settlement|ISDS]] cases already brought against EU countries under bilateral trade agreements in the last two decades, according to [[Friends of the Earth Europe]].<ref>{{cite web |last= Nielsen |first= Arthur |date= 23 October 2015 |title= TTIP: EU negotiators appear to break environmental pledge in leaked draft |url= https://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/oct/23/ttip-eu-negotiators-appear-to-break-environmental-pledge-in-leaked-draft |website= theguardian.com |accessdate= 23 February 2016 }}</ref>\nAccording to [[Joseph E. Stiglitz]], TTIP could have a \"chilling\" effect on regulation and thus \"undercut urgently needed action on climate that the Paris agreement requires\". He says that industries that do not pay for the \"social costs\" of pollution in effect receive hidden subsidies, and that TTIP would give companies many more opportunities to sue governments over environmental protection mechanisms.<ref name=\"stiglitz-2016\">{{cite news | first = Joseph E | last = Stiglitz | author-link = Joseph E. Stiglitz | date = 23 April 2016 | title = TTIP and Climate Change: A Tale of Two Cities from Paris to Hannover | newspaper = [[S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung]] | url = http://www.sueddeutsche.de/politik/exterior-view-ttip-and-climate-change-a-tale-of-two-cities-from-paris-to-hannover-1.2963133 | access-date = 11 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe draft energy chapter of the TTIP was leaked to ''[[The Guardian]]'' in July 2016.<ref name=\"neslen-2016\">{{cite news | first = Arthur | last = Neslen | title = Leaked TTIP energy proposal could 'sabotage' EU climate policy | date = 11 July 2016 | newspaper = [[The Guardian]] | url = https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2016/jul/11/leaked-ttip-energy-proposal-could-sabotage-eu-climate-policy | access-date = 11 July 2016}}</ref> According to ''The Guardian'', this draft could \"sabotage\" European efforts to implement mandatory energy savings measures and to favor the switch to renewable electricity generation.  The draft text obliges the two trade blocs to: \"foster industry self-regulation of energy efficiency requirements for goods where such self-regulation is likely to deliver the policy objectives faster or in a less costly manner than mandatory requirements\".<ref name=\"neslen-2016\"/>  The draft also mandates that operators of energy networks grant access to gas and electricity \"on commercial terms that are reasonable, transparent and non-discriminatory, including as between types of energy\".<ref name=\"neslen-2016\"/>  This would open [[feed-in tariff]] schemes to commercial challenge, including [[German Renewable Energy Sources Act|that]] used by Germany.  The [[The Greens (Luxembourg)|Green]] [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]] [[Claude Turmes]] stated: \"These proposals are completely unacceptable. They would sabotage EU legislators' ability to privilege renewables and energy efficiency over unsustainable fossil fuels. This is an attempt to undermine democracy in Europe.\"<ref name=\"neslen-2016\"/>\n\nThe EU's draft text for the trade and sustainable development chapter was also leaked to ''[[The Guardian]]'' in July 2016.<ref name=\"neslen-2016-b\">{{cite news | first = Arthur | last = Neslen | title = TTIP proposal casts doubt on G20 climate pledge, leaked EU draft shows | date =  13 July 2016 | newspaper = The Guardian | url = https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2016/jul/13/ttip-proposal-casts-doubt-on-g20-climate-pledge-leaked-eu-draft-shows | access-date = 2016-07-12}}</ref> The draft, dated 23 June 2016 and marked \"restricted\", reveals new loopholes on a [[G20]] pledge to phase out inefficient [[Energy subsidies|fossil fuel subsidies]] by 2025.  The [[International Monetary Fund|IMF]] estimates these subsidies run globally at $10{{nbsp}}million per minute<ref name=\"carrington-2015\">{{cite news | first = Damian | last = Carrington | title = Fossil fuels subsidised by $10m a minute, says IMF | date = 18 May 2015 | newspaper = The Guardian | url = https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2015/may/18/fossil-fuel-companies-getting-10m-a-minute-in-subsidies-says-imf | access-date = 2016-07-12}}</ref> and [[G7]] ministers pledged to remove them in May 2016 in a meeting in Japan.<ref name=\"mathiesen-2016\">{{cite news | first = Karl | last = Mathiesen | title = G7 nations pledge to end fossil fuel subsidies by 2025 | date = 27 May 2016 | newspaper = The Guardian | url = https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2016/may/27/g7-nations-pledge-to-end-fossil-fuel-subsidies-by-2025 | access-date = 2016-07-12}}</ref> The draft however states that \"such a phasing out may take into account security of supply considerations\".<ref name=\"neslen-2016-b\"/>  ''The Guardian'' believes that this passage could be open to abuse and used to slow the phase out of subsidies.\n\n==== Banking regulation ====\n{{See also|Bank regulation in the United States}}\n\nAccording to critics, TTIP could weaken the stricter [[bank regulation]]s that are governing banks in the United States as part of the financial reforms that followed the [[financial crisis of 2007\u201308]].<ref name=\"The Independent October 6, 2015\"/><ref name=\"BBC 18 December 2014\">Leala Padmanabhan. [https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-30493297 TTIP: The EU-US trade deal explained]. BBC News. 18 December 2014</ref>\n\n==== Privacy ====\n{{See also|Mass surveillance in the United States|Internet censorship in the United States}}\n\nCritics of TTIP argue that its proposals on intellectual property could have a similar effect as the EU-rejected [[Anti-Counterfeiting Trade Agreement]] (ACTA).<ref name=\"BBC 18 December 2014\"/> The [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]] and its German counterpart, [[Foundation for a Free Information Infrastructure|FFII]], in particular, compared TTIP to the ACTA.<ref>{{cite web|work=EFF|url=https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2013/03/transatlantic-declaration-leave-copyright-patent-issues-out-tafta|title=Transatlantic Civil Society Declaration: Leave Copyright and Patent Provisions Out of TAFTA|accessdate= 18 March 2013|date= 18 March 2013|author= Maira Sutton}}</ref>\n\n=== Activism against TTIP ===\n[[File:Stop TTIP Martin Schulz 01.jpg|thumb|\"Stop TTIP\" [[Civil society campaign|campaigner]]s hand 3,284,289 signatures to [[Martin Schulz]], [[President of the European Parliament]], November 2015.]]\nIn March 2013, a coalition of [[digital rights]] organisations and other groups issued a declaration<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.citizen.org/ip-out-of-tafta|title=IP out of TAFTA|work=citizen.org|accessdate=18 March 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130320190633/https://www.citizen.org/IP-out-of-TAFTA|archivedate=20 March 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> in which they called on the negotiating partners to have TTIP \"debated in the [[US Congress]], the [[European Parliament]], national parliaments, and other transparent forums\" instead of conducting \"closed negotiations that give privileged access to corporate insiders\", and to leave intellectual property out of the agreement.\n\nIn 2014, an online consultation conducted by the European Commission<ref>{{cite web |url= http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-14-292_en.htm |title= European Commission launches public online consultation on investor protection in TTIP |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= 27 March 2014 |website= |publisher= [[European Commission]] |accessdate= 26 July 2015}}</ref> received 150,000 responses.  According to the commission, 97% of the responses were pre-defined, negative answers provided by activists.<ref>{{cite news \n|title= EU finds 'huge skepticism' over US trade deal \n|url= https://news.yahoo.com/eu-finds-huge-scepticism-over-us-trade-deal-203636918.html \n|date= 13 January 2015 \n|work=Yahoo News \n|accessdate=21 January 2015 }}\n</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sueddeutsche.de/wirtschaft/buergerbefragung-zu-ttip-prozent-dagegen-1.2302201|title=B\u00fcrgerbefragung zu TTIP: 97 Prozent dagegen|first1=Michael|last1=Bauchm\u00fcller|first2=Cerstin |last2=Gammelin|publisher=|via=Sueddeutsche.de}}</ref> Additionally, hundreds of demonstrations and protests have taken place in an organised \"day of action\" on 11 October 2014,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stop-ttip-ceta-tisa.eu/ |title=October 11, 2014 \u2013 #O11DoA European Day of Action  |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website= |publisher= |accessdate= 26 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://stop-ttip.org/|title=Home \u2013 Stop TTIP Stop TTIP|work=Stop TTIP}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/nov/04/british-government-leading-gunpowder-plot-democracy-eu-us-trade|title=The British government is leading a gunpowder plot against democracy|author=George Monbiot|work=the Guardian}}</ref> and again on 18 April 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.euractiv.com/sections/trade-society/thousands-across-europe-protest-against-ttip-313921|title= Thousands across Europe protest against TTIP |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= 20 April 2015|website= euractiv.com|publisher= |accessdate= 27 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=imk56itZc_w|title= TTIP protests 17 18 April 2015 \u2013 Lewisham PeopleBeforeProfit|last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website= |publisher= YouTube|accessdate= 27 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZLrr0V2a8lE |title=TTIP Aktionstag in Mainz 18 April 2015  |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website= |publisher= YouTube|accessdate= 27 July 2015}}</ref> In February 2016, Greenpeace activists blocked secret talks on the Investment Court System.<ref>{{cite web |title = Greenpeace activists block secret TTIP talks |url = http://www.greenpeace.org/eu-unit/en/News/2016/Greenpeace-activists-block-secret-TTIP-talks/ |website = Greenpeace EU Unit |access-date = 23 February 2016 |date = 22 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nA self-organised [[European Citizens' Initiative]] against TTIP and [[Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement|CETA]] has also been established, acquiring over 3.2&nbsp;million signatures within a year.<ref name=\"guard 3 Aug 2015\" /><ref name=\"Stop TTIP\"/>\n\nIn April 2016, [[Barack Obama]] visited UK, and more than 130,000 people signed a petition organised by political activism group [[38 Degrees]], urging Obama to stop negotiating TTIP.<ref name=\"Independent 190416\" /> The group planned to send an open letter to Obama to urge Obama to oppose the pact, saying that TTIP would be a threat to [[National Health Service (England)|NHS]], food standards, animal welfare and democracy because it 'gives corporations more power than people'.<ref name=\"Independent 190416\">[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/ttip-more-than-130000-people-urge-barack-obama-to-kill-controversial-trade-deal-during-uk-visit-a6991286.html TTIP: More than 130,000 people urge Barack Obama to kill controversial trade deal during UK visit] R. Revesz, The Independent, 19 April 2016</ref>\n\n==== Leaks ====\nIn 2016, Greenpeace published 248 pages of classified documents from the TTIP trade negotiations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ttip-leaks.org/|title=Read the secret #TTIP papers here|publisher=}}</ref> Greenpeace Netherlands said it released the documents \"to provide much needed transparency and trigger an informed debate on the treaty\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/may/01/leaked-ttip-documents-cast-doubt-on-eu-us-trade-deal|title=Leaked TTIP documents cast doubt on EU-US trade deal|first=Arthur|last=Neslen|date=1 May 2016|publisher=|via=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n===National objections===\nFrom both the European and American sides of the agreement, there are issues which are seen as essential if an accord is to be reached.  According to Leif Johan Eliasson of Saarland University, \"For the EU these include greater access to the American public procurement market, retained bans on imports of [[genetically modified organisms]] (GMO) crops and [[Beef hormone controversy|hormone treated beef]], and recognition of [[geographical indications|geographic trademarks on food products]]. For the United States they include greater access for American dairy and other agricultural products (including scientific studies as the only accepted criteria for [[Sanitary and phytosanitary measures and agreements|SPS]] policies).\" He observes that measures like the EU ban on hormone treated beef (based as they are on the [[precautionary principle]]) are not considered by the [[World Trade Organization|WTO]] to be based on scientific studies.\n\nEliasson further states that US objectives in a deal include \"tariff-free motor vehicle exports,\" and retained bans on foreign contractors in several areas,\" including domestic shipping (see [[Merchant Marine Act of 1920]]).<ref name=\"eliasson2013\">Leif Johan Eliasson, [http://jean-monnet-saar.eu/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/10_07_14_TTIP-Eliasson.pdf What is at stake in the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP)? Assessing challenges and possible compromises], Saarland University, 10 July 2014</ref> Already, some American producers are concerned by EU proposals to restrict use of \"[[Geographical indications and traditional specialities in the European Union|particular designations]]\" (also known as <!-- people may search for: -->PDO or GI/geographical indications) that the EU considers location-specific, such as [[feta]] and [[Parmesan]] cheeses and possibly [[Budweiser Budvar|Budweiser]] beer.<ref>[https://www.economist.com/news/united-states/21607867-europeans-want-their-food-names-back-americans-are-peeved-stressed-are-cheesemakers Food names: Stressed are the cheesemakers: Europeans want their food names back. Americans are peeved], [[The Economist]], 19 July 2014</ref><ref>Beer from [[\u010cesk\u00e9 Bud\u011bjovice]]/Budweis([[Czech Republic]]) has [[Geographical indications and traditional specialities in the European Union|Protected Geographical Indication]]. [[Budweiser Budvar]] is already [[Budweiser trademark dispute|party to a trademark dispute]] with [[Anheuser-Busch InBev]] over which has the right to use the term.</ref> This has provoked debate between European politicians such as [[Renate K\u00fcnast]] and [[Christian Schmidt (politician)|Christian Schmidt]] over the value of the designations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euractiv.com/sections/trade-society/germans-fret-about-kentucky-fried-bratwurst-under-ttip-311067|title=Germans fret about 'Kentucky Fried Bratwurst' under TTIP|work=EurActiv \u2013 EU News & policy debates, across languages}}</ref>\n\nAt French insistence, [[Cultural exception|trade in audio-visual services was excluded]] from the EU negotiating mandate.<ref>[http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/html/152670.htm TTIP and Culture], European Commission DG Trade, 16 July 2014</ref> The European side has been pressing for the agreement to include a chapter on the regulation of financial services; but this is being resisted by the American side, which has recently passed the [[Dodd\u2013Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act|Dodd\u2013Frank Act]] in this field.<ref>[http://www.euractiv.com/sections/european-business-summit-2014/eu-us-clash-over-financial-services-ttip-302173 EU-US clash over financial services in TTIP], [[EurActiv]], 15 May 2014</ref> [[United States Ambassador to the European Union|US Ambassador to the European Union]] [[Anthony L. Gardner]] has denied any linkage between the two issues.<ref>[http://www.euractiv.com/sections/trade-industry/us-ambassador-eu-anthony-l-gardner-beyond-growth-ttip-must-happen US Ambassador: Beyond growth, TTIP must happen for geostrategic reasons], [[EurActiv]], 16 July 2014</ref>\n\nEuropean negotiators are also pressing the United States to loosen [[Energy policy of the United States|its restrictions]] on the export of crude oil and natural gas, to help the EU reduce its dependence on energy from Russia.<ref>Zach Carter and Kate Sheppard, [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/05/19/trade-fracking_n_5340420.html Read The Secret Trade Memo Calling For More Fracking and Offshore Drilling], ''Huffington Post'', 19 May 2014<br />Lidia Pillis, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/wonkblog/wp/2014/07/08/could-a-trade-deal-lift-the-u-s-longstanding-ban-on-crude-oil-exports-europe-thinks-so/ A leaked document shows just how much the EU wants a piece of America\u2019s fracking boom], ''Washington Post'', 8 July 2014<br />David J. Unger, [http://www.csmonitor.com/Environment/Energy-Voices/2014/0715/Europe-at-TTIP-talks-Open-the-US-energy-spigot Europe at TTIP talks: Open the US energy spigot], ''Christian Science Monitor'', 15 July 2014</ref>\n\n===Response to criticism===\n[[Karel De Gucht]] responded to criticism in a ''Guardian'' article in December 2013,<ref>The Guardian (2 December 2013) [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/dec/02/transatlantic-free-trade-deal-regulation-by-lawyers-eu-us The lies behind this transatlantic trade deal] Retrieved 1 January 2015.</ref> saying \"The commission has regularly consulted a broad range of civil society organisations in writing and in person, and our most recent meeting had 350 participants from trade unions, NGOs and business\" and that \"no agreement will become law before it is thoroughly examined and signed off by the European parliament and 29 democratically elected national governments \u2013 the US government and 28 in the EU's council\"<ref>The Guardian (18 December 2013) [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/dec/18/wrong-george-monbiot-nothing-secret-eu-trade-deal You're wrong, George Monbiot \u2013 there is nothing secret about this EU trade deal] Retrieved 2 February 2014.</ref> However, the [[Corporate Europe Observatory]] (cited in the original ''Guardian'' article) had pointed out, based on a [[Freedom of Information]] request, that \"more than 93% of the Commission's meetings with stakeholders during the preparations of the negotiations were with big business\". They characterized the industry meetings as \"about the EU's preparations of the trade talks\", and the civil society consultation as \"an information session after the talks were launched\".<ref>Corporate Europe Observatory (4 September 2013) [http://corporateeurope.org/trade/2013/09/european-commission-preparing-eu-us-trade-talks-119-meetings-industry-lobbyists European Commission preparing for EU-US trade talks] Retrieved 14 April 2015.</ref>\n\n== Effect on third-party countries ==\n[[File:Transatlantic Free Trade Area.svg|thumb|A possible future Transatlantic Free Trade Area: <br />the United States and European Union in dark blue and the other possible members in light blue ([[NAFTA]] and [[EFTA]])]]\n\nLooking beyond TTIP, a wider \"transatlantic free trade area\" has been postulated.{{by whom|date=April 2016}}{{citation needed|date=April 2016}} This might include, on the American side, the other members of [[North American Free Trade Area]] (Canada and Mexico); and on the European side, the members of the [[European Free Trade Association]] (Iceland, Norway, Switzerland and Liechtenstein). Mexico already has a free trade agreement with EFTA [[Free Trade Agreement between Mexico and the European Union|and the EU]] while [[Canada\u2013European Free Trade Association Free Trade Agreement|Canada has one with EFTA]] and has [[Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement|negotiated one with the EU]]. These agreements may need to be harmonized with the EU-US agreement and could potentially form a wider free trade area.\n\nIn early 2013, Canadian media observers had speculated that the launch of TTIP talks put pressure on Canada to secure ratification of its own three-year-long FTA negotiations with the EU by the close of 2013.<ref>{{cite news|author=Barrie Mckenna And Bertrand Marotte |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/international-business/potential-us-eu-free-trade-union-puts-the-squeeze-on-canada/article8592389/ |title=Potential US-EU free-trade union 'puts the squeeze' on Canada |publisher=The Globe and Mail |date=13 February 2013 |accessdate=2014-02-21 |location=Toronto}}</ref> Countries with customs agreements with the EU, [[European Union\u2013Turkey Customs Union|like Turkey's]], could face the prospect of opening their markets to American goods, without access for their own goods without a separate agreement with the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/transatlantic-alliance-to-cost-turkey-20-billion.aspx?pageID=238&nid=53844&NewsCatID=344 |title=Transatlantic alliance to cost Turkey '$20&nbsp;billion' \u2013 ECONOMICS |publisher=Hurriyetdailynews.com |date=13 September 2011 |accessdate=2014-02-21}}</ref>\n\n==Reports==\nVarious groups have produced reports about the proposed agreement, including:\n* ''The Politics of Transatlantic Trade Negotiations: TTIP in a Globalized World'' (2015) {{ISBN|9781472443649}}\n* ''The Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership: Ambitious but Achievable \u2013 A Stakeholder Survey and Three Scenarios'' (April 2013)  {{ISBN|978-1-61977-032-4}}<ref name=Stakeholder>{{cite web|title=The Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership: Ambitious but Achievable \u2013 A Stakeholder Survey and Three Scenarios|url=http://www.bertelsmann-stiftung.de/cps/rde/xbcr/SID-4C33D168-3FA15517/bst/xcms_bst_dms_37655_37656_2.pdf|publisher=[[Atlantic Council]], [[Bertelsmann Foundation]]|accessdate=18 May 2014}}</ref>\n* ''TTIP and the Fifty States: Jobs and Growth from Coast to Coast'' (September 2013) {{ISBN|978-1-61977-038-6}}<ref name=CoastToCoast>{{cite web|title=TTIP and the Fifty States: Jobs and Growth from Coast to Coast|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/245085/TTIP_and_the_50_States_GovUK.pdf|publisher=Atlantic Council, Bertelmanns Foundation|accessdate=18 May 2014}}</ref>\n* ''The Transatlantic Colossus: Global Contributions to Broaden the Debate on the EU-US Free Trade Agreement'' (December 2013) {{ISBN|978-3-00-044648-1}}<ref name=TransatlColoss>{{cite web|title=The Transatlantic Colossus: Global Contributions to Broaden the Debate on the EU-US Free Trade Agreement|url=http://bfogp.org/publications/the-transatlantic-colossus/|author=Berlin Forum on Global Politics, Internet & Society Collaboratory, FutureChallenges.org|accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref>\n* ''The Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership: A Charter for Deregulation, An Attack on Jobs, An End to Democracy'' (February 2014)<ref name=Charterforderegulation>{{cite web|title=A Charter for Deregulation, An Attack on Jobs, An End to Democracy|url=http://rosalux.gr/sites/default/files/publications/ttip_web.pdf\n|publisher=Rosa Luxemburg Stiftung, Brussels Office|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Anti-Counterfeiting Trade Agreement]] (ACTA)\n* [[Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement]] (CETA)\n* [[Copyright infringement]]\n* [[Digital rights]]\n* [[European Union free trade agreements]]\n* [[Investor-state dispute settlement]]\n* [[Trade in Services Agreement]] (TISA)\n* [[Trans-Pacific Partnership]] (TPP)\n* [[Transatlantic Free Trade Area]]\n* [[United States\u2013European Union relations]]\n* [[United States free trade agreements]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=guardian22may15>{{cite web|title=EU dropped pesticide laws due to US pressure over TTIP, documents reveal|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2015/may/22/eu-dropped-pesticide-laws-due-to-us-pressure-over-ttip-documents-reveal#comments|publisher=Guardian|accessdate=22 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"guard 3 Aug 2015\">{{cite web |last= Jeffries |first= Stuart |date= 3 August 2015 |title= What is TTIP and why should we be angry about it? |url= https://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/aug/03/ttip-what-why-angry-transatlantic-trade-investment-partnership-guide |website= theguardian.com |accessdate= 23 February 2016 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Stop TTIP\">{{cite web|url=https://stop-ttip.org/|title=Do the CETA-CHECK!|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"theguardian.com 27 August 2016\">Jennifer Rankin. [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/aug/27/cecilia-malmstrom-swedish-politician-play-hardball-with-uk-on-brexit Meet the Swedish politician ready to play hardball with the UK on Brexit]. [[theguardian.com]]. 27 August 2016.</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.dw.de/ttip-mega-marriage-facing-hurdles/av-17863865 What exactly is the Trans Atlantic Trade and Investment Partnership?] Video produced by DW ([[Deutsche Welle]])\n\n=== Official sites ===\n* [http://ec.europa.eu/trade/policy/countries-and-regions/countries/united-states/