ge": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ingrid_Goes_West"}
{"title_page": "Separatist movements of Pakistan", "text_new": "There are '''separatist movements in Pakistan''' which are based on ethnic and regional nationalism, including independence movements in [[Balawaristan]],<ref name=\"FH2014\"/> Sindh, and Balochistan.<ref name=\"Express Tribune\"/> The government of Pakistan has attempted to subdue these separatist movements.<ref name=\"FH2014\"/>\n\nThe separatist movements in Sindh and Balawaristan are inactive and lack support<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.satp.org/terrorist-groups/pakistan|title=Terrorist Groups|work=South Asian Terrorism Portal Index (SATP)|accessdate=15 June 2019}}</ref> while the separatist movement in Balochistan is engaged in a low-intensity insurgency against the government \nof Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1375529|title=Over 300 anti-state militants surrender arms in Balochistan|date=9 December 2017|work=Dawn News|quote=The largest province of the country by area, Balochistan is home to a low-level insurgency by ethnic Baloch separatists.}}</ref><ref name=\"gan\"/>\n\n==History==\n{{Further|Bangladesh Liberation War}}\nPakistan was established in 1947 as a state for Muslims. The driving force behind the Pakistan Movement were the Muslims in the Muslim minority provinces of [[United Province]] and [[Bombay Presidency]] rather than the Muslims from the Muslim majority provinces.<ref name=\"AhmadRafiq2016\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nzMlDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA127|title=Pakistan's Democratic Transition: Change and Persistence|author1=Ishtiaq Ahmad|author2=Adnan Rafiq|date=3 November 2016|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-317-23595-8|pages=127\u2013}}</ref> Its formation was based on the basis of [[Religious nationalism|Islamic nationalism]]. \n\nHowever, rampant corruption within the ranks of the government and bureaucracy, economic inequality between the country's two wings caused mainly by a lack of  [[democracy|representative government]] and the government's indifference to the efforts of fierce ethno-nationalistic politicians like Mujeeb-ur-Rehman from [[East Pakistan]], resulted in [[Bangladesh Liberation War|civil war in Pakistan]] and subsequent separation of [[East Pakistan]] as the new state of the [[People's Republic of Bangladesh]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}}\n\nIn 2009, the [[Pew Research Center]] conducted a Global Attitudes survey across Pakistan, in which it questioned respondents whether they viewed their primary identity as Pakistani or that of their ethnicity. The [[Survey sampling|sample]] covered an area representing 90% of the adult population, and included all major ethnic groups.<ref name=\"PEW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pewglobal.org/2009/08/13/chapter-2-religion-law-and-society/|title=Pakistani Public Opinion \u2013 Chapter 2. Religion, Law, and Society|work=Pew Research Center|date=13 August 2009|accessdate=25 September 2017}}</ref> According to the findings, 96% of [[Punjabis]] identified themselves first as Pakistanis, as did 92% each of [[Pashtuns]] and [[Muhajir people|Muhajirs]]; 55% of [[Sindhis]] chose a Pakistani identification, while 28% chose Sindhi and 16% selected \"both equally\"; whereas 58% of [[Baloch people|Baloch]] respondents chose Pakistani and 32% selected their ethnicity and 10% chose both equally.<ref name=\"PEW\"/> Collectively, 89% of the sample opted their primary identity as Pakistani.<ref name=\"PEW\"/> Similarly in 2010, [[Chatham House]] conducted an opinion poll in the Pakistani and Indian-administered regions of [[Kashmir]] asking respondents if they [[Kashmir conflict|favoured independence]] or an accession to either countries; in [[Azad Kashmir]], 95% of respondents voted for all of Kashmir to accede to Pakistan, 4% voted for independence, and only 1% voted for accession to India.<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.chathamhouse.org/sites/files/chathamhouse/public/Research/Asia/0510pp_kashmir.pdf |title=Kashmir: Path to Peace |last=Bradnock |first=Robert W. |date=May 2010 |journal=Chatham House |doi= |pmid= |access-date= |page=15|accessdate=25 September 2017}}</ref> In the northern region of [[Gilgit-Baltistan]], longstanding local sentiments oppose any merger of the area with Kashmir, and instead demand a constitutional integration with Pakistan.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/gilgitbaltistan-a-question-of-autonomy/519428/2|title=Gilgit-Baltistan: A question of autonomy|last=Singh|first=Pallavi|date=29 April 2010|work=The Indian Express|quote=But it falls short of the main demand of the people of Gilgit- Baltistan for a constitutional status to the region as a fifth province and for Pakistani citizenship to its people.|access-date=25 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pakistan-election-idUSTRE5AB1ZE20091112|title=Pakistan's disputed Northern Areas go to polls|last=Shigri|first=Manzar|date=12 November 2009|work=Reuters|quote=Many of the 1.5 million people of Gilgit-Baltistan oppose integration into Kashmir and want their area to be merged into Pakistan and declared a separate province.|access-date=25 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Gregory2015\">{{cite book|author=Victoria Schofield|editor=Shaun Gregory|title=Democratic Transition and Security in Pakistan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=acfMCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA147|date=23 October 2015|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-55011-2|pages=147\u2013|chapter=Kashmir and its regional context}}</ref><ref name=\"Manchanda2015\">{{cite book|author=Rita Manchanda|title=SAGE Series in Human Rights Audits of Peace Processes: Five-Volume Set|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bipPDAAAQBAJ&pg=RA2-PA8|date=16 March 2015|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=978-93-5150-213-5|pages=2\u2013}}</ref>\n\n== Balochistan ==\n{{Further|Insurgency in Balochistan}}\nThe [[Baloch Liberation Front]] (BLF) separatist group was founded by [[Jumma Khan Marri]] in 1964 in [[Damascus]], and played an important role in the 1968-1980 insurgency in [[Balochistan (Pakistan)|Pakistani Balochistan]] and [[Iranian Balochistan]]. Mir Hazar Ramkhani, the father of [[Jumma Khan Marri]], took over the group in the 1980s. The Balochistan Liberation Army (also Baloch Liberation Army or Baluchistan Liberation army) (BLA) is a [[Baloch nationalist]] militant secessionist organization. However, [[Jumma Khan Marri]] ended his opposition and pledged allegiance to Pakistan on 17 February 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1390521|title=Baloch leader distances himself from separatist movement|date=20 February 2018|work=Dawn News}}</ref> The stated goals of the organization include the establishment of an independent state of [[Balochistan (region)|Balochistan]] separate from [[Pakistan]] and [[Iran]]. The name Baloch Liberation Army first became public in summer 2000, after the organization claimed credit for a series of bomb attacks in markets and railways lines. The BLA has also claimed responsibility for the systematic ethnic genocide of [[Punjabis]], [[Pashtuns]] and [[Sindhis]] in Balochistan (about 25,000 as of July 2010) as well as blowing up of gas pipelines.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.samaa.tv/news/2018/05/gunmen-kill-six-labourers-in-balochistan-police/|title=Gunmen kill six labourers in Balochistan: police|date=4 May 2018|work=Samaa Tv}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1325031|title=Four Sindhi labourers gunned down in Balochistan|date=5 April 2017|work=Dawn News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nation.com.pk/14-May-2017/bla-kills-10-sindhi-labourers-in-gwadar|date=14 May 2017|work=The Nation|title=BLA kills 10 Sindhi labourers in Gwadar}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2015/06/cracking-pakistans-baloch-insurgency/|title=Understanding Pakistan\u2019s Baloch Insurgency|date=24 June 2015|work=The Diplomat}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/733754|title=Abductors kill seven coal miners in Balochistan|date=12 July 2012|work=Dawn News}}</ref> Local [[Baloch people|Balochs]] have also been targeted by the separatist groups in the province.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.huffpost.com/us/entry/6090920|title=The End of Pakistan\u2019s Baloch Insurgency?|date=11 March 2014|work=Huffington Post}}</ref> [[Brahamdagh Khan Bugti]], alleged leader of Baloch liberation army (BLA), also asked separatists to conduct ethnic cleansing of Non-Baloch citizens from the province.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.stanford.edu/group/mappingmilitants/cgi-bin/groups/view/297|title=Baloch Liberation Army|quote=Some human rights organizations accuse the BLA of ethnic cleansing because on April 15, 2009 during an interview on AAJ TV, alleged leader Brahamdagh Khan Bugti urged separatist to kill any non-native Balochi residing in Balochistan which allegedly led to the deaths of 500 non-Baloch|work=Mapping Militant Organizations- web.stanford.edu|accessdate=28 June 2019}}</ref> In 2006, the BLA was declared to be a [[terrorist organization]] by the [[Pakistan]]i and [[United Kingdom|British]] governments.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/963704|title=Pakistan bans 25 militant organisations|date=2009-08-06|work=DAWN.COM|access-date=2018-04-19|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nHowever, the insurgency led by the Baloch separatists in the province is on its last leg. Baloch separatists have been losing their leaders and they have been unable to fill their ranks. There is also currently ongoing infighting between the different insurgents groups.<ref name=\"gan\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://stratagem.pk/armed-dangerous/factionalism-balochistan-insurgency-overview/|title=Factionalism in the Balochistan Insurgency \u2013 An overview|work=STRATAGEM|accessdate=24 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422054425/https://stratagem.pk/armed-dangerous/factionalism-balochistan-insurgency-overview/|archive-date=22 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The last insurgent leader, [[Balach Marri]], was able to keep the different insurgent groups united. However, after his death in [[Afghanistan]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/urdu/pakistan-46834089|title=Balochistan: Insurgency could directly effect the children and women of refugees|date=12 January 2019|work=BBC News|lang=Urdu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101029053351/http://www.caravanmagazine.in/Story.aspx?Storyid=514&StoryStyle=FullStory|title=India in Afghanistan|date=29 October 2010|work=Caravan Magazine}}</ref>, infighting broke out between various insurgent groups. The insurgents were unable to replace him. Similarly, Baloch separatist follow [[Marxism]]. However, the Marxism ideology died across the world and there is no other ideologies to succeed it. So the founding father of Baloch separatist are dead.<ref name=\"gan\">{{cite web|url=https://gandhara.rferl.org/a/pakistan-balochistan-separatist-insurgency-on-the-wane-despite-recent-attack/29889887.html|title=Balochistan\u2019s Separatist Insurgency On The Wane Despite Recent Attack|date=18 April 2019|work=Gandhara Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberity}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.huffpost.com/us/entry/6090920|title=The End of Pakistan\u2019s Baloch Insurgency?|work=Huffington Post|date=11 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/world/baloch-movement-stilled-by-lack-of-leadership-strategy-5963791.html|title=Baloch movement stilled by lack of leadership, strategy|date=26 January 2019|work=First Post}}</ref> Moreover, attacks on pro-government leaders and politicians who are willing to take part in election has also contributed to the decline in separatist appeal.<ref name=\"gan\"/> \n\n''The News International'' reported in 2012 that a [[Gallup (company)|Gallup]] survey conducted for [[Department for International Development|DFID]] revealed that the majority of Baloch do not support [[independence]] from Pakistan. Only 37 percent of Baloch were in favour of independence. Amongst [[Balochistan, Pakistan|Balochistan's]] [[Pashtuns|Pashtun]] population support for independence was even lower at 12 percent. However, a majority (67 percent) of Balochistan's population did favour greater provincial [[autonomy]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/archive/print/624446-37pc-baloch-favour-independence-uk-survey|title=37pc Baloch favour independence: UK survey|date=13 August 2012|work=The News International}}</ref> Majority of Baloch also don't support separatist groups. They support political parties who use legislature to address their grievances. Experts also claim that most of the nationalist in the province had come to believe that they could fight for their political right within Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.trtworld.com/asia/what-s-behind-the-baloch-insurgency-in-pakistan-25982|title=What\u2019s behind the Baloch insurgency in Pakistan?|work=TRT World|date=19 April 2019|quote=But the majority of the population does not support the hardliners and continues to back local political parties, which want to use legislature to address day-to-day grievances. Experts say most of the nationalists had come to believe that they could fight for political rights within Pakistan.}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2018, the Pakistani state was using Islamist militants to crush Balochi separatists.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Akbar |first1=Malik Siraj |title=In Balochistan, Dying Hopes for Peace |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/19/opinion/pakistan-elections-balochistan-islamic-state.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=25 September 2019 |date=19 July 2018|quote=Increasing attacks by the Islamic State in Balochistan are connected to Pakistan\u2019s failed strategy of encouraging and using Islamist militants to crush Baloch rebels and separatists.}}</ref> Academics and journalists in the United States have been approached by [[Inter-Services Intelligence]] spies, who threatened them not to speak about the [[insurgency in Balochistan]], as well as [[Human rights violations in Balochistan|human rights abuses by the Pakistani Army]], or else their families would be harmed.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mazzetti |first1=Mark |last2=Schmitt |first2=Eric |last3=Savage |first3=Charlie |title=Pakistan Spies on Its Diaspora, Spreading Fear |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/07/24/world/asia/24isi.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=25 September 2019 |date=23 July 2011|quote=Several Pakistani journalists and scholars in the United States interviewed over the past week said that they were approached regularly by Pakistani officials, some of whom openly identified themselves as ISI officials. The journalists and scholars said the officials caution them against speaking out on politically delicate subjects like the indigenous insurgency in Baluchistan or accusations of human rights abuses by Pakistani soldiers. The verbal pressure is often accompanied by veiled warnings about the welfare of family members in Pakistan, they said.}}</ref>\n\n==Sindhudesh==\n{{Main|Sindhudesh}}\n'''Sindhudesh''' ({{lang-sd|\u0633\u0646\u068c\u0648 \u062f\u064a\u0634}}, literally \"Sindhi Country\") is an idea of a separate ''[[Homeland]] for [[Sindhis]]''<ref>{{cite book|last1=Syed|first1=G. M.|title=Sindhudesh : A Study in its Separate Identity Through the Ages|url=http://gmsyed.org/sindhudesh/saeen-book3.htm|publisher=G.M. Syed Academy|page=''These days a pragmatic situation has become dynamically alive in Pakistan. It is the exhilarating political idea of creating a new independent state of Sindh. So the sons of the soil, in full cooperation should increase the momentum for the demand and efforts to create Sindhu Desh with the new Sindhis who have settled down in this land permanently.''|accessdate=13 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Dawn_sindhi\">{{cite news|title=Analysis: Sindhi nationalists stand divided|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1148698|accessdate=13 May 2018|publisher=Dawn|date=4 December 2014}}</ref> proposed by [[Sindhi nationalism|Sindhi nationalist]] parties for the creation of a [[Sindhi people|Sindhi]] state, which would be independent from  Pakistan.<ref name=\"Express Tribune\">{{cite news|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/354308/pakistan-day-jsqm-leader-demands-freedom-for-sindh-and-balochistan/|title=pakistan-day-jsqm-leader-demands-freedom-for-sindh-and-balochistan|work=Express Tribune|date=24 March 2012|accessdate=3 June 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Thenews.com.pk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thenews.com.pk/Todays-News-4-98354-JST-demands-Sindhs-independence-from-Punjabs-occupation |title=JST demands Sindh\u2019s independence from Punjab\u2019s \u2018occupation\u2019 |publisher=Thenews.com.pk |date= |accessdate=2012-06-05}}</ref> The movement is based in the [[Sindh]] region of Pakistan and was conceived by the Sindhi political leader [[G. M. Syed]]. A Sindhi literary movement emerged in 1967 under the leadership of Syed and [[Ali Muhammad Rashidi|Pir Ali Mohammed Rashdi]], in opposition to the [[One Unit]] policy, the imposition of [[Urdu]] by the central government and to the presence of a large number of [[Muhajir people|Muhajir]] (Indian Muslim refugees) settled in the province.<ref name=\"Siddiqi2012\">{{cite book|author=Farhan Hanif Hanif Siddiqi|title=The Politics of Ethnicity in Pakistan: The Baloch, Sindhi and Mohajir Ethnic Movements|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0b0epgzkrz8C&pg=PA88|accessdate=16 July 2012|date=4 May 2012|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-33696-6|pages=88\u2013}}</ref>\n\nHowever, neither the separatist party nor the nationalist party have ever been able to take centre stage in Sindh. Local Sindhis strongly support [[Pakistan People Party]] (PPP). The unparalleled and unhindered success of the PPP in Sindh shows the preference of Sindhis for a [[constitutional political process]] over a separatist agenda to resolve their grievances. Similarly public opinion is also not heavily in favour of these parties either. In other words, neither the Sindhi separatists nor the nationalists have significant popular support \u2014 certainly not the kind that will make them capable of fuelling a full-scale insurgency. Almost all of the Sindhis have a strong [[Pakistani identity]] and prefer to remain part of Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.orfonline.org/research/sindh-is-not-east-pakistan/|title=Sindh is not East Pakistan|work=[[Observer Research Foundation]] (ORF)|date=16 April 2014|author=Aakash Tolani}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, a Sindhudesh rally was organised by a nationalist party in Karachi, which had a notably low turnout. The nationalist party had claimed that they would gather around million people for their million march. Although, only 3,000 to 4,000 people attended the rally.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/351873/million-march-jeay-sindh-tehreek-gathers-3000-people-demands-a-sindhu-desh/|title=Million march: Jeay Sindh Tehreek gathers 3,000 people, demands a Sindhu Desh|work=Express Tribune|date=19 March 2012|accessdate=15 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Azad Kashmir and Gilgit-Baltistan==\n[[File:Flag of Gilgit-Baltistan United Movement.svg|250px|right|flag of Gilgit-Baltistan United Movement]]\n[[File:Gilgit-Baltistan in Pakistan (de-facto + wo Glacier) (claims hatched).svg|250px|right|thumb|Location of Gilgit-Baltistan]]\n\nAn independence movement currently exists in [[Gilgit-Baltistan]] (called \"Balawaristan\" by its supporters).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Snedden |first1=Christopher |title=Understanding Kashmir and Kashmiris |date=2015 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9781849046220 |quote=An independence movement seeking to establish Balawaristan also now exists in Gilgit-Baltistan.}}</ref> The Pakistani government has tried to \"crush ruthlessly\" the separatist movement for a free Balawaristan.<ref name=\"FH2014\">{{cite book |author1=Arch Puddington, Aili Piano, Jennifer Dunham, Bret Nelson, Tyler Roylance |title=Freedom in the World 2014: The Annual Survey of Political Rights and Civil Liberties |date=2014 |publisher=[[Rowman & Littlefield]] |isbn=9781442247079 |page=805}}</ref>\n\n[[Abdul Hamid Khan (politician)|Balawaristan National Front (Hameed Group)]] (BNF-H) led by [[Abdul Hamid Khan (politician)|Abdul Hamid Khan]] were trying to seek independence of Gilgit-Baltistan from Pakistan. However, Abdul Hamid Khan unconditionally surrendered to Pakistan security officials on 8 February 2019. Following his surrender, 14 more members of BNF-H were arrested for their anti-Pakistani activities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nation.com.pk/21-May-2019/raw-network-busted-in-gb?show=preview|title=RAW network busted in GB|date=21 May 2019|work=The Nation|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190521224017/https://nation.com.pk/21-May-2019/raw-network-busted-in-gb?show=preview|archive-date=21 May 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/world/pakistan/pakistan-security-forces-say-they-busted-subversive-network-in-gilgit/articleshow/69429977.cms|title=Pakistan security forces say they busted subversive network in Gilgit|date=21 May 2019|work=Times of India}}</ref> Since then the fate of BNF-H is unknown. Another organisation by the name of [[Balawaristan National Front]] led by Nawaz Khan Naji seeks to declare Gilgit-Balistan a fifth province of Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ali |first=Manzoor |url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/159772/gilgit-baltistan-shocker-nationalist-candidate-wins-ghizer-by-poll/ |title=Gilgit-Baltistan shocker: Nationalist candidate wins Ghizer by-poll \u2013 The Express Tribune |publisher=Tribune.com.pk |date= |accessdate=2012-05-31|quote=Naji said that the federal government should declare Gilgit-Baltistan a province of Pakistan, give its people representation in the National Assembly and Senate, and extend the jurisdiction of the Supreme Court to the region}}</ref>\n\n[[Sardar Arif Shahid]], was a Kashmiri nationalist leader who advocated the independence of Kashmir from both [[India]] and [[Pakistan]]'s rule. He was killed on May 14, 2013 outside his house in Rawalpindi. It was the first time any pro-independence Kashmiri leader was targeted in this way in Pakistan. His supporters allege that he was killed by Pakistan security forces.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-22559730|title=Kashmiris protest at killing of Sardar Arif Shahid|date=16 May 2013|work=BBC News|quote=It is the first time that a pro-independence Kashmiri leader has been targeted in this way in Pakistan. Mr Shahid led the All Parties National Alliance (APNA), which advocates independence from India and Pakistan.}}</ref> Within the area, \"Custodial torture and intimidation of independence supporters and other activists\" has occurred.<ref name=\"FH2014\" />\n\n==Jinnahpur and Muhajir Sooba==\n{{Main|Jinnahpur}}\n[[File:Karachi Locator Sindh Pakistan.PNG|thumb|right|250px|Location of [[Karachi]] where the mujahir movement is mostly based]]\n\n[[Jinnahpur]] refers to an alleged plot in [[Pakistan]] to form a breakaway autonomous state to serve as a homeland for the [[Karachi]] based [[Urdu]]-speaking [[Muhajir (Pakistan)|Muhajir]] community.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/pakistan/Pakistan-cracks-showing-as-Mohajir-leader-appeals-to-UN-US-India-for-rescue/articleshow/48333750.cms|title=Pakistan cracks showing as Mohajir leader appeals to UN, US, India for rescue}}</ref> Mohajirs are [[immigrants]] who came to Pakistan from India in the wake of the violence that followed the [[Pakistan Movement|independence]] of [[India]] in 1947.  The alleged name to be given to the proposed breakaway state was \"Jinnahpur\", named after [[Mohammed Ali Jinnah]]. In 1992, the Pakistani military claimed it had found maps of the proposed Jinnahpur state in the offices of the [[Mohajir Qaumi Movement]] (now renamed [[Muttahida Qaumi Movement]]), despite the party's strong denial of the authenticity of the maps. Despite the party's strong commitment to the Pakistani state, at that time government of [[Nawaz Sharif]] chose to use it as the basis for the military operation against the MQM, known as [[Operation Clean-up]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=dObxI9xahSYC&lpg=PA185&dq=jinnahpur&lr=&pg=PA185#v=onepage&q=&f=false The MQM of Pakistan: Between Political Party and Ethnic Movement], Mohammad Waseem, in Political parties in South Asia, ed. Mitra, Enskat & Spiess, pp185</ref> \n\nThe [[Muhajir Sooba]] (literally meaning 'Immigrant Province') is a political movement which seeks to represent the [[Muhajir people]] of [[Sindh]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Altaf for 'Sindh One' and 'Sindh Two'|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1078561|accessdate=26 September 2014|agency=Dawn.com|date=Jan 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Z|first1=Ali|title=New province: Altaf Hussain kicks up a firestorm|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/654672/new-province-altaf-hussain-kicks-up-a-firestorm/|accessdate=26 September 2014|agency=The Express Tribune|date=January 4, 2014}}</ref> This concept floated as a political bargaining tool by the leader of [[Muttahida Qaumi Movement]], Altaf Hussain for the creation of a Muhajir province for the Muhajir-majority areas of Sindh, which would be independent from Sindh government.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n* {{citation |first=Ershad |last=Mahmud |title=The Gilgit-Baltistan Reforms Package 2007: Background, Phases and Analysis |journal=Policy Perspectives |publisher=Institute of Policy Studies |location=Islamabad |volume=5 |number=1 |year=2008 |pp=23-40 |url=http://www.ips.org.pk/politics/991-the-gilgit-baltistan-reforms-package-2007-background-phases-and-analysis}}\n\n\n{{Pakistan separatist movements}}\n{{Secession in Countries}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Separatist Movements Of Pakistan}}\n[[Category:Separatism in Pakistan| ]]\n", "text_old": "There are '''separatist movements in Pakistan''' which are based on ethnic and regional nationalism, including independence movements in [[Balawaristan]],<ref name=\"FH2014\"/> Sindh, and Balochistan.<ref name=\"Express Tribune\"/> The government of Pakistan has attempted to subdue these separatist movements.<ref name=\"FH2014\"/>\n\nThe separatist movements in Sindh and Balawaristan are inactive and lack support<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.satp.org/terrorist-groups/pakistan|title=Terrorist Groups|work=South Asian Terrorism Portal Index (SATP)|accessdate=15 June 2019}}</ref> while the separatist movement in Balochistan is engaged in a low-intensity insurgency against the government \nof Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1375529|title=Over 300 anti-state militants surrender arms in Balochistan|date=9 December 2017|work=Dawn News|quote=The largest province of the country by area, Balochistan is home to a low-level insurgency by ethnic Baloch separatists.}}</ref><ref name=\"gan\"/>\n\n==History==\n{{Further|Bangladesh Liberation War}}\nPakistan was established in 1947 as a state for Muslims. The driving force behind the Pakistan Movement were the Muslims in the Muslim minority provinces of [[United Province]] and [[Bombay Presidency]] rather than the Muslims from the Muslim majority provinces.<ref name=\"AhmadRafiq2016\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nzMlDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA127|title=Pakistan's Democratic Transition: Change and Persistence|author1=Ishtiaq Ahmad|author2=Adnan Rafiq|date=3 November 2016|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-317-23595-8|pages=127\u2013}}</ref> Its formation was based on the basis of [[Religious nationalism|Islamic nationalism]]. \n\nHowever, rampant corruption within the ranks of the government and bureaucracy, economic inequality between the country's two wings caused mainly by a lack of  [[democracy|representative government]] and the government's indifference to the efforts of fierce ethno-nationalistic politicians like Mujeeb-ur-Rehman from [[East Pakistan]], resulted in [[Bangladesh Liberation War|civil war in Pakistan]] and subsequent separation of [[East Pakistan]] as the new state of the [[People's Republic of Bangladesh]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}}\n\nIn 2009, the [[Pew Research Center]] conducted a Global Attitudes survey across Pakistan, in which it questioned respondents whether they viewed their primary identity as Pakistani or that of their ethnicity. The [[Survey sampling|sample]] covered an area representing 90% of the adult population, and included all major ethnic groups.<ref name=\"PEW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pewglobal.org/2009/08/13/chapter-2-religion-law-and-society/|title=Pakistani Public Opinion \u2013 Chapter 2. Religion, Law, and Society|work=Pew Research Center|date=13 August 2009|accessdate=25 September 2017}}</ref> According to the findings, 96% of [[Punjabis]] identified themselves first as Pakistanis, as did 92% each of [[Pashtuns]] and [[Muhajir people|Muhajirs]]; 55% of [[Sindhis]] chose a Pakistani identification, while 28% chose Sindhi and 16% selected \"both equally\"; whereas 58% of [[Baloch people|Baloch]] respondents chose Pakistani and 32% selected their ethnicity and 10% chose both equally.<ref name=\"PEW\"/> Collectively, 89% of the sample opted their primary identity as Pakistani.<ref name=\"PEW\"/> Similarly in 2010, [[Chatham House]] conducted an opinion poll in the Pakistani and Indian-administered regions of [[Kashmir]] asking respondents if they [[Kashmir conflict|favoured independence]] or an accession to either countries; in [[Azad Kashmir]], 95% of respondents voted for all of Kashmir to accede to Pakistan, 4% voted for independence, and only 1% voted for accession to India.<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.chathamhouse.org/sites/files/chathamhouse/public/Research/Asia/0510pp_kashmir.pdf |title=Kashmir: Path to Peace |last=Bradnock |first=Robert W. |date=May 2010 |journal=Chatham House |doi= |pmid= |access-date= |page=15|accessdate=25 September 2017}}</ref> In the northern region of [[Gilgit-Baltistan]], longstanding local sentiments oppose any merger of the area with Kashmir, and instead demand a constitutional integration with Pakistan.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/gilgitbaltistan-a-question-of-autonomy/519428/2|title=Gilgit-Baltistan: A question of autonomy|last=Singh|first=Pallavi|date=29 April 2010|work=The Indian Express|quote=But it falls short of the main demand of the people of Gilgit- Baltistan for a constitutional status to the region as a fifth province and for Pakistani citizenship to its people.|access-date=25 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pakistan-election-idUSTRE5AB1ZE20091112|title=Pakistan's disputed Northern Areas go to polls|last=Shigri|first=Manzar|date=12 November 2009|work=Reuters|quote=Many of the 1.5 million people of Gilgit-Baltistan oppose integration into Kashmir and want their area to be merged into Pakistan and declared a separate province.|access-date=25 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Gregory2015\">{{cite book|author=Victoria Schofield|editor=Shaun Gregory|title=Democratic Transition and Security in Pakistan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=acfMCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA147|date=23 October 2015|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-55011-2|pages=147\u2013|chapter=Kashmir and its regional context}}</ref><ref name=\"Manchanda2015\">{{cite book|author=Rita Manchanda|title=SAGE Series in Human Rights Audits of Peace Processes: Five-Volume Set|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bipPDAAAQBAJ&pg=RA2-PA8|date=16 March 2015|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=978-93-5150-213-5|pages=2\u2013}}</ref>\n\n== Balochistan ==\n{{Further|Insurgency in Balochistan}}\nThe [[Baloch Liberation Front]] (BLF) separatist group was founded by [[Jumma Khan Marri]] in 1964 in [[Damascus]], and played an important role in the 1968-1980 insurgency in [[Balochistan (Pakistan)|Pakistani Balochistan]] and [[Iranian Balochistan]]. Mir Hazar Ramkhani, the father of [[Jumma Khan Marri]], took over the group in the 1980s. The Balochistan Liberation Army (also Baloch Liberation Army or Baluchistan Liberation army) (BLA) is a [[Baloch nationalist]] militant secessionist organization. However, [[Jumma Khan Marri]] ended his opposition and pledged allegiance to Pakistan on 17 February 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1390521|title=Baloch leader distances himself from separatist movement|date=20 February 2018|work=Dawn News}}</ref> The stated goals of the organization include the establishment of an independent state of [[Balochistan (region)|Balochistan]] separate from [[Pakistan]] and [[Iran]]. The name Baloch Liberation Army first became public in summer 2000, after the organization claimed credit for a series of bomb attacks in markets and railways lines. The BLA has also claimed responsibility for the systematic ethnic genocide of [[Punjabis]], [[Pashtuns]] and [[Sindhis]] in Balochistan (about 25,000 as of July 2010) as well as blowing up of gas pipelines.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.samaa.tv/news/2018/05/gunmen-kill-six-labourers-in-balochistan-police/|title=Gunmen kill six labourers in Balochistan: police|date=4 May 2018|work=Samaa Tv}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1325031|title=Four Sindhi labourers gunned down in Balochistan|date=5 April 2017|work=Dawn News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nation.com.pk/14-May-2017/bla-kills-10-sindhi-labourers-in-gwadar|date=14 May 2017|work=The Nation|title=BLA kills 10 Sindhi labourers in Gwadar}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2015/06/cracking-pakistans-baloch-insurgency/|title=Understanding Pakistan\u2019s Baloch Insurgency|date=24 June 2015|work=The Diplomat}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/733754|title=Abductors kill seven coal miners in Balochistan|date=12 July 2012|work=Dawn News}}</ref> Local [[Baloch people|Balochs]] have also been targeted by the separatist groups in the province.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.huffpost.com/us/entry/6090920|title=The End of Pakistan\u2019s Baloch Insurgency?|date=11 March 2014|work=Huffington Post}}</ref> [[Brahamdagh Khan Bugti]], alleged leader of Baloch liberation army (BLA), also asked separatists to conduct ethnic cleansing of Non-Baloch citizens from the province.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.stanford.edu/group/mappingmilitants/cgi-bin/groups/view/297|title=Baloch Liberation Army|quote=Some human rights organizations accuse the BLA of ethnic cleansing because on April 15, 2009 during an interview on AAJ TV, alleged leader Brahamdagh Khan Bugti urged separatist to kill any non-native Balochi residing in Balochistan which allegedly led to the deaths of 500 non-Baloch|work=Mapping Militant Organizations- web.standford.edu|accessdate=28 June 2019}}</ref> In 2006, the BLA was declared to be a [[terrorist organization]] by the [[Pakistan]]i and [[United Kingdom|British]] governments.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/963704|title=Pakistan bans 25 militant organisations|date=2009-08-06|work=DAWN.COM|access-date=2018-04-19|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nHowever, the insurgency led by the Baloch separatists in the province is on its last leg. Baloch separatists have been losing their leaders and they have been unable to fill their ranks. There is also currently ongoing infighting between the different insurgents groups.<ref name=\"gan\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://stratagem.pk/armed-dangerous/factionalism-balochistan-insurgency-overview/|title=Factionalism in the Balochistan Insurgency \u2013 An overview|work=STRATAGEM|accessdate=24 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422054425/https://stratagem.pk/armed-dangerous/factionalism-balochistan-insurgency-overview/|archive-date=22 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The last insurgent leader, [[Balach Marri]], was able to keep the different insurgent groups united. However, after his death in [[Afghanistan]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/urdu/pakistan-46834089|title=Balochistan: Insurgency could directly effect the children and women of refugees|date=12 January 2019|work=BBC News|lang=Urdu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101029053351/http://www.caravanmagazine.in/Story.aspx?Storyid=514&StoryStyle=FullStory|title=India in Afghanistan|date=29 October 2010|work=Caravan Magazine}}</ref>, infighting broke out between various insurgent groups. The insurgents were unable to replace him. Similarly, Baloch separatist follow [[Marxism]]. However, the Marxism ideology died across the world and there is no other ideologies to succeed it. So the founding father of Baloch separatist are dead.<ref name=\"gan\">{{cite web|url=https://gandhara.rferl.org/a/pakistan-balochistan-separatist-insurgency-on-the-wane-despite-recent-attack/29889887.html|title=Balochistan\u2019s Separatist Insurgency On The Wane Despite Recent Attack|date=18 April 2019|work=Gandhara Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberity}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.huffpost.com/us/entry/6090920|title=The End of Pakistan\u2019s Baloch Insurgency?|work=Huffington Post|date=11 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/world/baloch-movement-stilled-by-lack-of-leadership-strategy-5963791.html|title=Baloch movement stilled by lack of leadership, strategy|date=26 January 2019|work=First Post}}</ref> Moreover, attacks on pro-government leaders and politicians who are willing to take part in election has also contributed to the decline in separatist appeal.<ref name=\"gan\"/> \n\n''The News International'' reported in 2012 that a [[Gallup (company)|Gallup]] survey conducted for [[Department for International Development|DFID]] revealed that the majority of Baloch do not support [[independence]] from Pakistan. Only 37 percent of Baloch were in favour of independence. Amongst [[Balochistan, Pakistan|Balochistan's]] [[Pashtuns|Pashtun]] population support for independence was even lower at 12 percent. However, a majority (67 percent) of Balochistan's population did favour greater provincial [[autonomy]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/archive/print/624446-37pc-baloch-favour-independence-uk-survey|title=37pc Baloch favour independence: UK survey|date=13 August 2012|work=The News International}}</ref> Majority of Baloch also don't support separatist groups. They support political parties who use legislature to address their grievances. Experts also claim that most of the nationalist in the province had come to believe that they could fight for their political right within Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.trtworld.com/asia/what-s-behind-the-baloch-insurgency-in-pakistan-25982|title=What\u2019s behind the Baloch insurgency in Pakistan?|work=TRT World|date=19 April 2019|quote=But the majority of the population does not support the hardliners and continues to back local political parties, which want to use legislature to address day-to-day grievances. Experts say most of the nationalists had come to believe that they could fight for political rights within Pakistan.}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2018, the Pakistani state was using Islamist militants to crush Balochi separatists.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Akbar |first1=Malik Siraj |title=In Balochistan, Dying Hopes for Peace |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/19/opinion/pakistan-elections-balochistan-islamic-state.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=25 September 2019 |date=19 July 2018|quote=Increasing attacks by the Islamic State in Balochistan are connected to Pakistan\u2019s failed strategy of encouraging and using Islamist militants to crush Baloch rebels and separatists.}}</ref> Academics and journalists in the United States have been approached by [[Inter-Services Intelligence]] spies, who threatened them not to speak about the [[insurgency in Balochistan]], as well as [[Human rights violations in Balochistan|human rights abuses by the Pakistani Army]], or else their families would be harmed.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mazzetti |first1=Mark |last2=Schmitt |first2=Eric |last3=Savage |first3=Charlie |title=Pakistan Spies on Its Diaspora, Spreading Fear |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/07/24/world/asia/24isi.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=25 September 2019 |date=23 July 2011|quote=Several Pakistani journalists and scholars in the United States interviewed over the past week said that they were approached regularly by Pakistani officials, some of whom openly identified themselves as ISI officials. The journalists and scholars said the officials caution them against speaking out on politically delicate subjects like the indigenous insurgency in Baluchistan or accusations of human rights abuses by Pakistani soldiers. The verbal pressure is often accompanied by veiled warnings about the welfare of family members in Pakistan, they said.}}</ref>\n\n==Sindhudesh==\n{{Main|Sindhudesh}}\n'''Sindhudesh''' ({{lang-sd|\u0633\u0646\u068c\u0648 \u062f\u064a\u0634}}, literally \"Sindhi Country\") is an idea of a separate ''[[Homeland]] for [[Sindhis]]''<ref>{{cite book|last1=Syed|first1=G. M.|title=Sindhudesh : A Study in its Separate Identity Through the Ages|url=http://gmsyed.org/sindhudesh/saeen-book3.htm|publisher=G.M. Syed Academy|page=''These days a pragmatic situation has become dynamically alive in Pakistan. It is the exhilarating political idea of creating a new independent state of Sindh. So the sons of the soil, in full cooperation should increase the momentum for the demand and efforts to create Sindhu Desh with the new Sindhis who have settled down in this land permanently.''|accessdate=13 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Dawn_sindhi\">{{cite news|title=Analysis: Sindhi nationalists stand divided|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1148698|accessdate=13 May 2018|publisher=Dawn|date=4 December 2014}}</ref> proposed by [[Sindhi nationalism|Sindhi nationalist]] parties for the creation of a [[Sindhi people|Sindhi]] state, which would be independent from  Pakistan.<ref name=\"Express Tribune\">{{cite news|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/354308/pakistan-day-jsqm-leader-demands-freedom-for-sindh-and-balochistan/|title=pakistan-day-jsqm-leader-demands-freedom-for-sindh-and-balochistan|work=Express Tribune|date=24 March 2012|accessdate=3 June 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Thenews.com.pk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thenews.com.pk/Todays-News-4-98354-JST-demands-Sindhs-independence-from-Punjabs-occupation |title=JST demands Sindh\u2019s independence from Punjab\u2019s \u2018occupation\u2019 |publisher=Thenews.com.pk |date= |accessdate=2012-06-05}}</ref> The movement is based in the [[Sindh]] region of Pakistan and was conceived by the Sindhi political leader [[G. M. Syed]]. A Sindhi literary movement emerged in 1967 under the leadership of Syed and [[Ali Muhammad Rashidi|Pir Ali Mohammed Rashdi]], in opposition to the [[One Unit]] policy, the imposition of [[Urdu]] by the central government and to the presence of a large number of [[Muhajir people|Muhajir]] (Indian Muslim refugees) settled in the province.<ref name=\"Siddiqi2012\">{{cite book|author=Farhan Hanif Hanif Siddiqi|title=The Politics of Ethnicity in Pakistan: The Baloch, Sindhi and Mohajir Ethnic Movements|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0b0epgzkrz8C&pg=PA88|accessdate=16 July 2012|date=4 May 2012|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-33696-6|pages=88\u2013}}</ref>\n\nHowever, neither the separatist party nor the nationalist party have ever been able to take centre stage in Sindh. Local Sindhis strongly support [[Pakistan People Party]] (PPP). The unparalleled and unhindered success of the PPP in Sindh shows the preference of Sindhis for a [[constitutional political process]] over a separatist agenda to resolve their grievances. Similarly public opinion is also not heavily in favour of these parties either. In other words, neither the Sindhi separatists nor the nationalists have significant popular support \u2014 certainly not the kind that will make them capable of fuelling a full-scale insurgency. Almost all of the Sindhis have a strong [[Pakistani identity]] and prefer to remain part of Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.orfonline.org/research/sindh-is-not-east-pakistan/|title=Sindh is not East Pakistan|work=[[Observer Research Foundation]] (ORF)|date=16 April 2014|author=Aakash Tolani}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, a Sindhudesh rally was organised by a nationalist party in Karachi, which had a notably low turnout. The nationalist party had claimed that they would gather around million people for their million march. Although, only 3,000 to 4,000 people attended the rally.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/351873/million-march-jeay-sindh-tehreek-gathers-3000-people-demands-a-sindhu-desh/|title=Million march: Jeay Sindh Tehreek gathers 3,000 people, demands a Sindhu Desh|work=Express Tribune|date=19 March 2012|accessdate=15 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Azad Kashmir and Gilgit-Baltistan==\n[[File:Flag of Gilgit-Baltistan United Movement.svg|250px|right|flag of Gilgit-Baltistan United Movement]]\n[[File:Gilgit-Baltistan in Pakistan (de-facto + wo Glacier) (claims hatched).svg|250px|right|thumb|Location of Gilgit-Baltistan]]\n\nAn independence movement currently exists in [[Gilgit-Baltistan]] (called \"Balawaristan\" by its supporters).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Snedden |first1=Christopher |title=Understanding Kashmir and Kashmiris |date=2015 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9781849046220 |quote=An independence movement seeking to establish Balawaristan also now exists in Gilgit-Baltistan.}}</ref> The Pakistani government has tried to \"crush ruthlessly\" the separatist movement for a free Balawaristan.<ref name=\"FH2014\">{{cite book |author1=Arch Puddington, Aili Piano, Jennifer Dunham, Bret Nelson, Tyler Roylance |title=Freedom in the World 2014: The Annual Survey of Political Rights and Civil Liberties |date=2014 |publisher=[[Rowman & Littlefield]] |isbn=9781442247079 |page=805}}</ref>\n\n[[Abdul Hamid Khan (politician)|Balawaristan National Front (Hameed Group)]] (BNF-H) led by [[Abdul Hamid Khan (politician)|Abdul Hamid Khan]] were trying to seek independence of Gilgit-Baltistan from Pakistan. However, Abdul Hamid Khan unconditionally surrendered to Pakistan security officials on 8 February 2019. Following his surrender, 14 more members of BNF-H were arrested for their anti-Pakistani activities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nation.com.pk/21-May-2019/raw-network-busted-in-gb?show=preview|title=RAW network busted in GB|date=21 May 2019|work=The Nation|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190521224017/https://nation.com.pk/21-May-2019/raw-network-busted-in-gb?show=preview|archive-date=21 May 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/world/pakistan/pakistan-security-forces-say-they-busted-subversive-network-in-gilgit/articleshow/69429977.cms|title=Pakistan security forces say they busted subversive network in Gilgit|date=21 May 2019|work=Times of India}}</ref> Since then the fate of BNF-H is unknown. Another organisation by the name of [[Balawaristan National Front]] led by Nawaz Khan Naji seeks to declare Gilgit-Balistan a fifth province of Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ali |first=Manzoor |url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/159772/gilgit-baltistan-shocker-nationalist-candidate-wins-ghizer-by-poll/ |title=Gilgit-Baltistan shocker: Nationalist candidate wins Ghizer by-poll \u2013 The Express Tribune |publisher=Tribune.com.pk |date= |accessdate=2012-05-31|quote=Naji said that the federal government should declare Gilgit-Baltistan a province of Pakistan, give its people representation in the National Assembly and Senate, and extend the jurisdiction of the Supreme Court to the region}}</ref>\n\n[[Sardar Arif Shahid]], was a Kashmiri nationalist leader who advocated the independence of Kashmir from both [[India]] and [[Pakistan]]'s rule. He was killed on May 14, 2013 outside his house in Rawalpindi. It was the first time any pro-independence Kashmiri leader was targeted in this way in Pakistan. His supporters allege that he was killed by Pakistan security forces.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-22559730|title=Kashmiris protest at killing of Sardar Arif Shahid|date=16 May 2013|work=BBC News|quote=It is the first time that a pro-independence Kashmiri leader has been targeted in this way in Pakistan. Mr Shahid led the All Parties National Alliance (APNA), which advocates independence from India and Pakistan.}}</ref> Within the area, \"Custodial torture and intimidation of independence supporters and other activists\" has occurred.<ref name=\"FH2014\" />\n\n==Jinnahpur and Muhajir Sooba==\n{{Main|Jinnahpur}}\n[[File:Karachi Locator Sindh Pakistan.PNG|thumb|right|250px|Location of [[Karachi]] where the mujahir movement is mostly based]]\n\n[[Jinnahpur]] refers to an alleged plot in [[Pakistan]] to form a breakaway autonomous state to serve as a homeland for the [[Karachi]] based [[Urdu]]-speaking [[Muhajir (Pakistan)|Muhajir]] community.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/pakistan/Pakistan-cracks-showing-as-Mohajir-leader-appeals-to-UN-US-India-for-rescue/articleshow/48333750.cms|title=Pakistan cracks showing as Mohajir leader appeals to UN, US, India for rescue}}</ref> Mohajirs are [[immigrants]] who came to Pakistan from India in the wake of the violence that followed the [[Pakistan Movement|independence]] of [[India]] in 1947.  The alleged name to be given to the proposed breakaway state was \"Jinnahpur\", named after [[Mohammed Ali Jinnah]]. In 1992, the Pakistani military claimed it had found maps of the proposed Jinnahpur state in the offices of the [[Mohajir Qaumi Movement]] (now renamed [[Muttahida Qaumi Movement]]), despite the party's strong denial of the authenticity of the maps. Despite the party's strong commitment to the Pakistani state, at that time government of [[Nawaz Sharif]] chose to use it as the basis for the military operation against the MQM, known as [[Operation Clean-up]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=dObxI9xahSYC&lpg=PA185&dq=jinnahpur&lr=&pg=PA185#v=onepage&q=&f=false The MQM of Pakistan: Between Political Party and Ethnic Movement], Mohammad Waseem, in Political parties in South Asia, ed. Mitra, Enskat & Spiess, pp185</ref> \n\nThe [[Muhajir Sooba]] (literally meaning 'Immigrant Province') is a political movement which seeks to represent the [[Muhajir people]] of [[Sindh]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Altaf for 'Sindh One' and 'Sindh Two'|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1078561|accessdate=26 September 2014|agency=Dawn.com|date=Jan 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Z|first1=Ali|title=New province: Altaf Hussain kicks up a firestorm|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/654672/new-province-altaf-hussain-kicks-up-a-firestorm/|accessdate=26 September 2014|agency=The Express Tribune|date=January 4, 2014}}</ref> This concept floated as a political bargaining tool by the leader of [[Muttahida Qaumi Movement]], Altaf Hussain for the creation of a Muhajir province for the Muhajir-majority areas of Sindh, which would be independent from Sindh government.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n* {{citation |first=Ershad |last=Mahmud |title=The Gilgit-Baltistan Reforms Package 2007: Background, Phases and Analysis |journal=Policy Perspectives |publisher=Institute of Policy Studies |location=Islamabad |volume=5 |number=1 |year=2008 |pp=23-40 |url=http://www.ips.org.pk/politics/991-the-gilgit-baltistan-reforms-package-2007-background-phases-and-analysis}}\n\n\n{{Pakistan separatist movements}}\n{{Secession in Countries}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Separatist Movements Of Pakistan}}\n[[Category:Separatism in Pakistan| ]]\n", "name_user": "Wikiacc", "label": "safe", "comment": "\"standford\" (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Separatist_movements_of_Pakistan"}
{"title_page": "Qira County", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name = Qira County\n|native_name = {{nobold|{{lang|ug|\u0686\u0649\u0631\u0627 \u0646\u0627\u06be\u0649\u064a\u0649\u0633\u0649}}<br/>{{lower|0.2em|{{lang|zh-hans|\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf}}}}}}\n|other_name = Chira, Cele\n|seat_type =\n|settlement_type = [[Counties of China|County]]\n|image_skyline = \n|image_map = Location of Chira within Xinjiang (China).png\n|map_caption = Location of the county in Hotan Prefecture (yellow) and Xinjiang\n|pushpin_map = China Xinjiang\n|pushpin_label = Qira\n|pushpin_map_caption = Location of the seat in Xinjiang\n|parts  = 2 [[Towns of China|towns]], 6 [[Townships of China|townships]]\n|parts_type  = [[Township-level divisions]]\n|subdivision_type = Country\n|subdivision_name = [[China|People's Republic of China]]\n|subdivision_type1 = [[Autonomous regions of China|Autonomous region]]\n|subdivision_name1 = [[Xinjiang]]\n|subdivision_type2 = [[Administrative divisions of China#Prefecture level|Prefecture]]\n|subdivision_name2 = [[Hotan Prefecture]]\n|area_total_km2 = 31688.01\n|area_footnotes = <ref name=\"govxjcl\"/><ref name=\"xzqhqira\"/>\n|population_total = 147050\n|population_as_of = 2010\n|population_footnotes = <ref name=\"xzqhqira\"/>\n|population_density_km2 = auto\n|population_density_urban_km2 = auto\n|demographics_type2              = [[List of ethnic groups in China|Ethnic groups]]\n|demographics2_title1            = Major ethnic groups\n|demographics2_info1             = [[Uyghurs|Uyghur]]<ref name=\"govxjcl\"/><ref name=\"1997govqiracounty\">{{cite web|url=http://www.xzqh.org/html/show/xj/22419.html|script-title=zh:1997\u5e74\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u884c\u653f\u533a\u5212|trans-title=1997 Qira County Administrative Divisions|date=6 January 2011|accessdate=3 April 2020|website=XZQH.org|quote={{lang|zh-hans|\u548c\u7530\u5730\u533a\u8f96\u53bf\u3002\u4f4d\u4e8e\u6606\u4ed1\u5c71\u5317\u9e93\u3001\u5854\u514b\u62c9\u739b\u5e72\u6c99\u6f20\u5357\u7f18\u3002\u9762\u79ef3.6\u4e07\u5e73\u65b9\u5343\u7c73\uff0c\u4eba\u53e312.6\u4e07\uff0c\u6709\u7ef4\u543e\u5c14\u3001\u6c49\u3001\u56de\u3001\u85cf\u3001\u58ee\u7b49\u6c11\u65cf\u3002\u5176\u4e2d\u7ef4\u543e\u5c14\u65cf\u536098.4\uff05\uff0c\u8f961\u95477\u4e61\u3002}}}}</ref>\n|coordinates = {{Coord|37|00|N|80|48|E|type:adm3rd_region:CN-65|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_ft = \n|elevation_m = \n|timezone = [[China Standard Time|China Standard]]\n|utc_offset = +8\n|postal_code_type = Postal code\n|postal_code = 848300\n|website = {{URL|xjcl.gov.cn}} {{in lang|zh-hans}}\n}}\n{{Chinese\n|ibox-order=ug, zh\n|s={{linktext|\u7b56\u52d2|\u53bf}}\n|t={{linktext|\u7b56\u52d2|\u7e23}}\n|w=Ts\u02bb\u00ea\u2074-l\u00ea\u2074 Hsien\u2074\n|p=C\u00e8l\u00e8 Xi\u00e0n\n|uig=\u0686\u0649\u0631\u0627 \u0646\u0627\u06be\u0649\u064a\u0649\u0633\u0649\n|uly=Chira Nahiyisi\n|uyy=Qira Nah\u0321iyisi\n|sgs=Qira Nahiyisi\n|usy=\u0427\u0438\u0440\u0430 \u041d\u0430\u04bb\u0438\u0439\u0438\u0441\u0438\n|order=st\n}}\n'''Qira County'''<ref>The official spelling is \"Qira\" according to ''Zh\u014dnggu\u00f3 d\u00ecm\u00edngl\u00f9'' {{lang|zh-hans|\u4e2d\u56fd\u5730\u540d\u5f55}} (Beijing, ''[[SinoMaps Press]]'' 1997); {{ISBN|7-5031-1718-4}}; p. 308.</ref><ref name=\"3rdedition\">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/CompleteAtlasOfTheWorld3rdEdition2016/page/n239|title=Complete Atlas Of The World|edition=3|publisher=[[Penguin Random House]]|page=238|quote=Qira{...}Muztag 7282m|via=[[Internet Archive]]|date=2016}}</ref> ([[Uyghur language|Uyghur]]: {{lang|ug|\u0686\u0649\u0631\u0627 \u0646\u0627\u06be\u0649\u064a\u0649\u0633\u0649}}), alternatively '''Chira''' or '''Cele''' (from [[Mandarin Chinese]]), is a county in [[Hotan Prefecture]], [[Xinjiang|Xinjiang Uyghur Autonomous Region]], China. Almost all the residents of the county are [[Uyghurs]] and live around [[oases]] situated between the desolate [[Taklamakan Desert]] and [[Kunlun Mountains]].<ref name=\"1997govqiracounty\"/> The county is bordered to the north by [[Aksu Prefecture]], to the east by [[Yutian County, Xinjiang|Yutian / Keriya County]], to the northwest by [[Lop County]], to the southwest by [[Hotan County]] including the China-India disputed [[Aksai Chin]] area and to the south by [[Rutog County]], [[Ngari Prefecture]] in Tibet.\n\n==History==\nThe sixth century [[Dandan Oilik]] oasis town archaeological site where Buddhist shrines and texts were discovered is located in the desert of northern Qira (Chira) County.\n\nQira town (Chira), the town that is the current county seat of Qira County, has been forced to change locations on three occasions due to encroachment by the sands of the Taklamakan Desert.<ref name=\"govxjcl\"/><ref name=\"chinadaily\"/><ref name=\"landuse\"/>\n\nIn his 1900-01 expedition in the region, [[Aurel Stein]] travelled across the northern section of today's Qira County, a section of the [[Taklamakan Desert]] between today's [[Lop County]] and the [[Keriya River]]. There were several wells along the course he took.<ref name=\"qiranorth\">{{cite web|location=[[Washington, D. C.]]|url=http://legacy.lib.utexas.edu/maps/imw/txu-oclc-6654394-nj-44-3rd-ed.jpg|language=en|title=NJ 44 Ho-tien|date=1971|via=[[Perry\u2013Casta\u00f1eda Library Map Collection]]|publisher=[[U.S. Army Topographic Command]]|quote=DUNES{...}STEIN 1900-01{...}WELL{...}Ts'e-lo Ho{...}WU-LU-KO HO SHAN (MO-SHIH SHAN)}}</ref>\n\nQira County was divided from [[Yutian County, Xinjiang|Yutian / Keriya County]] in 1928/9.<ref name=\"historyqira\"/><ref name=\"cihai\">{{cite book|editor1=\u590f\u5f81\u519c|editor2=\u9648\u81f3\u7acb|script-title=zh:\u8f9e\u6d77\uff1a\u7b2c\u516d\u7248\u5f69\u56fe\u672c |trans-title=[[Cihai]] (Sixth Edition in Color) |date=September 2009|location=\u4e0a\u6d77. [[Shanghai]]|publisher=\u4e0a\u6d77\u8f9e\u4e66\u51fa\u7248\u793e. [[Shanghai Lexicographical Publishing House]].|isbn=9787532628599| language=zh|page=230| url=|quote={{lang|zh-hans|1929\u5e74\u7531\u4e8e\u9617\u53bf\uff08\u4eca\u4e8e\u7530\u53bf\uff09\u6790\u7f6e\u3002{...}\u519c\u4ea7\u6709\u5c0f\u9ea6\u3001\u7389\u7c73\u3001\u5c0f\u9ea6\u3001\u68c9\u82b1\u3001\u6cb9\u6599\u4f5c\u7269\u53ca\u751c\u74dc\u3001\u77f3\u69b4\u3001\u6838\u6843\u3001\u6843\u3001\u674f\u7b49\u3002\u755c\u4ea7\u4ee5\u9a6c\u3001\u725b\u3001\u7f8a\u4e3a\u4e3b\u3002\u5de5\u4e1a\u6709\u7535\u529b\u3001\u5efa\u6750\u3001\u8f67\u82b1\u3001\u98df\u54c1\u52a0\u5de5\uff08\u679c\u812f\uff09\u7b49\u3002}}}}</ref>\n\nIn the thirty years between the 1950s and 1980s, a significant area of farmland near the county seat was taken into the desert by blown sand.<ref>{{cite book|date=2001|chapter=The Control of Drift Sand on the Southern Fringe of the Taklamakan Desert \u2014 an Example from the Cele Oasis|authors=Ximing Zhang, Xiaoming Li, Henian Zhang|title=Sustainable Land Use in Deserts|page=350|doi=10.1007/978-3-642-59560-8_37|isbn=978-3-642-64027-8|quote=In the 30 years from the 1950s to the 1980s, shifting sand had moved about 5 km in the village of Cele located on the margin of the Cele county oasis, so that 1.333 ha farmland was desertified.}}</ref>\n\nSince the founding of Xinjiang Autonomous Region in 1955, Qira County has been part of Hotan Prefecture.<ref name=\"historyqira\">{{cite web|url=http://xjcl.gov.cn/zjcl/lsyg.htm|script-title=zh:\u5386\u53f2\u6cbf\u9769|language=zh-hans|accessdate=14 December 2019|website=\u0686\u0649\u0631\u0627 \u0646\u0627\u06be\u0649\u064a\u0649\u0633\u0649 \u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u4eba\u6c11\u653f\u5e9c|quote={{lang|zh-hans|\u6c11\u56fd17\u5e74(\u516c\u51431928\u5e74)2\u670823\u65e5\uff0c\u4e2d\u534e\u6c11\u56fd\u653f\u5e9c\u6279\u51c6\u5c06\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u4f50\u5347\u683c\u4e3a\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u6cbb\uff0c\u540c\u5e74\uff0c\u548c\u9617\u884c\u653f\u957f\u5b98\u5236\u6539\u4e3a\u548c\u7530\u884c\u653f\u957f\u5b98\u516c\u7f72\uff0c\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u96b6\u5c5e\u65b0\u7586\u7701\u548c\u9617\u884c\u653f\u957f\u5b98\u516c\u7f72\u7ba1\u8f96\u3002\u4e2d\u534e\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u56fd\u6210\u7acb\u521d\uff0c\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u96b6\u5c5e\u65b0\u7586\u7701\u548c\u9617\u884c\u653f\u516c\u7f72\uff1b1955\u5e7410\u67081\u65e5\uff0c\u65b0\u7586\u7ef4\u543e\u5c14\u81ea\u6cbb\u533a\u6210\u7acb\uff0c\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u96b6\u5c5e\u65b0\u7586\u7ef4\u543e\u5c14\u81ea\u6cbb\u533a\u548c\u7530\u5730\u533a\u3002}}}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1980s, 446 households living in the county seat were forced to relocate due to the effects of [[desertification]] which had brought the [[Taklamakan Desert]] within {{convert|1.5|km|mi}} km of their homes, sometimes burying homes in sand overnight.<ref name=\"chinadaily\">{{cite web|url=https://www.chinadaily.com.cn/life/2013-05/27/content_16536602.htm|title=Holding back the sands of time|date=27 May 2013|accessdate=15 December 2019|website=[[China Daily]]|quote=Qira county was once a kingdom on the ancient Silk Road in the days of the Eastern Han Dynasty (AD 25-220). The county seat has relocated north three times because the sands have eaten up the cultivatable land. The first relocation occurred more than 2,000 years ago and the most recent about 620 years ago. In the 1980s, the county seat faced yet another relocation because the desert was only about 1.5 km away. Many locals were forced to move because their houses were buried under sand, often overnight.{...}Memet Simay's household was one of 446 in Qira township forced to relocate in the 1980s, although the family has since returned to the area. \"When I woke up one morning, I found I couldn't open the door because of the weight of sand that had accumulated overnight. My crops were buried too, so I had no choice but to move,\" he recalled.}}</ref>\n{{quote|\"When I woke up one morning, I found I couldn't open the door because of the weight of sand that had accumulated overnight. My crops were buried too, so I had no choice but to move\" -Memet Simay, area resident<ref name=\"chinadaily\"/>}}\n\nIn 1983, the Qira research station of the [[Chinese Academy of Sciences]] was founded to combat drift sand.<ref name=\"landuse\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com.tw/books?id=EvfsCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA351&lpg=PA351|title=Sustainable Land Use in Deserts|page=351|via=[[Google Books]]|editors=Siegmar-W. Breckle, Maik Veste, Walter Wucherer|isbn=978-3-642-64027-8|last1=Breckle|first1=Siegmar-W|last2=Veste|first2=Maik|last3=Wucherer|first3=Walter|date=2012-12-06}}</ref> A transitional zone was established with help from the scientists at the station, and the sands were pushed back over {{convert|5|km|mi}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2013-09/16/content_16971364.htm|title=Scientists make land arable again|author=Cheng Yingqi|date=16 August 2013|accessdate=15 December 2019|publisher=[[China Daily]]}}</ref>{{better source|date=December 2019|reason=Could be true in some sense, but a report from the station confirming the particulars of these efforts and their confirmable effects and results is needed.}}\n\nIn 2005, a small 1,500 year-old [[Buddhist temple]] was discovered {{convert|7|km|mi|abbr=on}} from Damiku (Damagou).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/rest-of-world/Worlds-smallest-temple-discovered-in-China/articleshow/1282270.cms|title=World's smallest temple discovered in China|website=[[Times of India]]|date=2 November 2005|accessdate=16 December 2019|quote=The temple, dating back more than 1,500 years, was located about seven kilometres from the Damagou Township of Cele County.}}</ref>\n\nOn October 20, 2014, Damiku (Damagou) was changed from a township to a town.<ref name=\"xzqhqira\"/>\n\nOn January 7, 2016, areas near Nur, Bostan and Ulughsay townships in Qira County were made part of the newly-created [[Kunyu, Xinjiang|Kunyu]].<ref name=\"yimuchang\"/><ref name=\"xzqhky\"/>\n\nOn February 28, 2017, it was announced by the county government that those who reported others for stitching the '[[Star and crescent|star and crescent moon]]' insignia on their clothing or personal items or having the words '[[East Turkestan]]' on their mobile phone case, purse or other jewelry, would be eligible for cash payments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rfa.org/english/news/uyghur/searches-04042017172301.html|title=Xinjiang Police Search Uyghur Homes For 'Illegal Items'|website=[[Radio Free Asia]]|date=4 April 2017|accessdate=16 December 2019|quote=A second announcement, issued Feb. 28 by the Chira (Cele) county government, said those who report individuals for having \u201cstitched the \u2018star and crescent moon\u2019 insignia on their clothing or personal items\u201d or the words \u201cEast Turkestan\u201d\u2014referring to the name of a short-lived Uyghur republic\u2014on their mobile phone case, purse or other jewelry, were also eligible for cash payments.|translator=Mamatjan Juma|authors=Joshua Lipes, Jilil Kashgary}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017, Salamet Memetimin, the [[Communist Party of China|Communist Party]] secretary for Chaka township's Bekchan village and ethnic Uyghur, was relieved of her duties for taking her [[Marriage in Islam|nikah]] marriage vows at her home. According to the Hotan Daily, 97 officials were charged with disciplinary violations at this time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rfa.org/english/news/china/kazakh-imam-08092017121527.html|title='No Sign' of Kazakh Imam Scheduled For Release From Prison in July|website=[[Radio Free Asia]]|date=9 August 2017|accessdate=16 December 2019|quote=In March, Xinjiang authorities fired an ethnic Uyghur official for holding her wedding ceremony at home according to Islamic traditions instead of at a government-sanctioned venue. Salamet Memetimin, the communist party secretary for Chaka township\u2019s Bekchan village, in Hotan (in Chinese, Hetian) prefecture\u2019s Chira (Cele) county, was among 97 officials recently charged with disciplinary violations, according to an April 10 report by the state-run Hotan Daily newspaper. Local residents said the woman was relieved of her duties for taking her \"nikah\" marriage vows in her own home. \"I think this may be a local policy unique to Xinjiang,\" the source said. \"You have to first apply for a marriage certificate and then carry out the Islamic practice of nikah.\" \"The imams aren't allowed to perform nikah if there is no marriage certificate, or they will be sent to prison.\"}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, local government authorities in the county expected to have almost 12,000 detainees in [[Xinjiang re-education camps|vocational camps and detention centres]] and some projects related to the centres outstripped budgetary limits.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jan/11/if-you-enter-a-camp-you-never-come-out-inside-chinas-war-on-islam|title='If you enter a camp, you never come out': inside China's war on Islam|website=[[The Guardian]]|date=11 January 2019|accessdate=16 December 2019|language=zh-hans|author=Lily Kuo|quote=Some local governments are struggling to maintain this pace of spending. In neighbouring Cele county, where authorities expected to have almost 12,000 detainees in vocational camps and detention centres, a budget for 2018 says: \u201cThere are still many projects not included in the budget due to a lack of funds. The financial situation in 2018 is very severe.\u201d}}</ref>\n\nTo increase aid delivery to Xinjiang, places in Xinjiang are paired with other areas of China which can provide aid. [[Tianjin]] and Hotan are paired in this program. Through assistance from the Tianjin government, a standard football field and training center was constructed at the No. 1 Primary School in the county.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-07/08/c_138208976.htm|title=Tianjin helping Xinjiang's football development in China|date=8 July 2019|accessdate=16 December 2019|website=[[Xinhua News Agency]]|editor=Shi Yinglun|quote=Memet Azizi, director of Cele County's bureau of education, said that Tianjin's help had brought them hope for the future. With support from Tianjin, a standard football field and training center was constructed at Cele County's No. 1 Primary School.}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nThe northern part of Qira County is made up of sand dunes<ref name=\"qiranorth\"/> and ends in a straight line drawn in the [[Taklamakan Desert]] that forms part of the boundary between Hotan Prefecture and [[Aksu Prefecture]]. The area is between {{convert|1500|m|ft|abbr=on}} and {{convert|1800|m|ft|abbr=on}} above sea level.<ref name=\"govxjcl\"/>\n\nOasis areas occupy 2.9% of the total area of the county.<ref name=\"govxjcl\"/> The oasis areas along [[China National Highway 315]] include the Qira County county seat area, Gulahma and Damiku. Qaka, Ulughsay, Nur, Bostan and [[Kunyu, Xinjiang|Kunyu]]'s small exclaves in Qira County are located close to the Kunlun Mountains.<!--Basis: Google Maps-->\n\nThe southern part of Qira County is mountainous with an average elevation of {{convert|3200|m|ft|abbr=on}} above sea level.<ref name=\"govxjcl\"/> The upper reaches of the [[White Jade River]] (Yurung Kash), which provide water for [[Hotan|Hotan (Khotan)]], are found in the [[Kunlun Mountains]]<ref name=\"govxjcl\"/> of southern Qira County.<ref name=\"qirasouth\"/> Mountain passes in the area include Mandar Kol Dawan, Shalgon Dawan, Kuchkash Bulak Dawan, and Art Dawan.<ref name=\"qirasouth\"/> One of the prominent mountains in the county is Muztag<ref name=\"3rdedition\"/><ref name=\"GNISmuztag\">{{GEOnet2|32FA8826E5343774E0440003BA962ED3|Muztag   (Approved - N)}}, [[National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency|United States National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency]]</ref> (K5,<ref name=\"GNISK5\">{{GEOnet2|32FA8826E53A3774E0440003BA962ED3|K5 (Variant - V)}}, [[National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency|United States National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency]]</ref> Wu-lu-ko Ho Shan,<ref name=\"qiranorth\"/> Mo-shih Shan,<ref name=\"qiranorth\"/> Mu-shih Shan,<ref name=\"GNISmushihshan\">{{GEOnet2|32FA8826E5393774E0440003BA962ED3|Mu-shih Shan   (Variant - V)}}, [[National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency|United States National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency]]</ref> Muztagh Jilga;<ref name=\"qirasouth\"/> {{lang|zh|\u6155\u58eb\u5c71}},<ref name=\"GNISmushishan\">{{GEOnet2|AD4CEC26540D4485866711038E92B7DD|\u6155\u58eb\u5c71   (Non-Roman Script - NS)}}, [[National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency|United States National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency]]</ref> {{lang|zh|\u6728\u65af\u5c71}}<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/shijiedituji00ditu/page/66|script-title=zh:\u4e16\u754c\u5730\u56fe\u96c6|language=zh|date=1958|publisher=\u5730\u5716\u51fa\u7248\u793e|edition=1|id = [[:zh:\u7edf\u4e00\u4e66\u53f7|\u7edf\u4e00\u4e66\u53f7 (National Standard Book Number of China)]] 12014\u00b7449 |location= [[Beijing]]|page=66|quote=\u7b56\u52d2{...}\u6728\u65af\u5c71}}</ref>) which is {{convert|7282|m|ft|abbr=on}} above sea level.<ref name=\"3rdedition\"/> The [[meltwater]] from this mountain creates the Qira River (Cele River, Ts'e-lo Ho;<ref name=\"qiranorth\"/> {{lang|zh|\u7b56\u52d2\u6cb3}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sn.xinhuanet.com/2019-07/20/c_1124777517.htm|website=[[Xinhua News Agency]]|date=20 July 2019|accessdate=16 December 2019|language=zh-hans|script-title=zh:\u3010\u65b0\u7586\u662f\u4e2a\u597d\u5730\u65b9\u3011 \u201c\u98de\u2018\u9605\u2019\u65b0\u7586\u201d\u4e4b\u516b\uff1a\u6606\u4ed1\u5c71\u4e0b\u201c\u4e16\u5916\u6843\u6e90\u201d\u5367\u9f99\u8c37 \u6258\u8d77\u6751\u6c11\u81f4\u5bcc\u65b0\u5e0c\u671b|quote={{lang|zh-hans|\u5367\u9f99\u8c37\u4f4d\u4e8e\u65b0\u7586\u548c\u7530\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u6070\u54c8\u4e61\u7389\u5982\u514b\u5854\u4ec0\u6751\uff0c\u5728\u5b83\u7684\u6000\u62b1\u91cc\uff0c\u7b56\u52d2\u6cb3\u5e26\u7740\u8fd9\u91cc\u4eba\u7684\u559c\u6012\u54c0\u4e50\u60a0\u60a0\u5730\u6d41\u5411\u8fdc\u65b9\u3002}}}}</ref>) which flows through Qaka into the Qira county seat.<ref name=\"qiranorth\"/>\n\nIn the mid-20th century, camping grounds in the sparsely populated southern mountainous area of the county included Chotma, Yangi kan, Zaiuk, Yaskako Tagh, Mandar Chap, and Chumik.<ref name=\"qirasouth\">{{cite web|location=[[Washington, D. C.]]|url=http://legacy.lib.utexas.edu/maps/imw/txu-oclc-6654394-ni-44-3rd-ed.jpg|language=en|title=NI 44 Pangong Tso|date=1950|via=[[Perry\u2013Casta\u00f1eda Library Map Collection]]|publisher=[[Army Map Service]]|quote=Muztagh Jilga{...}Yurung Kash{...}Chotma (Camping ground){...}Yangi kan (Camping ground){...}Zaiuk (Camping ground){...}Yaskako Tagh (Camping ground){...}Mandar Chap (Camping ground){...}Chumik (Camping ground){...}Mandar Kol Dawan{...}Shalgon Dawan{...}Kuchkash Bulak Dawan{...}Art Dawan}}</ref>\n\n==Administrative divisions==\nQira County includes two [[Town (China)|towns]] and six [[Township (China)|townships]] and one other area:<ref name=\"govxjcl\">{{cite web|url=http://xjcl.gov.cn/zjcl/clgk.htm|script-title=zh:\u7b56\u52d2\u6982\u51b5|language=zh-hans|accessdate=14 December 2019|quote={{lang|zh-hans|\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u4f4d\u4e8e\u65b0\u7586\u6700\u5357\u7aef\uff0c\u5357\u6795\u6606\u4ed1\u5c71\u3001\u5317\u4e34\u5854\u514b\u62c9\u739b\u5e72\u5927\u6c99\u6f20\uff0c\u53bf\u57df\u603b\u9762\u79ef3.16\u4e07\u5e73\u65b9\u516c\u91cc\u3002\u5168\u53bf\u5730\u52bf\u603b\u4f53\u5357\u9ad8\u5317\u4f4e\uff0c\u5c71\u533a\u5e73\u5747\u6d77\u62d43200\u7c73\uff0c\u5e73\u539f\u533a\u6d77\u62d41500\u20141800\u7c73\u3002{...}\u53bf\u5883\u5185\u53ef\u4f9b\u4eba\u7c7b\u751f\u5b58\u7684\u7eff\u6d32\u9762\u79ef\u4ec5\u53602.9%\uff0c\u4e14\u88ab\u6c99\u6f20\u548c\u6208\u58c1\u5206\u5272\u5305\u56f4\u6210\u5927\u5c0f\u4e0d\u7b49\u768472\u5757\uff0c\u5386\u53f2\u4e0a\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u57ce\u56e0\u98ce\u6c99\u4fb5\u88ad\u4e09\u6b21\u88ab\u8feb\u642c\u8fc1\u3002\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u603b\u4eba\u53e316.8\u4e07\u4eba\uff0c\u7ef4\u543e\u5c14\u65cf\u5360\u603b\u4eba\u53e3\u768498%\u4ee5\u4e0a\u3002\u5168\u53bf\u8f966\u4e612\u95471\u8857\u9053\uff0c}}|website=\u0686\u0649\u0631\u0627 \u0646\u0627\u06be\u0649\u064a\u0649\u0633\u0649 \u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u4eba\u6c11\u653f\u5e9c}}</ref><ref name=\"xzqhqira\">{{cite web |url=http://www.xzqh.org/html/show/xj/22421.html|script-title=zh:\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u5386\u53f2\u6cbf\u9769 |trans-title=Qira County Historical Development |publisher=XZQH.org |date=2 December 2014 |language=zh-hans |accessdate=14 December 2019 |quote={{lang|zh-hans|2000\u5e74\u7b2c\u4e94\u6b21\u4eba\u53e3\u666e\u67e5\uff0c\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u5e38\u4f4f\u603b\u4eba\u53e3132139\u4eba\uff0c{...}2003\u5e74\uff0c\u5168\u53bf\u603b\u9762\u79ef31688.01\u5e73\u65b9\u5343\u7c73\uff0c{...}2010\u5e74\u7b2c\u516d\u6b21\u4eba\u53e3\u666e\u67e5\uff0c\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u5e38\u4f4f\u603b\u4eba\u53e3147050\u4eba\uff0c\u5176\u4e2d\uff1a\u7b56\u52d2\u954714562\u4eba\uff0c\u7b56\u52d2\u4e6131123\u4eba\uff0c\u56fa\u62c9\u54c8\u739b\u4e6126621\u4eba\uff0c\u8fbe\u739b\u6c9f\u4e6119250\u4eba\uff0c\u6070\u54c8\u4e6115010\u4eba\uff0c\u4e4c\u9c81\u514b\u8428\u4f9d\u4e614587\u4eba\uff0c\u5974\u5c14\u4e6111581\u4eba\uff0c\u535a\u65af\u5766\u4e616626\u4eba\uff0c\u8272\u65e5\u514b\u8857\u905315684\u4eba\uff0c\u5175\u56e2\u4e00\u7267\u573a2006\u4eba\u3002 2014\u5e7410\u670820\u65e5\uff0c\u81ea\u6cbb\u533a\u653f\u5e9c\uff08\u65b0\u653f\u51fd[2014]177\u53f7\uff09\u540c\u610f\u64a4\u9500\u56fa\u62c9\u5408\u739b\u4e61\uff0c\u8bbe\u7acb\u56fa\u62c9\u5408\u739b\u9547\u3002\u8c03\u6574\u540e\uff0c\u5168\u53bf\u8f962\u4e2a\u9547\u30016\u4e2a\u4e61\uff1a\u7b56\u52d2\u9547\u3001\u56fa\u62c9\u54c8\u739b\u9547\u3001\u7b56\u52d2\u4e61\u3001\u8fbe\u739b\u6c9f\u4e61\u3001\u6070\u54c8\u4e61\u3001\u4e4c\u9c81\u514b\u8428\u4f9d\u4e61\u3001\u5974\u5c14\u4e61\u3001\u535a\u65af\u5766\u4e61\u3002}}}}</ref><ref name=\"statsqira\">{{cite web |url=http://www.stats.gov.cn/tjsj/tjbz/tjyqhdmhcxhfdm/2018/65/32/653225.html |script-title=zh:2018\u5e74\u7edf\u8ba1\u7528\u533a\u5212\u4ee3\u7801\u548c\u57ce\u4e61\u5212\u5206\u4ee3\u7801\uff1a\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf |trans-title=2018 Statistical Area Numbers and Rural-Urban Area Numbers: Qira County |language=zh-hans |publisher=[[National Bureau of Statistics of the People's Republic of China]] |date=2018 |accessdate=15 December 2019 |quote={{lang|zh-hans|\u7edf\u8ba1\u7528\u533a\u5212\u4ee3\u7801 \u540d\u79f0 653225100000 \u7b56\u52d2\u9547 653225101000 \u56fa\u62c9\u5408\u739b\u9547 653225200000 \u7b56\u52d2\u4e61 653225202000 \u8fbe\u739b\u6c9f\u4e61 653225203000 \u6070\u54c8\u4e61 653225204000 \u4e4c\u9c81\u514b\u8428\u4f9d\u4e61 653225205000 \u5974\u5c14\u4e61 653225206000 \u535a\u65af\u5766\u4e61 653225500000 \u5175\u56e2\u4e00\u7267\u573a|}}}}</ref>\n\nTowns:\n*Qira<ref name=\"3rdedition\"/> (Cele, Chira; {{lang|ug|\u0686\u0649\u0631\u0627 \u0628\u0627\u0632\u0649\u0631\u0649}} / {{linktext|\u7b56\u52d2|\u9547}}), Gulahma (Gulahema, Gulakhma, Gulahama; {{lang|ug|\u06af\u06c7\u0644\u0627\u062e\u0645\u0627 \u0628\u0627\u0632\u0649\u0631\u0649}}<ref name=\"GNISgulahma\">{{GEOnet2|4079295DAF422317E0440003BA962ED3|\u06af\u06c7\u0644\u0627\u062e\u0645\u0627   (Variant Non-Roman Script - VS)}}, [[National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency|United States National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency]]</ref> / {{linktext|\u56fa\u62c9\u5408\u739b|\u9547}} ({{linktext|\u56fa\u62c9\u54c8\u739b|\u9547}}), formerly {{linktext|\u56fa\u62c9\u5408\u739b|\u4e61}})\n\nTownships:\n*Qira (Cele, Chira; {{lang|ug|\u0686\u0649\u0631\u0627 \u064a\u06d0\u0632\u0649\u0633\u0649}} / {{linktext|\u7b56\u52d2|\u4e61}}), Damiku (Damagou, Ta-mu-kou, Ha-lang-kou, Dumuka;<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.174923|title=The Pulse of Asia A Journey in Central Asia Illustrating the Geographic Basis of History|via=[[Internet Archive]]|publisher=[[Houghton Mifflin Company]]|author=Ellsworth Huntington|quote=We tried in vain to hire camles at Chira, and so went eastward a few miles to Dumuka, a neighboring village, to try again.|page=[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.174923/page/n239 171]|date=1907|author-link=Ellsworth Huntington}}</ref> {{lang|ug|\u062f\u0627\u0645\u0649\u0643\u06c7 \u064a\u06d0\u0632\u0649\u0633\u0649}}<ref name=\"GNISdamiku\">{{GEOnet2|4079295DAB222317E0440003BA962ED3|\u062f\u0627\u0645\u0649\u0643\u06c7   (Variant Non-Roman Script - VS)}}, [[National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency|United States National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency]]</ref> / {{linktext|\u8fbe\u739b\u6c9f|\u4e61}}), [[Qaka]]  (Qiaha, Chaqa, Ch'i-ko-erh, Ch'ia-ha; {{lang|ug|\u0686\u0627\u0642\u0627 \u064a\u06d0\u0632\u0649\u0633\u0649}}<ref name=\"GNISqaka\">{{GEOnet2|4079295DA9E22317E0440003BA962ED3|\u0686\u0627\u0642\u0627   (Variant Non-Roman Script - VS)}}, [[National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency|United States National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency]]</ref> / {{linktext|\u6070\u54c8|\u4e61}}), Ulughsay (Wulukesayi; {{lang|ug|\u0626\u06c7\u0644\u06c7\u063a\u0633\u0627\u064a \u064a\u06d0\u0632\u0649\u0633\u0649}} / {{linktext|\u4e4c\u9c81\u514b\u8428\u4f9d|\u4e61}}), Nur (Nu'er, Nuri; {{lang|ug|\u0646\u06c7\u0631\u0649 \u064a\u06d0\u0632\u0649\u0633\u0649}} / {{linktext|\u5974\u5c14|\u4e61}}), Bostan (Bositan; {{lang|ug|\u0628\u0648\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646 \u064a\u06d0\u0632\u0649\u0633\u0649}} / {{linktext|\u535a\u65af\u5766|\u4e61}})\n\nOther:\n* Regiment One Pasture ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5175\u56e2\u4e00\u7267\u573a}}) (part of [[Kunyu, Xinjiang|Kunyu]]<ref name=\"yimuchang\">{{cite web|url=http://www.xzqh.org/html/show/xj/37700.html|script-title=zh:\u6606\u7389\u5e02\u6982\u51b5\u5730\u56fe|language=zh-hans|date=24 February 2016|accessdate=15 December 2019|quote=\u8f964\u4e2a\u519c\u7267\u56e2\u573a\uff08\u76ae\u5c71\u519c\u573a\u3001\u4e00\u7267\u573a\u300147\u56e2\u3001224\u56e2\uff09\uff0c\u5176\u4e2d{...}\u4e00\u7267\u573a\u9a7b\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u3001}}</ref><ref name=\"xzqhky\">{{cite web|url=http://www.xzqh.org/html/show/xj/37699.html|script-title=zh:\u6606\u7389\u5e02\u5386\u53f2\u6cbf\u9769|date=24 February 2016|accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref>)\n\n==Economy==\nAgricultural products of the county include wheat, corn, cotton, petroleum products, melons, pomegranates, walnuts, peaches, and apricots. Livestock raised in the county include horses, cows and sheep. Industry in the country includes electronics, construction, cotton ginning and food processing (fruits).<ref name=\"cihai\"/>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Historical populations\n|type=China\n|percentages = pagr\n|2000|132139\n|2010|147050\n|footnote = <ref name=\"xzqhqira\"/>\n|}}\n\nAs of 2015, 163,705 of the 166,735 residents of the county were [[Uyghurs|Uyghur]], 2,921 were [[Han Chinese]] and 109 were from other ethnic groups.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.xjtj.gov.cn/sjcx/tjnj_3415/2016xjtjnj/rkjy/201707/t20170714_539450.html |language = zh-CN |script-title= zh:3-7 \u5404\u5730\u3001\u5dde\u3001\u5e02\u3001\u53bf(\u5e02)\u5206\u6c11\u65cf\u4eba\u53e3\u6570 |language=zh-hans||publisher={{lang|ug|\u0634\u0649\u0646\u062c\u0627\u06ad \u0626\u06c7\u064a\u063a\u06c7\u0631 \u0626\u0627\u067e\u062a\u0648\u0646\u0648\u0645 \u0631\u0627\u064a\u0648\u0646\u0649}} {{lang|zh-hans|\u65b0\u7586\u7ef4\u543e\u5c14\u81ea\u6cbb\u533a\u7edf\u8ba1\u5c40}} Statistic Bureau of Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region |access-date= 2017-09-03 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171011101904/http://www.xjtj.gov.cn/sjcx/tjnj_3415/2016xjtjnj/rkjy/201707/t20170714_539450.html |archive-date= 2017-10-11 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAs of the 2010s<!--Rationale: Population figure for 2010 census (\"2010\u5e74\u7b2c\u516d\u6b21\u4eba\u53e3\u666e\u67e5\uff0c\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u5e38\u4f4f\u603b\u4eba\u53e3147050\u4eba\uff0c\") is less than the figure given in this sentence (\"\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u603b\u4eba\u53e316.8\u4e07\u4eba\uff0c\u7ef4\u543e\u5c14\u65cf\u5360\u603b\u4eba\u53e3\u768498%\u4ee5\u4e0a\u3002\"), so it seems likely that this percentage was from the 2010s.-->, the population of Qira County was more than 98% [[Uyghurs|Uyghur]].<ref name=\"govxjcl\"/>\n\n==Transportation==\n* [[China National Highway 315]] runs through the Qira County county seat, Gulahma and Damiku.\n\n==Notable persons==\n* [[Ismail Amat]]\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"160\">\nFile:Johnson-journey-ilchi1865-mapa.jpg|Map including Chira (1865)\nFile:China West 1906-08 Sven Hedin.jpg|Map of the expeditions of [[Sven Hedin]] (1906-8) including Qira (labeled as Chira) ([[Royal Geographical Society|RGS]], early 20th century)\nFile:Txu-oclc-6654394-nj-44-3rd-ed.jpg|Map including Qira (labeled as TS'E-LO (CHIRA BAZAR)) and surrounding region ([[U.S. Army Topographic Command|USATC]], 1971){{efn|From map: \"DELINEATION OF INTERNATIONAL BOUNDARIES MUST NOT BE CONSIDERED AUTHORITATIVE\".}}\nFile:Txu-oclc-6654394-ni-44-3rd-ed.jpg|Map including the southern part of Qira County and the county's border with Tibet ([[Army Map Service|AMS]], 1950){{efn|From map: \"THE DELINEATION OF INTERNATIONAL BOUNDARIES ON THIS MAP MUST NOT BE CONSIDERED AUTHORITATIVE.\"}}\nFile:Operational Navigation Chart G-7, 6th edition.jpg|From the Operational Navigation Chart; map including Qira (labeled as QIRA (TS'E-LE)) ([[Defense Mapping Agency|DMA]], 1980){{efn|From map: \"The representation of international boundaries is not necessarily authoritative.\"}}\nFile:Txu-pclmaps-oclc-22834566 g-7a.jpg|Map including Qira (labeled as QIRA (TS'E-LE)) ([[Defense Mapping Agency|DMA]], 1984){{efn|From map: \"The representation of international boundaries is not necessarily authoritative\"}}\nFile:CHANTOS TAKING MELONS TO MARKET IN THE OASIS OF CHIRA.jpg|Traders in early 20th century Qira (Chira)\nFile:Mural excavated at Dandan-Uiliq CD-4.jpg|Buddhist Mural from [[Dandan Oilik]]\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Commons category}}\n\n{{Xinjiang Administrative Divisions}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:County-level divisions of Xinjiang]]\n[[Category:Hotan Prefecture]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name = Qira County\n|native_name = {{nobold|{{lang|ug|\u0686\u0649\u0631\u0627 \u0646\u0627\u06be\u0649\u064a\u0649\u0633\u0649}}<br/>{{lower|0.2em|{{lang|zh-hans|\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf}}}}}}\n|other_name = Chira, Cele\n|seat_type =\n|settlement_type = [[Counties of China|County]]\n|image_skyline = \n|image_map = Location of Chira within Xinjiang (China).png\n|map_caption = Location of the county in Hotan Prefecture (yellow) and Xinjiang\n|pushpin_map = China Xinjiang\n|pushpin_label = Qira\n|pushpin_map_caption = Location of the seat in Xinjiang\n|parts  = 2 [[Towns of China|towns]], 6 [[Townships of China|townships]]\n|parts_type  = [[Township-level divisions]]\n|subdivision_type = Country\n|subdivision_name = [[China|People's Republic of China]]\n|subdivision_type1 = [[Autonomous regions of China|Autonomous region]]\n|subdivision_name1 = [[Xinjiang]]\n|subdivision_type2 = [[Administrative divisions of China#Prefecture level|Prefecture]]\n|subdivision_name2 = [[Hotan Prefecture]]\n|area_total_km2 = 31688.01\n|area_footnotes = <ref name=\"govxjcl\"/><ref name=\"xzqhqira\"/>\n|population_total = 147050\n|population_as_of = 2010\n|population_footnotes = <ref name=\"xzqhqira\"/>\n|population_density_km2 = auto\n|population_density_urban_km2 = auto\n|demographics_type2              = [[List of ethnic groups in China|Ethnic groups]]\n|demographics2_title1            = Major ethnic groups\n|demographics2_info1             = [[Uyghurs|Uyghur]]<ref name=\"govxjcl\"/><ref name=\"1997govqiracounty\">{{cite web|url=http://www.xzqh.org/html/show/xj/22419.html|script-title=zh:1997\u5e74\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u884c\u653f\u533a\u5212|trans-title=1997 Qira County Administrative Divisions|date=6 January 2011|accessdate=3 April 2020|website=XZQH.org|quote={{lang|zh-hans|\u548c\u7530\u5730\u533a\u8f96\u53bf\u3002\u4f4d\u4e8e\u6606\u4ed1\u5c71\u5317\u9e93\u3001\u5854\u514b\u62c9\u739b\u5e72\u6c99\u6f20\u5357\u7f18\u3002\u9762\u79ef3.6\u4e07\u5e73\u65b9\u5343\u7c73\uff0c\u4eba\u53e312.6\u4e07\uff0c\u6709\u7ef4\u543e\u5c14\u3001\u6c49\u3001\u56de\u3001\u85cf\u3001\u58ee\u7b49\u6c11\u65cf\u3002\u5176\u4e2d\u7ef4\u543e\u5c14\u65cf\u536098.4\uff05\uff0c\u8f961\u95477\u4e61\u3002}}}}</ref>\n|coordinates = {{Coord|37|00|N|80|48|E|type:adm3rd_region:CN-65|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_ft = \n|elevation_m = \n|timezone = [[China Standard Time|China Standard]]\n|utc_offset = +8\n|postal_code_type = Postal code\n|postal_code = 848300\n|website = {{URL|xjcl.gov.cn}} {{in lang|zh-hans}}\n}}\n{{Chinese\n|ibox-order=ug, zh\n|s={{linktext|\u7b56\u52d2|\u53bf}}\n|t={{linktext|\u7b56\u52d2|\u7e23}}\n|w=Ts\u02bb\u00ea\u2074-l\u00ea\u2074 Hsien\u2074\n|p=C\u00e8l\u00e8 Xi\u00e0n\n|uig=\u0686\u0649\u0631\u0627 \u0646\u0627\u06be\u0649\u064a\u0649\u0633\u0649\n|uly=Chira Nahiyisi\n|uyy=Qira Nah\u0321iyisi\n|sgs=Qira Nahiyisi\n|usy=\u0427\u0438\u0440\u0430 \u041d\u0430\u04bb\u0438\u0439\u0438\u0441\u0438\n|order=st\n}}\n'''Qira County'''<ref>The official spelling is \"Qira\" according to ''Zh\u014dnggu\u00f3 d\u00ecm\u00edngl\u00f9'' {{lang|zh-hans|\u4e2d\u56fd\u5730\u540d\u5f55}} (Beijing, ''[[SinoMaps Press]]'' 1997); {{ISBN|7-5031-1718-4}}; p. 308.</ref><ref name=\"3rdedition\">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/CompleteAtlasOfTheWorld3rdEdition2016/page/n239|title=Complete Atlas Of The World|edition=3|publisher=[[Penguin Random House]]|page=238|quote=Qira{...}Muztag 7282m|via=[[Internet Archive]]|date=2016}}</ref> ([[Uyghur language|Uyghur]]: {{lang|ug|\u0686\u0649\u0631\u0627 \u0646\u0627\u06be\u0649\u064a\u0649\u0633\u0649}}), alternatively '''Chira''' or '''Cele''' (from [[Mandarin Chinese]]), is a county in [[Hotan Prefecture]], [[Xinjiang|Xinjiang Uyghur Autonomous Region]], China. Almost all the residents of the county are [[Uyghurs]] and live around [[oases]] situated between the desolate [[Taklamakan Desert]] and [[Kunlun Mountains]].<ref name=\"1997govqiracounty\"/> The county is bordered to the north by [[Aksu Prefecture]], to the east by [[Yutian County, Xinjiang|Yutian / Keriya County]], to the northwest by [[Lop County]], to the southwest by [[Hotan County]] including the China-India disputed [[Aksai Chin]] area and to the south by [[Rutog County]], [[Ngari Prefecture]] in Tibet.\n\n==History==\nThe sixth century [[Dandan Oilik]] oasis town archaeological site where Buddhist shrines and texts were discovered is located in the desert of northern Qira (Chira) County.\n\nQira town (Chira), the town that is the current county seat of Qira County, has been forced to change locations on three occasions due to encroachment by the sands of the Taklamakan Desert.<ref name=\"govxjcl\"/><ref name=\"chinadaily\"/><ref name=\"landuse\"/>\n\nIn his 1900-01 expedition in the region, [[Aurel Stein]] travelled across the northern section of today's Qira County, a section of the [[Taklamakan Desert]] between today's [[Lop County]] and the [[Keriya River]]. There were several wells along the course he took.<ref name=\"qiranorth\">{{cite web|location=[[Washington, D. C.]]|url=http://legacy.lib.utexas.edu/maps/imw/txu-oclc-6654394-nj-44-3rd-ed.jpg|language=en|title=NJ 44 Ho-tien|date=1971|via=[[Perry\u2013Casta\u00f1eda Library Map Collection]]|publisher=[[U.S. Army Topographic Command]]|quote=DUNES{...}STEIN 1900-01{...}WELL{...}Ts'e-lo Ho{...}WU-LU-KO HO SHAN (MO-SHIH SHAN)}}</ref>\n\nQira County was divided from [[Yutian County, Xinjiang|Yutian / Keriya County]] in 1928/9.<ref name=\"historyqira\"/><ref name=\"cihai\">{{cite book|editor1=\u590f\u5f81\u519c|editor2=\u9648\u81f3\u7acb|script-title=zh:\u8f9e\u6d77\uff1a\u7b2c\u516d\u7248\u5f69\u56fe\u672c |trans-title=[[Cihai]] (Sixth Edition in Color) |date=September 2009|location=\u4e0a\u6d77. [[Shanghai]]|publisher=\u4e0a\u6d77\u8f9e\u4e66\u51fa\u7248\u793e. [[Shanghai Lexicographical Publishing House]].|isbn=9787532628599| language=zh|page=230| url=|quote={{lang|zh-hans|1929\u5e74\u7531\u4e8e\u9617\u53bf\uff08\u4eca\u4e8e\u7530\u53bf\uff09\u6790\u7f6e\u3002{...}\u519c\u4ea7\u6709\u5c0f\u9ea6\u3001\u7389\u7c73\u3001\u5c0f\u9ea6\u3001\u68c9\u82b1\u3001\u6cb9\u6599\u4f5c\u7269\u53ca\u751c\u74dc\u3001\u77f3\u69b4\u3001\u6838\u6843\u3001\u6843\u3001\u674f\u7b49\u3002\u755c\u4ea7\u4ee5\u9a6c\u3001\u725b\u3001\u7f8a\u4e3a\u4e3b\u3002\u5de5\u4e1a\u6709\u7535\u529b\u3001\u5efa\u6750\u3001\u8f67\u82b1\u3001\u98df\u54c1\u52a0\u5de5\uff08\u679c\u812f\uff09\u7b49\u3002}}}}</ref>\n\nIn the thirty years between the 1950s and 1980s, a significant area of farmland near the county seat was taken into the desert by blown sand.<ref>{{cite book|date=2001|chapter=The Control of Drift Sand on the Southern Fringe of the Taklamakan Desert \u2014 an Example from the Cele Oasis|authors=Ximing Zhang, Xiaoming Li, Henian Zhang|title=Sustainable Land Use in Deserts|page=350|doi=10.1007/978-3-642-59560-8_37|isbn=978-3-642-64027-8|quote=In the 30 years from the 1950s to the 1980s, shifting sand had moved about 5 km in the village of Cele located on the margin of the Cele county oasis, so that 1.333 ha farmland was desertified.}}</ref>\n\nSince the founding of Xinjiang Autonomous Region in 1955, Qira County has been part of Hotan Prefecture.<ref name=\"historyqira\">{{cite web|url=http://xjcl.gov.cn/zjcl/lsyg.htm|script-title=zh:\u5386\u53f2\u6cbf\u9769|language=zh-hans|accessdate=14 December 2019|website=\u0686\u0649\u0631\u0627 \u0646\u0627\u06be\u0649\u064a\u0649\u0633\u0649 \u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u4eba\u6c11\u653f\u5e9c|quote={{lang|zh-hans|\u6c11\u56fd17\u5e74(\u516c\u51431928\u5e74)2\u670823\u65e5\uff0c\u4e2d\u534e\u6c11\u56fd\u653f\u5e9c\u6279\u51c6\u5c06\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u4f50\u5347\u683c\u4e3a\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u6cbb\uff0c\u540c\u5e74\uff0c\u548c\u9617\u884c\u653f\u957f\u5b98\u5236\u6539\u4e3a\u548c\u7530\u884c\u653f\u957f\u5b98\u516c\u7f72\uff0c\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u96b6\u5c5e\u65b0\u7586\u7701\u548c\u9617\u884c\u653f\u957f\u5b98\u516c\u7f72\u7ba1\u8f96\u3002\u4e2d\u534e\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u56fd\u6210\u7acb\u521d\uff0c\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u96b6\u5c5e\u65b0\u7586\u7701\u548c\u9617\u884c\u653f\u516c\u7f72\uff1b1955\u5e7410\u67081\u65e5\uff0c\u65b0\u7586\u7ef4\u543e\u5c14\u81ea\u6cbb\u533a\u6210\u7acb\uff0c\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u96b6\u5c5e\u65b0\u7586\u7ef4\u543e\u5c14\u81ea\u6cbb\u533a\u548c\u7530\u5730\u533a\u3002}}}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1980s, 446 households living in the county seat were forced to relocate due to the effects of [[desertification]] which had brought the [[Taklamakan Desert]] within {{convert|1.5|km|mi}} km of their homes, sometimes burying homes in sand overnight.<ref name=\"chinadaily\">{{cite web|url=https://www.chinadaily.com.cn/life/2013-05/27/content_16536602.htm|title=Holding back the sands of time|date=27 May 2013|accessdate=15 December 2019|website=[[China Daily]]|quote=Qira county was once a kingdom on the ancient Silk Road in the days of the Eastern Han Dynasty (AD 25-220). The county seat has relocated north three times because the sands have eaten up the cultivatable land. The first relocation occurred more than 2,000 years ago and the most recent about 620 years ago. In the 1980s, the county seat faced yet another relocation because the desert was only about 1.5 km away. Many locals were forced to move because their houses were buried under sand, often overnight.{...}Memet Simay's household was one of 446 in Qira township forced to relocate in the 1980s, although the family has since returned to the area. \"When I woke up one morning, I found I couldn't open the door because of the weight of sand that had accumulated overnight. My crops were buried too, so I had no choice but to move,\" he recalled.}}</ref>\n{{quote|\"When I woke up one morning, I found I couldn't open the door because of the weight of sand that had accumulated overnight. My crops were buried too, so I had no choice but to move\" -Memet Simay, area resident<ref name=\"chinadaily\"/>}}\n\nIn 1983, the Qira research station of the [[Chinese Academy of Sciences]] was founded to combat drift sand.<ref name=\"landuse\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com.tw/books?id=EvfsCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA351&lpg=PA351|title=Sustainable Land Use in Deserts|page=351|via=[[Google Books]]|editors=Siegmar-W. Breckle, Maik Veste, Walter Wucherer|isbn=978-3-642-64027-8|last1=Breckle|first1=Siegmar-W|last2=Veste|first2=Maik|last3=Wucherer|first3=Walter|date=2012-12-06}}</ref> A transitional zone was established with help from the scientists at the station, and the sands were pushed back over {{convert|5|km|mi}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2013-09/16/content_16971364.htm|title=Scientists make land arable again|author=Cheng Yingqi|date=16 August 2013|accessdate=15 December 2019|publisher=[[China Daily]]}}</ref>{{better source|date=December 2019|reason=Could be true in some sense, but a report from the station confirming the particulars of these efforts and their confirmable effects and results is needed.}}\n\nIn 2005, a small 1,500 year-old [[Buddhist temple]] was discovered {{convert|7|km|mi|abbr=on}} from Damiku (Damagou).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/rest-of-world/Worlds-smallest-temple-discovered-in-China/articleshow/1282270.cms|title=World's smallest temple discovered in China|website=[[Times of India]]|date=2 November 2005|accessdate=16 December 2019|quote=The temple, dating back more than 1,500 years, was located about seven kilometres from the Damagou Township of Cele County.}}</ref>\n\nOn October 20, 2014, Damiku (Damagou) was changed from a township to a town.<ref name=\"xzqhqira\"/>\n\nOn January 7, 2016, areas near Nur, Bostan and Ulughsay townships in Qira County were made part of the newly-created [[Kunyu, Xinjiang|Kunyu]].<ref name=\"yimuchang\"/><ref name=\"xzqhky\"/>\n\nOn February 28, 2017, it was announced by the county government that those who reported others for stitching the '[[Star and crescent|star and crescent moon]]' insignia on their clothing or personal items or having the words '[[East Turkestan]]' on their mobile phone case, purse or other jewelry, would be eligible for cash payments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rfa.org/english/news/uyghur/searches-04042017172301.html|title=Xinjiang Police Search Uyghur Homes For 'Illegal Items'|website=[[Radio Free Asia]]|date=4 April 2017|accessdate=16 December 2019|quote=A second announcement, issued Feb. 28 by the Chira (Cele) county government, said those who report individuals for having \u201cstitched the \u2018star and crescent moon\u2019 insignia on their clothing or personal items\u201d or the words \u201cEast Turkestan\u201d\u2014referring to the name of a short-lived Uyghur republic\u2014on their mobile phone case, purse or other jewelry, were also eligible for cash payments.|translator=Mamatjan Juma|authors=Joshua Lipes, Jilil Kashgary}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017, Salamet Memetimin, the [[Communist Party of China|Communist Party]] secretary for Chaka township's Bekchan village and ethnic Uyghur, was relieved of her duties for taking her [[Marriage in Islam|nikah]] marriage vows at her home. According to the Hotan Daily, 97 officials were charged with disciplinary violations at this time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rfa.org/english/news/china/kazakh-imam-08092017121527.html|title='No Sign' of Kazakh Imam Scheduled For Release From Prison in July|website=[[Radio Free Asia]]|date=9 August 2017|accessdate=16 December 2019|quote=In March, Xinjiang authorities fired an ethnic Uyghur official for holding her wedding ceremony at home according to Islamic traditions instead of at a government-sanctioned venue. Salamet Memetimin, the communist party secretary for Chaka township\u2019s Bekchan village, in Hotan (in Chinese, Hetian) prefecture\u2019s Chira (Cele) county, was among 97 officials recently charged with disciplinary violations, according to an April 10 report by the state-run Hotan Daily newspaper. Local residents said the woman was relieved of her duties for taking her \"nikah\" marriage vows in her own home. \"I think this may be a local policy unique to Xinjiang,\" the source said. \"You have to first apply for a marriage certificate and then carry out the Islamic practice of nikah.\" \"The imams aren't allowed to perform nikah if there is no marriage certificate, or they will be sent to prison.\"}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, local government authorities in the county expected to have almost 12,000 detainees in [[Xinjiang re-education camps|vocational camps and detention centres]] and some projects related to the centres outstripped budgetary limits.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jan/11/if-you-enter-a-camp-you-never-come-out-inside-chinas-war-on-islam|title='If you enter a camp, you never come out': inside China's war on Islam|website=[[The Guardian]]|date=11 January 2019|accessdate=16 December 2019|language=zh-hans|author=Lily Kuo|quote=Some local governments are struggling to maintain this pace of spending. In neighbouring Cele county, where authorities expected to have almost 12,000 detainees in vocational camps and detention centres, a budget for 2018 says: \u201cThere are still many projects not included in the budget due to a lack of funds. The financial situation in 2018 is very severe.\u201d}}</ref>\n\nTo increase aid delivery to Xinjiang, places in Xinjiang are paired with other areas of China which can provide aid. [[Tianjin]] and Hotan are paired in this program. Through assistance from the Tianjin government, a standard football field and training center was constructed at the No. 1 Primary School in the county.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-07/08/c_138208976.htm|title=Tianjin helping Xinjiang's football development in China|date=8 July 2019|accessdate=16 December 2019|website=[[Xinhua News Agency]]|editor=Shi Yinglun|quote=Memet Azizi, director of Cele County's bureau of education, said that Tianjin's help had brought them hope for the future. With support from Tianjin, a standard football field and training center was constructed at Cele County's No. 1 Primary School.}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nThe northern part of Qira County is made up of sand dunes<ref name=\"qiranorth\"/> and ends in a straight line drawn in the [[Taklamakan Desert]] that forms part of the boundary between Hotan Prefecture and [[Aksu Prefecture]]. The area is between {{convert|1500|m|ft|abbr=on}} and {{convert|1800|m|ft|abbr=on}} above sea level.<ref name=\"govxjcl\"/>\n\nOasis areas occupy 2.9% of the total area of the county.<ref name=\"govxjcl\"/> The oasis areas along [[China National Highway 315]] include the Qira County county seat area, Gulahma and Damiku. Qaka, Ulughsay, Nur, Bostan and [[Kunyu, Xinjiang|Kunyu]]'s small exclaves in Qira County are located close to the Kunlun Mountains.<!--Basis: Google Maps-->\n\nThe southern part of Qira County is mountainous with an average elevation of {{convert|3200|m|ft|abbr=on}} above sea level.<ref name=\"govxjcl\"/> The upper reaches of the [[White Jade River]] (Yurung Kash), which provide water for [[Hotan|Hotan (Khotan)]], are found in the [[Kunlun Mountains]]<ref name=\"govxjcl\"/> of southern Qira County.<ref name=\"qirasouth\"/> Mountain passes in the area include Mandar Kol Dawan, Shalgon Dawan, Kuchkash Bulak Dawan, and Art Dawan.<ref name=\"qirasouth\"/> One of the prominent mountains in the county is Muztag<ref name=\"3rdedition\"/><ref name=\"GNISmuztag\">{{GEOnet2|32FA8826E5343774E0440003BA962ED3|Muztag   (Approved - N)}}, [[National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency|United States National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency]]</ref> (K5,<ref name=\"GNISK5\">{{GEOnet2|32FA8826E53A3774E0440003BA962ED3|K5 (Variant - V)}}, [[National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency|United States National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency]]</ref> Wu-lu-ko Ho Shan,<ref name=\"qiranorth\"/> Mo-shih Shan,<ref name=\"qiranorth\"/> Mu-shih Shan,<ref name=\"GNISmushihshan\">{{GEOnet2|32FA8826E5393774E0440003BA962ED3|Mu-shih Shan   (Variant - V)}}, [[National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency|United States National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency]]</ref> Muztagh Jilga;<ref name=\"qirasouth\"/> {{lang|zh|\u6155\u58eb\u5c71}},<ref name=\"GNISmushishan\">{{GEOnet2|AD4CEC26540D4485866711038E92B7DD|\u6155\u58eb\u5c71   (Non-Roman Script - NS)}}, [[National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency|United States National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency]]</ref> {{lang|zh|\u6728\u65af\u5c71}}<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/shijiedituji00ditu/page/66|script-title=zh:\u4e16\u754c\u5730\u56fe\u96c6|language=zh|date=1958|publisher=\u5730\u5716\u51fa\u7248\u793e|edition=1|id = [[:zh:\u7edf\u4e00\u4e66\u53f7|\u7edf\u4e00\u4e66\u53f7 (National Standard Book Number of China)]] 12014\u00b7449 |location= [[Beijing]]|page=66|quote=\u7b56\u52d2{...}\u6728\u65af\u5c71}}</ref>) which is {{convert|7282|m|ft|abbr=on}} above sea level.<ref name=\"3rdedition\"/> The [[meltwater]] from this mountain creates the Qira River (Cele River, Ts'e-lo Ho;<ref name=\"qiranorth\"/> {{lang|zh|\u7b56\u52d2\u6cb3}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sn.xinhuanet.com/2019-07/20/c_1124777517.htm|website=[[Xinhua News Agency]]|date=20 July 2019|accessdate=16 December 2019|language=zh-hans|script-title=zh:\u3010\u65b0\u7586\u662f\u4e2a\u597d\u5730\u65b9\u3011 \u201c\u98de\u2018\u9605\u2019\u65b0\u7586\u201d\u4e4b\u516b\uff1a\u6606\u4ed1\u5c71\u4e0b\u201c\u4e16\u5916\u6843\u6e90\u201d\u5367\u9f99\u8c37 \u6258\u8d77\u6751\u6c11\u81f4\u5bcc\u65b0\u5e0c\u671b|quote={{lang|zh-hans|\u5367\u9f99\u8c37\u4f4d\u4e8e\u65b0\u7586\u548c\u7530\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u6070\u54c8\u4e61\u7389\u5982\u514b\u5854\u4ec0\u6751\uff0c\u5728\u5b83\u7684\u6000\u62b1\u91cc\uff0c\u7b56\u52d2\u6cb3\u5e26\u7740\u8fd9\u91cc\u4eba\u7684\u559c\u6012\u54c0\u4e50\u60a0\u60a0\u5730\u6d41\u5411\u8fdc\u65b9\u3002}}}}</ref>) which flows through Qaka into the Qira county seat.<ref name=\"qiranorth\"/>\n\nIn the mid-20th century, camping grounds in the sparsely populated southern mountainous area of the county included Chotma, Yangi kan, Zaiuk, Yaskako Tagh, Mandar Chap, and Chumik.<ref name=\"qirasouth\">{{cite web|location=[[Washington, D. C.]]|url=http://legacy.lib.utexas.edu/maps/imw/txu-oclc-6654394-ni-44-3rd-ed.jpg|language=en|title=NI 44 Pangong Tso|date=1950|via=[[Perry\u2013Casta\u00f1eda Library Map Collection]]|publisher=[[Army Map Service]]|quote=Muztagh Jilga{...}Yurung Kash{...}Chotma (Camping ground){...}Yangi kan (Camping ground){...}Zaiuk (Camping ground){...}Yaskako Tagh (Camping ground){...}Mandar Chap (Camping ground){...}Chumik (Camping ground){...}Mandar Kol Dawan{...}Shalgon Dawan{...}Kuchkash Bulak Dawan{...}Art Dawan}}</ref>\n\n==Administrative divisions==\nQira County includes two [[Town (China)|towns]] and six [[Township (China)|townships]] and one other area:<ref name=\"govxjcl\">{{cite web|url=http://xjcl.gov.cn/zjcl/clgk.htm|script-title=zh:\u7b56\u52d2\u6982\u51b5|language=zh-hans|accessdate=14 December 2019|quote={{lang|zh-hans|\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u4f4d\u4e8e\u65b0\u7586\u6700\u5357\u7aef\uff0c\u5357\u6795\u6606\u4ed1\u5c71\u3001\u5317\u4e34\u5854\u514b\u62c9\u739b\u5e72\u5927\u6c99\u6f20\uff0c\u53bf\u57df\u603b\u9762\u79ef3.16\u4e07\u5e73\u65b9\u516c\u91cc\u3002\u5168\u53bf\u5730\u52bf\u603b\u4f53\u5357\u9ad8\u5317\u4f4e\uff0c\u5c71\u533a\u5e73\u5747\u6d77\u62d43200\u7c73\uff0c\u5e73\u539f\u533a\u6d77\u62d41500\u20141800\u7c73\u3002{...}\u53bf\u5883\u5185\u53ef\u4f9b\u4eba\u7c7b\u751f\u5b58\u7684\u7eff\u6d32\u9762\u79ef\u4ec5\u53602.9%\uff0c\u4e14\u88ab\u6c99\u6f20\u548c\u6208\u58c1\u5206\u5272\u5305\u56f4\u6210\u5927\u5c0f\u4e0d\u7b49\u768472\u5757\uff0c\u5386\u53f2\u4e0a\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u57ce\u56e0\u98ce\u6c99\u4fb5\u88ad\u4e09\u6b21\u88ab\u8feb\u642c\u8fc1\u3002\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u603b\u4eba\u53e316.8\u4e07\u4eba\uff0c\u7ef4\u543e\u5c14\u65cf\u5360\u603b\u4eba\u53e3\u768498%\u4ee5\u4e0a\u3002\u5168\u53bf\u8f966\u4e612\u95471\u8857\u9053\uff0c}}|website=\u0686\u0649\u0631\u0627 \u0646\u0627\u06be\u0649\u064a\u0649\u0633\u0649 \u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u4eba\u6c11\u653f\u5e9c}}</ref><ref name=\"xzqhqira\">{{cite web |url=http://www.xzqh.org/html/show/xj/22421.html|script-title=zh:\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u5386\u53f2\u6cbf\u9769 |trans-title=Qira County Historical Development |publisher=XZQH.org |date=2 December 2014 |language=zh-hans |accessdate=14 December 2019 |quote={{lang|zh-hans|2000\u5e74\u7b2c\u4e94\u6b21\u4eba\u53e3\u666e\u67e5\uff0c\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u5e38\u4f4f\u603b\u4eba\u53e3132139\u4eba\uff0c{...}2003\u5e74\uff0c\u5168\u53bf\u603b\u9762\u79ef31688.01\u5e73\u65b9\u5343\u7c73\uff0c{...}2010\u5e74\u7b2c\u516d\u6b21\u4eba\u53e3\u666e\u67e5\uff0c\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u5e38\u4f4f\u603b\u4eba\u53e3147050\u4eba\uff0c\u5176\u4e2d\uff1a\u7b56\u52d2\u954714562\u4eba\uff0c\u7b56\u52d2\u4e6131123\u4eba\uff0c\u56fa\u62c9\u54c8\u739b\u4e6126621\u4eba\uff0c\u8fbe\u739b\u6c9f\u4e6119250\u4eba\uff0c\u6070\u54c8\u4e6115010\u4eba\uff0c\u4e4c\u9c81\u514b\u8428\u4f9d\u4e614587\u4eba\uff0c\u5974\u5c14\u4e6111581\u4eba\uff0c\u535a\u65af\u5766\u4e616626\u4eba\uff0c\u8272\u65e5\u514b\u8857\u905315684\u4eba\uff0c\u5175\u56e2\u4e00\u7267\u573a2006\u4eba\u3002 2014\u5e7410\u670820\u65e5\uff0c\u81ea\u6cbb\u533a\u653f\u5e9c\uff08\u65b0\u653f\u51fd[2014]177\u53f7\uff09\u540c\u610f\u64a4\u9500\u56fa\u62c9\u5408\u739b\u4e61\uff0c\u8bbe\u7acb\u56fa\u62c9\u5408\u739b\u9547\u3002\u8c03\u6574\u540e\uff0c\u5168\u53bf\u8f962\u4e2a\u9547\u30016\u4e2a\u4e61\uff1a\u7b56\u52d2\u9547\u3001\u56fa\u62c9\u54c8\u739b\u9547\u3001\u7b56\u52d2\u4e61\u3001\u8fbe\u739b\u6c9f\u4e61\u3001\u6070\u54c8\u4e61\u3001\u4e4c\u9c81\u514b\u8428\u4f9d\u4e61\u3001\u5974\u5c14\u4e61\u3001\u535a\u65af\u5766\u4e61\u3002}}}}</ref><ref name=\"statsqira\">{{cite web |url=http://www.stats.gov.cn/tjsj/tjbz/tjyqhdmhcxhfdm/2018/65/32/653225.html |script-title=zh:2018\u5e74\u7edf\u8ba1\u7528\u533a\u5212\u4ee3\u7801\u548c\u57ce\u4e61\u5212\u5206\u4ee3\u7801\uff1a\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf |trans-title=2018 Statistical Area Numbers and Rural-Urban Area Numbers: Qira County |language=zh-hans |publisher=[[National Bureau of Statistics of the People's Republic of China]] |date=2018 |accessdate=15 December 2019 |quote={{lang|zh-hans|\u7edf\u8ba1\u7528\u533a\u5212\u4ee3\u7801 \u540d\u79f0 653225100000 \u7b56\u52d2\u9547 653225101000 \u56fa\u62c9\u5408\u739b\u9547 653225200000 \u7b56\u52d2\u4e61 653225202000 \u8fbe\u739b\u6c9f\u4e61 653225203000 \u6070\u54c8\u4e61 653225204000 \u4e4c\u9c81\u514b\u8428\u4f9d\u4e61 653225205000 \u5974\u5c14\u4e61 653225206000 \u535a\u65af\u5766\u4e61 653225500000 \u5175\u56e2\u4e00\u7267\u573a|}}}}</ref>\n\nTowns:\n*Qira<ref name=\"3rdedition\"/> (Cele, Chira; {{lang|ug|\u0686\u0649\u0631\u0627 \u0628\u0627\u0632\u0649\u0631\u0649}} / {{linktext|\u7b56\u52d2|\u9547}}), Gulahma (Gulahema, Gulakhma, Gulahama; {{lang|ug|\u06af\u06c7\u0644\u0627\u062e\u0645\u0627 \u0628\u0627\u0632\u0649\u0631\u0649}}<ref name=\"GNISgulahma\">{{GEOnet2|4079295DAF422317E0440003BA962ED3|\u06af\u06c7\u0644\u0627\u062e\u0645\u0627   (Variant Non-Roman Script - VS)}}, [[National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency|United States National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency]]</ref> / {{linktext|\u56fa\u62c9\u5408\u739b|\u9547}} ({{linktext|\u56fa\u62c9\u54c8\u739b|\u9547}}), formerly {{linktext|\u56fa\u62c9\u5408\u739b|\u4e61}})\n\nTownships:\n*Qira (Cele, Chira; {{lang|ug|\u0686\u0649\u0631\u0627 \u064a\u06d0\u0632\u0649\u0633\u0649}} / {{linktext|\u7b56\u52d2|\u4e61}}), Damiku (Damagou, Ta-mu-kou, Ha-lang-kou, Dumuka;<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.174923|title=The Pulse of Asia A Journey in Central Asia Illustrating the Geographic Basis of History|via=[[Internet Archive]]|publisher=[[Houghton Mifflin Company]]|author=Ellsworth Huntington|quote=We tried in vain to hire camles at Chira, and so went eastward a few miles to Dumuka, a neighboring village, to try again.|page=[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.174923/page/n239 171]|date=1907|author-link=Ellsworth Huntington}}</ref> {{lang|ug|\u062f\u0627\u0645\u0649\u0643\u06c7 \u064a\u06d0\u0632\u0649\u0633\u0649}}<ref name=\"GNISdamiku\">{{GEOnet2|4079295DAB222317E0440003BA962ED3|\u062f\u0627\u0645\u0649\u0643\u06c7   (Variant Non-Roman Script - VS)}}, [[National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency|United States National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency]]</ref> / {{linktext|\u8fbe\u739b\u6c9f|\u4e61}}), [[Qaka]]  (Qiaha, Chaqa, Ch'i-ko-erh, Ch'ia-ha; {{lang|ug|\u0686\u0627\u0642\u0627 \u064a\u06d0\u0632\u0649\u0633\u0649}}<ref name=\"GNISqaka\">{{GEOnet2|4079295DA9E22317E0440003BA962ED3|\u0686\u0627\u0642\u0627   (Variant Non-Roman Script - VS)}}, [[National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency|United States National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency]]</ref> / {{linktext|\u6070\u54c8|\u4e61}}), Ulughsay (Wulukesayi; {{lang|ug|\u0626\u06c7\u0644\u06c7\u063a\u0633\u0627\u064a \u064a\u06d0\u0632\u0649\u0633\u0649}} / {{linktext|\u4e4c\u9c81\u514b\u8428\u4f9d|\u4e61}}), Nur (Nu'er, Nuri; {{lang|ug|\u0646\u06c7\u0631\u0649 \u064a\u06d0\u0632\u0649\u0633\u0649}} / {{linktext|\u5974\u5c14|\u4e61}}), Bostan (Bositan; {{lang|ug|\u0628\u0648\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646 \u064a\u06d0\u0632\u0649\u0633\u0649}} / {{linktext|\u535a\u65af\u5766|\u4e61}})\n\nOther:\n* Regiment One Pasture ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5175\u56e2\u4e00\u7267\u573a}}) (part of [[Kunyu, Xinjiang|Kunyu]]<ref name=\"yimuchang\">{{cite web|url=http://www.xzqh.org/html/show/xj/37700.html|script-title=zh:\u6606\u7389\u5e02\u6982\u51b5\u5730\u56fe|language=zh-hans|date=24 February 2016|accessdate=15 December 2019|quote=\u8f964\u4e2a\u519c\u7267\u56e2\u573a\uff08\u76ae\u5c71\u519c\u573a\u3001\u4e00\u7267\u573a\u300147\u56e2\u3001224\u56e2\uff09\uff0c\u5176\u4e2d{...}\u4e00\u7267\u573a\u9a7b\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u3001}}</ref><ref name=\"xzqhky\">{{cite web|url=http://www.xzqh.org/html/show/xj/37699.html|script-title=zh:\u6606\u7389\u5e02\u5386\u53f2\u6cbf\u9769|date=24 February 2016|accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref>)\n\n==Economy==\nAgricultural products of the county include wheat, corn, cotton, petroleum products, melons, pomegranates, walnuts, peaches, and apricots. Livestock raised in the county include horses, cows and sheep. Industry in the country includes electronics, construction, cotton ginning and food processing (fruits).<ref name=\"cihai\"/>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Historical populations\n|type=China\n|percentages = pagr\n|2000|132139\n|2010|147050\n|footnote = <ref name=\"xzqhqira\"/>\n|}}\n\nAs of 2015, 163,705 of the 166,735 residents of the county were [[Uyghurs|Uyghur]], 2,921 were [[Han Chinese]] and 109 were from other ethnic groups.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.xjtj.gov.cn/sjcx/tjnj_3415/2016xjtjnj/rkjy/201707/t20170714_539450.html |language = zh-CN |script-title= zh:3-7 \u5404\u5730\u3001\u5dde\u3001\u5e02\u3001\u53bf(\u5e02)\u5206\u6c11\u65cf\u4eba\u53e3\u6570 |publisher= Xinjiang Uyghur Autonomous Region Bureau of Statistics |access-date= 2017-09-03 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171011101904/http://www.xjtj.gov.cn/sjcx/tjnj_3415/2016xjtjnj/rkjy/201707/t20170714_539450.html |archive-date= 2017-10-11 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAs of the 2010s<!--Rationale: Population figure for 2010 census (\"2010\u5e74\u7b2c\u516d\u6b21\u4eba\u53e3\u666e\u67e5\uff0c\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u5e38\u4f4f\u603b\u4eba\u53e3147050\u4eba\uff0c\") is less than the figure given in this sentence (\"\u7b56\u52d2\u53bf\u603b\u4eba\u53e316.8\u4e07\u4eba\uff0c\u7ef4\u543e\u5c14\u65cf\u5360\u603b\u4eba\u53e3\u768498%\u4ee5\u4e0a\u3002\"), so it seems likely that this percentage was from the 2010s.-->, the population of Qira County was more than 98% [[Uyghurs|Uyghur]].<ref name=\"govxjcl\"/>\n\n==Transportation==\n* [[China National Highway 315]] runs through the Qira County county seat, Gulahma and Damiku.\n\n==Notable persons==\n* [[Ismail Amat]]\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"160\">\nFile:Johnson-journey-ilchi1865-mapa.jpg|Map including Chira (1865)\nFile:China West 1906-08 Sven Hedin.jpg|Map of the expeditions of [[Sven Hedin]] (1906-8) including Qira (labeled as Chira) ([[Royal Geographical Society|RGS]], early 20th century)\nFile:Txu-oclc-6654394-nj-44-3rd-ed.jpg|Map including Qira (labeled as TS'E-LO (CHIRA BAZAR)) and surrounding region ([[U.S. Army Topographic Command|USATC]], 1971){{efn|From map: \"DELINEATION OF INTERNATIONAL BOUNDARIES MUST NOT BE CONSIDERED AUTHORITATIVE\".}}\nFile:Txu-oclc-6654394-ni-44-3rd-ed.jpg|Map including the southern part of Qira County and the county's border with Tibet ([[Army Map Service|AMS]], 1950){{efn|From map: \"THE DELINEATION OF INTERNATIONAL BOUNDARIES ON THIS MAP MUST NOT BE CONSIDERED AUTHORITATIVE.\"}}\nFile:Operational Navigation Chart G-7, 6th edition.jpg|From the Operational Navigation Chart; map including Qira (labeled as QIRA (TS'E-LE)) ([[Defense Mapping Agency|DMA]], 1980){{efn|From map: \"The representation of international boundaries is not necessarily authoritative.\"}}\nFile:Txu-pclmaps-oclc-22834566 g-7a.jpg|Map including Qira (labeled as QIRA (TS'E-LE)) ([[Defense Mapping Agency|DMA]], 1984){{efn|From map: \"The representation of international boundaries is not necessarily authoritative\"}}\nFile:CHANTOS TAKING MELONS TO MARKET IN THE OASIS OF CHIRA.jpg|Traders in early 20th century Qira (Chira)\nFile:Mural excavated at Dandan-Uiliq CD-4.jpg|Buddhist Mural from [[Dandan Oilik]]\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Commons category}}\n\n{{Xinjiang Administrative Divisions}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:County-level divisions of Xinjiang]]\n[[Category:Hotan Prefecture]]\n", "name_user": "Geographyinitiative", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDemographics", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Qira_County"}
{"title_page": "Andrew Burstein", "text_new": "{{Underlinked|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|American historian and Charles P|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n\n'''Andrew Burstein''' is an American historian and Charles P. Manship Professor of History at [[Louisiana State University]]. He was professor at  [[University of Northern Iowa]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/jefferson/archives/interviews/Burstein.htm|title=Andrew Burstein {{!}} Historian|last=|first=|date=|website=www.pbs.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref>\n\n== Works ==\n\n* ''Madison and Jefferson'' New York : Random House, 2013. {{ISBN|9780812979008}} \n* ''Problem of Democracy : The Presidents Adams Confront the Cult of Personality.'' Penguin Publishing Group, 2019. {{ISBN|9780525557500}}<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/22/books/review/nancy-isenberg-andrew-burstein-the-problem-of-democracy.html|title=Two Early Presidents Who Questioned the Wisdom of \u2018the People\u2019|last=Anderson|first=Virginia DeJohn|date=2019-04-22|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-01-10|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/Books/Book-Reviews/2019/0625/Two-early-presidents-raised-warnings-about-the-cult-of-personality|title=Two early presidents raised warnings about the cult of personality|date=2019-06-25|work=Christian Science Monitor|access-date=2020-01-10|issn=0882-7729}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2019/apr/13/john-quincy-adams-jefferson-jackson-trump-the-problem-of-democracy-extract|title=Adams family values: two presidents with a message for Trump's America|last=Isenberg|first=Nancy|date=2019-04-13|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-10|last2=Burstein|first2=Andrew|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/outlook/how-john-and-john-quincy-adams-predicted-the-age-of-trump/2019/05/03/a8663134-5f96-11e9-9ff2-abc984dc9eec_story.ht